These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity). This protein has antibacterial activities.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1b
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Hainantoxin-X-2
description: Reversibly blocks N-type calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B) in rat dorsal root ganglion cells. Elicits no toxic symptoms in either vertebrates or invertebrates during a period of 48 hours post-injection, when it was assayed in vivo by direct injection into mice and cockroaches (By similarity).

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hhn1c
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Delta-conotoxin GmVIA
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process. Injection of this peptide in the head region of garden snail induces retraction of the head and body into shell. This is followed by secretion of viscous green slime and a convulsive undulation into and out of the shell. No apparent biological activity was observed when a much greater dose of peptide was injected peritoneally into mice.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1f
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1e
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1d
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1c
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like alborhagin
description: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like alborhagin: induces platelet activation and glycoprotein VI (GP6)-dependent platelet aggregation. Induces ectodomain cleavage of GP6 by activating endogenous platelet metalloproteinases (probably ADAM10). Has fibrinogenolytic activity against the alpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA). Recognizes distinct binding sites as convulxin, since alborhagin has minimal effect on convulxin binding to GPVI-expressing cells.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like AAV1
description: Zinc metalloprotease-disintegrin AAV1: snake venom zinc metalloprotease that binds to the platelet collagen receptor glycoprotein VI (GP6) thus inhibiting collagen- and convulxin- (a GP6 agonist) induced platelet aggregation and the tyrosine phosphorylation of intracellular signaling proteins (LAT, SYK, p76SLP76, PIK3C, and PLCG2) that follows GP6 activation. Interestingly, blocks platelet aggregation but does not affect shape change. Also degrades the Aalpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA), followed by the Bbeta chain (FGB).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase alsophinase
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that has potent hemorrhagic activity, fibrinogenolytic activity on the alpha-subunit of human fibrinogen (FGA) in vitro and provokes necrosis in skin, muscle and lung tissues. May contribute to local edema and ecchymosis induced by venom. Hydrolyzes model substrate (beta-chain of insulin) at Ala(14)-Leu(15).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like daborhagin-M
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that possesses high hemorrhagic activity (minimum hemorrhagic dose, MHD=0.86 ug) when subcutaneously injected into mice. Has potent fibrinogenolytic activity on alpha-chain of fibrinogen (FGA). Hydrolyzes model substrate (beta-chain of insulin) at Ala(14)-Leu(15) and Tyr(16)-Leu(17) followed by His(10)-Leu(11) and Phe(24)-Phe(25).

name: Alpha-conotoxin LvIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin blocks alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 nAChR with high selectivity (IC(50)=8.67 nM (on rat) and 17.5 (on human)) (PubMed:24398291). Has also weaker activity on alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-2-beta-3 (CHRNA6/CHRNA3-CHRNB2-CHRNB3) (IC(50)=108 nM (on rat)), alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-4 (CHRNA6/CHRNA3-CHRNB4) (IC(50)=121 nM (on rat)), alpha-3-beta-4 (CHRNA3-CHRNB4) (IC(50)=148 nM (on rat)), and alpha-7/CHRNA7 nAChRs (IC(50)=3000 nM (on rat)) (PubMed:24398291). When tested on mouse with hot-plate tests, this toxin significantly increases the base pain threshold and shows analgesic effects (PubMed:26742048).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase that inhibits ADP- and collagen-induced human platelet aggregation. This inhibition is completely inhibited by abolition of catalytic activity in case of collagen as inducer and partially inhibited in case of ADP as inducer. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that displays local myotoxin and edema-inducing activities and is lethal by intraperitoneal injection.

name: Peptide Ctri9677
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Peptide Ctri10261
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg2a
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels of the subtype Kv4.1/KCND1 with high affinity and shows weak effects on Kv4.2/KCND2 and Kv2.1/KCNB1 subtypes. The toxin modifies the gating behavior of the channel and may interact with the S3-S4 extracellular loop.

name: Peptide Ctry2146
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Peptide Hp1478
description: Amphipathic peptide with antimicrobial activity.

name: Peptide Ctry2459
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Peptide Ctry2346
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Peptide Ctri9194
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Peptide Ctry2606
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Peptide Ctri9594
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Toxin Ts16
description: Blocks potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 21.1
description: Reversibly and voltage-independently blocks voltage-gated potassium channels rKv1.2/KCNA2 (73%) (IC(50)=196 nM), hKv1.3/KCNA3 (50%) (IC(50)=508 nM), Shaker IR (30%), rKv1.6/KCNA6 (22%) (at 0.5 uM). Interaction of Ts15 with Kv1.3/KCNA3 is stronger than its interaction with Kv1.2/KCNA2.

name: Hyaluronidase-Pk1a
description: Hydrolyzes high molecular weight hyaluronic acid to produce small oligosaccharides.

name: Cholecystoxin
description: Cholecystokinin-22: hypotensive neuropeptide that binds cholecystokinin receptor type A receptor (CCKAR).

name: Bradykinin-releasing enzyme KR-E-1
description: Bradykinin-releasing enzyme. Releases bradykinin from bovine HMW kininogen. Has anticoagulant activity. Increases permeability of capillaries by intradermal injection into rabbits.

name: Kappa-buthitoxin-Tt2b
description: Blocks potassium channels Shaker-IR (with inactivation domain removed) and hKv1.2/KCNA2.

name: Alpha-conotoxin AusIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This peptide has been experimentally synthesized as AusIA-globular and AusIA-ribbon. Both forms are active on neuronal nAChRs alpha-7/CHRNA7 (IC(50)=11.68 uM for AusIA-globular and 9.67 uM for AusIA-ribbon).

name: Delta/omega-plectoxin-Pt1a
description: Excitatory toxin that acts on both calcium and sodium (Nav) channels. It preferentially blocks a subset of calcium channels that is apparently not required for neurotransmitter release, it decreases threshold for sodium channel activation and it slows sodium channel inactivation. As it enhances synaptic transmission by prolonging presynaptic release of neurotransmitter, its effects on sodium and calcium channels may act synergistically to sustain the terminal excitability.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6.21
description: Blocker of voltage-gated potassium channels. Has highest activity on human voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.2/KCNA2 channels, with an IC(50) of 160 pM, whereas its affinity for other channels tested was in the nanomolar range (hKv1.1/KCNA1, IC(50)=253 nM; hKv1.3/KCNA3, IC(50)=91 nM; and hKCa3.1/KCNN4, IC(50)=70 nM).

name: Mu-scoloptoxin-Ssm6a
description: Gating-modifier toxin that inhibits voltage-gated sodium channel with a preference for hNav1.7/SCN9A (IC(50)=25.4 nM) over hNav1.1/SCN1A (IC(50)=4.1 uM), hNav1.2/SCN2A (IC(50)=813 nM), and hNav1.6/SCN8A (IC(50)=15.2 uM). Is an effective analgesic in rodent pain models, since it is several-fold more effective than morphine in a rodent model of formalin-induced pain and is equipotent with morphine in its ability to reduce thermal and acid-induced pain. In addition, this peptide shows a high level of resistance to proteases and a high thermal stability that may be explained by its predominant composition of alpha-helices.

name: Neurotoxin alpha-KTx 30.3
description: inhibits Kv1.3/KCNA3 channel.

name: Neurotoxin alpha-KTx 30.2
description: inhibits Kv1.3/KCNA3 channel.

name: Neurotoxin alpha-KTx 30.1
description: inhibits Kv1.3/KCNA3 channel (1 uM of the toxin inhibits currents by 64.1%).

name: Fulvonin
description: Inhibits angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) with a Ki of 1.2 uM, targets B1 bradykinin receptors (BDKRB1), and potentiates the smooth muscle contraction elicited by bradykinin. In vivo, induces hyperalgesic effects in living rats after intraplantar injection.

name: Omega-conotoxin RsXXVIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin inhibits rat Cav2.2/CACNA1B calcium channels in a dose-dependent manner with an EC(50) of 2.8 uM, whose effect is partially reversed after washing. In vivo, when injected into mice, it shows both an analgesic effect in acute thermal pain at 30 and 45 minutes post-injection and an anti-nociceptive effect in a formalin chronic pain test.

name: C-type lectin BPL
description: Galactose-binding protein which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. Calcium-dependent lectin. Shows high hemagglutinating activity in the presence of human erythrocytes, which are agglutinated with a minimum hemagglutination concentration (MHC) of 2.5-0.35 ug/ml. Causes indirect nephrotoxicity. Causes reductions in perfusion pressures, renal vascular resistance, urinary flow, glomerular filtration rate, sodium, potassium and chloride tubular transport. Its effects may be caused by the release of inflammatory mediators.

name: Ponericin-G5
description: Has antibacterial activity and non-hemolytic activities.

name: Phospholipase A2 3
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Venom prothrombin activator notecarin-D1
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This protein is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Qc1.1b
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Ponericin-G4
description: Has activity against some Gram-positive bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has a non-hemolytic activity.

name: Boigatoxin-A
description: This toxin may inhibit nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR). It has poorly reversible postsynaptic blocking activity in a chick muscle preparation and readily reversible inhibitory activity at a presynaptic site in the rat vas deferens prostatic segment most likely to prevent the release of neurotransmitters.

name: Ponericin-G3
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and non-hemolytic activities.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 ammodytoxin B
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that acts as a presynaptic neurotoxin, an inhibitor of blood coagulation, and has been found to bind with high affinity to intracellular proteins. The response of indirectly stimulated neuromuscular preparations to ammodytoxin (Atx) is triphasic. The first phase, the transient inhibition of the acetylcholine (ACh) release, starts soon after the addition of Atx and lasts for several minutes. This phase is probably independent of Atx enzymatic activity. The effect may be due to the specific binding of the toxin to presynaptic receptors. These receptors, called N-type receptors, are still unidentified. It is noteworthy that a neuronal isoform of the M-type PLA2 receptor (R180) has been identified as a high-affinity receptor for Atx in neuronal plasma membranes. It was demonstrated however that this receptor is not essential for expression of neurotoxicity by Atx. The second phase corresponds to an augmentation of neurotransmitter release. A peak is reached 10-20 min after exposure of the preparation to Atx and is followed by a gradual reduction. In this phase, the enzymatic activity of Atx of the mammalian is not significant. It is speculated that the increased release of neurotransmitter in this phase is induced by the interference of Atx with voltage-gated potassium channels. Measurements of ionic currents showed however that voltage-gated potassium channels are not affected by Atx. The third phase of the response of neuromuscular preparations to Atx, which corresponds to a complete and irreversible paralysis, is clearly dependent on the hydrolytic activity of the toxin. In addition to its presynaptic neurotoxicity, Atx shows an anticoagulant activity by binding with high affinity to activated coagulation factor X (F10) thus inhibiting the formation of the prothrombinase complex (FX/FV) and its activity (IC(50) is 82 nM). Surprisingly, Atx was discovered to bind intracellular proteins such as calmodulin (CaM), 14-3-3 proteins gamma (YWHAG) and epsilon (YWHAE) (by similarity with AtxC), as well as R25 (by similarity with AtxC), a mitochondrial integral membrane protein found in cerebral cortex. These findings raised a doubt about the dogma of the exclusively extracellular action of PLA2s, defended by the potential instability of these molecules in the reducing environment of the eukaryotic cytosol coupled with their possible inability to act as enzymes in this cellular compartment, due to too low concentration of calcium ions. This hypothesis was challenged efficiently by demonstrating the internalization of AtxA into a culture cells, but still remains to be directly demonstrated in vivo (By similarity). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Lipolysis-activating peptide 1-alpha chain
description: The heterodimer non-edited LVP1 induces lipolysis in rat adipocytes. Induction of lipolysis by LVP1 appears to be mediated through the beta-2 adrenergic receptor pathway (ADRB2) (By similarity).

name: Neutral phospholipase A2 agkistrodotoxin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 vipoxin B chain
description: Heterodimer: postsynaptic neurotoxin.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows anticoagulant and neurotoxic activities.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 3
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows anticoagulant and neurotoxic activities. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows anticoagulant and neurotoxic activities. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Snaclec salmorin subunit B
description: Inhibits thrombin-induced fibrinogen clotting and factor Xa-induced prothrombin activation. Binds to thrombin and prothrombin exosites.

name: Snaclec salmorin subunit A
description: Inhibits thrombin-induced fibrinogen clotting and factor Xa-induced prothrombin activation. Binds to thrombin and prothrombin exosites.

name: Potassium channel toxin AaTXK-beta
description: Potassium channel toxin AaTXK-beta: blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv) (By similarity). Does not activate Kv7 channels.

name: Alpha-conotoxin Lt14.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them (PubMed:16797781, PubMed:25617597). This synthetic peptide displays analgesic activity in a hot plate assay (PubMed:16797781, PubMed:25617597, PubMed:21126549). Analgesia is also observed against second phase pain in formalin-induced inflammatory pain model, and in a rat model of mechanically-induced pain (PubMed:25617597). Effects downstream of nAChR are inhibition of calcium influx, inhibition of ERK1/2 phosphorylation and inhibition of c-fos/NOS expression (PubMed:25617597). Genes associated with drug dependence are not up-regulated by this toxin (PubMed:25617597). Treatment with this toxin reversed morphine withdrawal symptoms in mice (PubMed:25617597).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Lt1.3
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Lt1.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Lt1.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Phospholipase D LapSicTox-alphaIB1aiv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin cal12b
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods (tested on squid giant-fiber-lobe neurons) with an inhibitor constant (Ki) of 15 nmol/l, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation. Has no effect on sodium channels of the two gastropod S.luhuanus and A.californica (which are not natural prey).

name: Phospholipase D LapSicTox-alphaIB1aiii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.1.1d
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIB1aii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 BITP01A
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that induces edema in mice, produces neuromuscular blockade in chick biventer cervicis, increases CK release and produces myonecrosis. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snake venom serine protease BITS01A
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BITM02A
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like BITM06A
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide F
description: This peptide potentiates the effect of bradykinin on the isolated guinea-pig ileum, does not potentiate the effects of bradykinin upon blood pressure and inhibits the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) from rat plasma.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 13a
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: Pantinin-2
description: Amphipathic peptide that possesses relatively strong activities against Gram-positive bacteria and a fungus, but has very weak antimicrobial activities against Gram-negative bacteria. Also exhibits mild hemolytic activities against human erythrocytes (16 uM induce 8% of hemolysis). Minimal inhibitory concentration (MIC) are the following: 48 uM against S.aureus, 36 uM against B.magaterium, 18 uM against M.luteus, 36 uM against vancomycin-resistant Enterococci, 28 uM against methicillin-resistant S.aureus, 48 uM against E.coli, >87 uM against P.putida, >87 uM against K.oxytoca, >87 uM against E.cloacae, 68 uM against S.enterica and 16 uM against the fungus C.tropicalis.

name: Phospholipase A2 1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Antimicrobial peptide TsAP-1
description: Has a low antimicrobial activity against S.aureus, E.coli, and C.albicans (MICs 120-160 uM). Has a low hemolytic activity (4% at 160 uM). Also inhibits the growth of two cancer cell lines (on a total of five).

name: Snake venom serine protease BPA
description: Snake venom serine protease that has a potent and selective fibrinogenolytic activity. Preferentially cleaves the alpha-chain (FGA) of human and rat fibrinogen and slowly digests the beta-chain (FGB). In vivo, completely avoids thrombus formation induced in rat, decreases the fibrinogen plasma level and prolonges the recalcification time. Possesses esterolytic and amidolytic activities.

name: Mastoparan-V2
description: Chemotactic peptide for polymorphonucleated leukocytes (PMNL), but causing no hemolysis to erythrocytes and no mast cell degranulation activity at physiological concentrations. Potent antimicrobial peptide against Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria (By similarity).

name: Mastoparan-V1
description: Chemotactic peptide for polymorphonucleated leukocytes (PMNL), but causing no hemolysis to erythrocytes and no mast cell degranulation activity at physiological concentrations. Potent antimicrobial peptide against Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria (By similarity).

name: Mastoparan
description: Potent antimicrobial peptide against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria (By similarity). This hemolytic peptide shows potent histamine releasing activities on rat peritoneal mast cells.

name: Mastoparan-1
description: Chemotactic peptide for polymorphonucleated leukocytes (PMNL), but causing no hemolysis to rat erythrocytes and no mast cell degranulation activity at physiological concentrations. Potent antimicrobial peptide against Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis CCT 2576 (MIC=4 ug/ml), and S.aureus ATCC 6538 (MIC=15 ug/ml) and Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=8 ug/ml) and P.aeruginosa ATCC 15422 (MIC=8 ug/ml).

name: Mastoparan-T
description: Chemotactic peptide for polymorphonucleated leukocytes (PMNL), but causing no hemolysis to erythrocytes and no mast cell degranulation activity at physiological concentrations. Potent antimicrobial peptide against Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria (By similarity).

name: Mastoparan-A
description: Chemotactic peptide for polymorphonucleated leukocytes (PMNL), but causing no hemolysis to erythrocytes and no mast cell degranulation activity at physiological concentrations. Potent antimicrobial peptide against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria (By similarity).

name: Cystatin
description: Inhibits various C1 cysteine proteases including cathepsin L, papain and cathepsin B. This protein has no toxic activity and its function in the venom is unknown. It may play a role as a housekeeping or regulatory protein (By similarity).

name: Cystatin
description: Inhibits various C1 cysteine proteases including cathepsin L, papain and cathepsin B. This protein has no toxic activity and its function in the venom is unknown. It may play a role as a housekeeping or regulatory protein (By similarity).

name: Cystatin
description: Inhibits various C1 cysteine proteases including cathepsin L, papain and cathepsin B. This protein has no toxic activity and its function in the venom is unknown. It may play a role as a housekeeping or regulatory protein (By similarity).

name: M-zodatoxin-Lt1a
description: Has antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacteria (A.globiformis VKM Ac-1112 (MIC=0.5 ug/ml), and B.subtilis VKM B-501 (MIC=1.0 ug/ml)), Gram-negative bacteria (E.coli DH5-alpha (MIC=1.0 ug/ml), E.coli MH1 (MIC=0.7 ug/ml), and P.aeruginosa PAO1 (MIC=4.1 ug/ml)), and yeasts (P.pastoris GS115 (MIC=17 ug/ml), and S.cerevisiae Y190 (MIC>33 ug/ml)). Has a moderate hemolytic activity against rabbit erythrocytes. Causes paralysis, but is not lethal when injected into insect (M.domestica) larvae.

name: Cystatin
description: Inhibits various C1 cysteine proteases including cathepsin L, papain and cathepsin B. This protein has no toxic activity and its function in the venom is unknown. It may play a role as a housekeeping or regulatory protein (By similarity).

name: Mauriporin
description: Amphipathic peptide that exerts potent selective cytotoxic and antiproliferative activity against three different prostate cancer cell lines (IC(50)=4.4-7.8 uM), compared to non-tumorigenic cells (IC(50)=59.7 in Vero and 62.5 in HUVEC cells). This peptide possibly exerts its cytotoxic activity through a necrotic mode of cell death.

name: Venom nerve growth factor 1
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Natriuretic peptide GNP1
description: Exhibits natriuretic and vasodepressor activity. Acts by stimulating cGMP (By similarity).

name: Snake venom serine proteinase 9
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: U17-barytoxin-Tl1a
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1f
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1e
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 S7-48J
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: U9-hexatoxin-Mg1a
description: No toxicity is observed upon intracranial injection into mice and intrathorax injection into crickets.

name: Putative antimicrobial peptide clone 6
description: Antibacterial peptide.

name: Anionic peptide clone 7
description: May be an antimicrobial peptide.

name: Probable antimicrobial peptide Con13
description: Hemolytic and antibacterial and antifungal peptide.

name: Anionic peptide clone 9
description: May be an antimicrobial peptide.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 4.5
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Putative antimicrobial peptide clone 4
description: Antibacterial peptide.

name: Putative antimicrobial peptide clone 5
description: Antibacterial peptide.

name: Toxin Tco-gamma
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor textilinin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits plasmin (Ki=2.2 nM), and reduces blood loss in the mouse tail vein blood loss model.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor textilinin-1
description: Strongly inhibits plasmin (Ki=0.44 nM) and trypsin (Ki=0.42 nM). Has little effect on plasma (Ki=1870 nM) and tissue (Ki=12900 nM) kallikreins. In vivo, reduces bleeding in a small animal model.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 1.5
description: Potent blocker of both large-conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa1.1/KCNMA1) and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv1.3/KCNA3).

name: C-type lectin Cal
description: Galactose-binding protein which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. Calcium-dependent lectin. Shows high hemagglutinating activity (MHC is 10 ng/ml) (PubMed:1989986).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 8.4
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Beta/kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg2a
description: Inhibits tetrodotoxin-resistant and tetrodotoxin-sensitive sodium channels (Nav) in rat dorsal root ganglion neurons. Highly inhibits Kv4.2/KCND2 and Kv4.3/KCND3 potassium channels and weakly inhibits Kv2.1/KCNB1 potassium channels. The toxin shifts the activation curves to more depolarized potentials. Also binds to phospholipid membranes.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like 3
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme batroxobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Cleaves Arg-Gly bonds in fibrinogen alpha chains (FGA).

name: Putative alpha-neurotoxin RjAa44
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Putative alpha-neurotoxin RjAa16
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Putative beta-neurotoxin RjAa7
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Turripeptide Lol142
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Birtoxin
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. Moderately toxic, but very high abundant. Does not target reptilian channels. Does not produce effect when administered to blowfly and cabbage looper larvae. In mice, produces convulsions, tremors, increased ventilation and, subsequently, death.

name: Kappa-conotoxin RIIIK
description: Kappa-conotoxins inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv). This synthetic toxin reversibly inhibits the insect potassium channel Shaker K+, the teleost homolog TSha1 and the mammalian Kv1.2/KCNA2 channel. Interacts with the pore region of the insect channel, in a state-dependent manner. Causes seizure when intracerebrovascularly injected into mice. Is also toxic when intrathecally injected into mice, but shows no visible effects by intraperitoneal injection. Shows protective effects on cardiac tissue when administered after an ischemic event.

name: Potassium channel toxin gamma-KTx 4.5
description: Reversibly blocks Kv11/ERG potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin gamma-KTx 4.4
description: Reversibly blocks Kv11/ERG potassium channels.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like Vc6.4
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels. Act on high voltage-activated (HVA) calcium currents in molluscan neurons (By similarity).

name: Hyaluronidase-4
description: Snake venom endo-hyaluronidase that degrades hyaluronan to smaller oligosaccharide fragments. In venom, it is not toxic by itself, but increases the diffusion of other venom proteins by degrading the extracellular matrix. In addition, it displays antiedematogenic activity (By similarity).

name: Hyaluronidase-3
description: Snake venom endo-hyaluronidase that degrades hyaluronan to smaller oligosaccharide fragments. In venom, it is not toxic by itself, but increases the diffusion of other venom proteins by degrading the extracellular matrix. In addition, it displays antiedematogenic activity (By similarity).

name: Hyaluronidase

In venom, it is not toxic by itself, but increases the diffusion of other venom proteins by degrading the extracellular matrix. In addition, it displays antiedematogenic activity (By similarity).

In venom, it is not toxic by itself, but increases the diffusion of other venom proteins by degrading the extracellular matrix. In addition, it displays antiedematogenic activity (By similarity).

name: Hyaluronidase-1
description: Snake venom endo-hyaluronidase that degrades hyaluronan to smaller oligosaccharide fragments. In venom, it is not toxic by itself, but increases the diffusion of other venom proteins by degrading the extracellular matrix. In addition, it displays antiedematogenic activity (By similarity).

name: Neurotoxin BtITx3
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity). Induces contraction, severe paralysis and death in insect larva of Helicoverpa armigera.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 19.1
description: Selective inhibitor of high conductance calcium-activated potassium channels KCa1.1/KCNMA1. May be insect specific.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 9.7
description: Calcium channel activator. Rapidly and reversibly activates ryanodine receptor 1 (RYR1).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 9.6
description: Calcium channel activator. Rapidly and reversibly activates ryanodine receptor 1 (RYR1).

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 1
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Disintegrin leucogastin-B
description: Inhibits ADP-induced human platelet aggregation.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein VAR3
description: Blocks ryanodine receptors, and potassium channels.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Conolysin-Mt1
description: This cytolytic peptide has ability to disrupt the integrity of cell membranes from both prokaryotes and eukaryotes. It permeabilizes both negatively charged prokaryotic (PE:PG) and zwitterionic eukaryotic (PC:cholesterol) model membranes. It has potent hemolytic activity on human erythrocytes and exhibits low antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacterium E.coli (MIC>50 uM) and the Gram-positive bacterium S.aureus (MIC=25-50 uM). Intracranial injection causes mice to shuffle backward until the encounter an obstacle, at which time the mouse jump into the air. The backward shuffle is reminiscent to the signature dance 'moonwalk' that gained widespread popularity after being performed by Michael Jackson.

name: Alpha-conotoxin PrXA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin inhibit both adult and fetal (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta and alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta subunits) mammalian muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR). Causes paralysis and death in mice and fish.

name: Mu-diguetoxin-Dc1c
description: Acts by delaying the inactivation of presynaptic voltage-sensitive sodium channels (Nav). Acts against insects and causes a progressive spastic paralysis.

name: Mu-diguetoxin-Dc1b
description: Acts by delaying the inactivation of presynaptic voltage-sensitive sodium channels (Nav). Acts against insects and cause a progressive spastic paralysis.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 CB2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows presynaptic neurotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 CB1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows presynaptic neurotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 Cll-N6
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows myotoxic activities. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A2 crotoxin basic chain 3
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows presynaptic neurotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1v
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U6-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 4
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 8
description: Ion channel inhibitor.
