Integrates into cell membranes and has multiple effects, probably, as a result of its interaction with negatively charged phospholipids. It inhibits well known transport pumps such as the Na(+)-K(+)-ATPase and the H(+)-K(+)-ATPase. Increases the permeability of cell membranes to ions, particularly Na(+) and indirectly Ca(2+), because of the Na(+)-Ca(2+)-exchange.

name: Cytotoxin 1c
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Conomarphin
description: May act as a neurotoxin.

name: Latartoxin-1b
description: Insect toxin.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1o
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1p
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Mu-agatoxin-Aa1e
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1n
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1m
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1l
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Venom prothrombin activator notanarin-D
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This protein is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog CTs-K49c
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that induces local edema a few hours after injection (5-10 ug) in the hind paw.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1q
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Latartoxin-2a
description: Insect toxin. Causes paralysis in larvae of C.vicina by depolarizing membranes at the neuromuscular junction.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase ACTX-8
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Its effect on platelets is controversial, since it either induces aggregation or inhibits agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity). Induces apoptosis in HeLa cervical cancer cells. Both the caspase-dependent and the mitochondrial pathways seem to be involved in apoptosis.

name: Disintegrin EC3A
description: Inhibits adhesion of cells expressing alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) and alpha-4/beta-7 (ITGA4/ITGB7) integrins to the natural ligands vascular cell adhesion molecule 1 (VCAM-1) and mucosal addressin cell adhesion molecule 1 (MADCAM-1). It is also a weaker inhibitor of alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) and alpha-2b/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) integrins. The inhibitory activity of EC3 towards alpha-4 integrins is associated with the MLD sequence of EC3B subunit. The ability of EC3 to inhibit ITGA5/ITGB1 resides in both subunits A and B.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like S6.6
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin blocks N-, P- and Q-type calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 13
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Aa2a
description: Binds to muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby potently impairing neuromuscular transmission. Pseudo-irreversibly inhibits the nAChR through competitive antagonism. In contrast to other long-chain alpha-neurotoxins, lacks affinity for neuronal alpha-7 nicotinic acetylcholine receptor.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor Bt-KTI
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits plasmin (Ki=2.01 nM) and trypsin. Acts as an antifibrinolytic agent.

name: Melectin
description: Antimicrobial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis (MIC=0.8 uM) and S.aureus (MIC=6.8 uM), and against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli (MIC=2.0 uM) and P.aeruginosa (MIC=18.5 uM). Stimulates degranulation from rat peritoneal mast cells with an EC(50) of 19.4 uM. Has very weak hemolytic activity towards rat erythrocytes.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase Ac1
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Phospholipase D LgRec1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces platelet aggregation in platelet rich plasma, but not in washed platelet, indicating that this activity is dependent on plasma components. Also induces hemolysis. In vivo, the recombinant protein evokes an intense inflammatory reaction and dermonecrosis, similar to those induced by L.gaucho total venom. Is a good immunogen, capable of inducing immunoprotection in test animals.

name: Peptide BmKn1
description: Antibacterial peptide.

name: Toxin BmKaIT1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). Shows a high toxicity toward insects and moderate toxicity against mammals.

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Asp2b
description: Potent inhibitor of insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Asp2a
description: Potent inhibitor of insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hi2a
description: Potent inhibitor of insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx34.2
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx64.1
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx19
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx15.1
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx21.1
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx30
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx35.2
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx35.1
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx11.6
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx11.1
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids (L-Tyr followed by L-Phe, L-Met, L-Leu, L-Trp), thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Inhibits ADP- and collagen-induced platelet aggregation. This inhibition is inhibited by catalase, indicating the importance of generated H(2)O(2) for the inhibitory effect. This effect on platelets among snake L-amino-acid oxidases is however controversial, since some of them induce aggregation, whereas the other inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. In vivo, this enzyme induces a rapid, substantial and reversible increase in the paw volume of mice (edema). In addition, myofibrosis, and inflammatory cell infiltration on the paw tissue are also observed.

name: Venom peptide 3
description: Exhibits strong antimicrobial activity against the fungi C.albicans and B.cinerea, and weaker activity against the Gram-negative bacterium E.coli and the Gram-positive bacterium S.aureus.

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-alphaI-Loxn-A
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity). Induces dermonecrosis, but is not lethal.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like 1
description: Inhibits the vertebrate voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 and Kv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Probable weak neurotoxin NNAM2I
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Orpotrin
description: Vasoconstrictor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1i
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Peptide Dq-1030
description: The synthetic peptide has no antimicrobial activity against strains of Gram-positive or Gram-negative bacteria, or against yeasts and other fungi.

name: Neurotoxin Hm-3
description: Inhibits mammalian and insect voltage-gated sodium channels. Shifts the voltage dependence of channel activation to more positive voltages. At a concentration of 1 uM, the toxin inhibits 90-100% of sodium current through Nav1.2/SCN2A, Nav1.4/SCN4A, Nav1.5/SCN5A, Nav1.6/SCN8A and Para/DmNav1 channels, when the voltage of maximal activation of the channel in control conditions is applied (Ref.1, PubMed:25352595). EC(50) are 1447 nM for Nav1.2, 103 nM for Nav1.4, 268 nM for Nav1.5, 3504 nM for Nav1.6 and 555 nM for Para/DmNav1 channel. It may bind to receptor site 4. The toxin is amphiphilic and binds to both neutral and negatively charged lipid vesicles with high affinity. The hydrophobic face lies on the opposite side to the hydrophobic faces of classical gating modifiers (PubMed:25352595).

name: Non-disulfide-bridged peptide 5.6
description: Has weak hemolytic activity and antibacterial activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria probably by forming pores in the cell membrane. It adopts an amphipathic alpha-helical structure.

name: Putative beta-neurotoxin
description: Causes transient paralysis of the rear legs of and spasms in insects (A.domestica).

name: Conotoxin di16a
description: Injection of the synthetic peptide causes a hyperexcitable phenotype in mice greater than three weeks of age at lower doses, and lethargy at higher doses.

name: Non-disulfide-bridged peptide 5.5
description: Has weak hemolytic activity and antibacterial activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria probably by forming pores in the cell membrane. It adopts an amphipathic alpha-helical structure.

name: Potassium channel toxin TstKMK
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Beta-mammal toxin Css2
description: Beta toxin. Both native and non-amidated recombinant forms of this protein bind in a voltage-independent fashion at site-4 of Nav1.6/SCN8A voltage-gated sodium channels. This binding shifts the voltage of activation towards more negative potentials which in turn affects sodium channel activation and promotes spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is only active against mammals. Binds to phospholipids.

name: Kappa-scoloptoxin-Ssm2f
description: Toxin that inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PL-Y
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that can cleave arachidonate at the sn-2 position from phospholipides in the micellar state or in bilayer membranes. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Short neurotoxin VAN-10
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin VAN-29
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 CbIalpha
description: Heterodimer: presynaptic neurotoxin.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like moojenin
description: Metalloproteinase moojenin: snake venom metalloproteinase that cleaves both alpha- and beta-chains of fibrinogen, but not the gamma-chain. Shows a coagulant activity on bovine plasma about 3.1 fold lower than crude venom. Renders the blood incoagulable when intraperitoneally administered into mice. Induces necrosis in liver and muscle, but does not cause histological alterations in mouse lungs, kidney or heart.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 22.1
description: May block potassium channels.

name: Snake venom serine protease gussurobin
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 CbII
description: Heterodimer: presynaptic neurotoxin.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 CbIbeta
description: Heterodimer: presynaptic neurotoxin.

name: Three-finger toxin W-IV
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Three finger toxin W-V
description: Three-finger toxin that binds and inhibits the muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR). The neuromuscular block is irreversible in chick biventer cervicis, but partially reversible in the rat diaphragm preparation.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PL-I
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey (By similarity). Exhibits hydrolytic activities, and prefers the anionic micelles (dPPC with deoxycholate) (793 umol/mg/min) to the zwitterionic micelles (dPPC with Triton X-100) (591 umol/mg/min). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Three-finger toxin W-III
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PL-II
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey (By similarity). Exhibits hydrolytic activities, and prefers the anionic micelles (dPPC with deoxycholate) (54 umol/mg/min) to the zwitterionic micelles (dPPC with Triton X-100) (15 umol/mg/min). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog mojave toxin acidic chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Postsynaptic neurotoxin.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Neurotoxin active on both insects and mammals.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Neurotoxin active on both insects and mammals.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hhn1d
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 3
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hhn1e
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Snaclec EMS16 subunit alpha
description: EMS16 is a potent and selective inhibitor of alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1) integrin and acts as a potent antagonist of platelet aggregation and cell migration. Binds specifically to the I domain of the alpha-2 subunit, in a metal ion-independent fashion.

name: Snaclec EMS16 subunit beta
description: EMS16 is a potent and selective inhibitor of alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1) integrin and acts as a potent antagonist of platelet aggregation and cell migration. Binds specifically to the I domain of the alpha-2 subunit, in a metal ion-independent fashion.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog beta-bungarotoxin B chain
description: Beta-bungarotoxin is a presynaptic neurotoxin of the venom. The B chain is homologous to venom basic protease inhibitors but has no protease inhibitor activity and is non-toxic.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snake venom serine protease
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Disintegrin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen (By similarity).

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase Bfon25
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase Bco22
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Snaclec Bfon18
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 Bfon11
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that impairs hemostasis. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Alpha-toxin BmalphaTx47
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin expressed with the pET-14b vector has low inhibitory activity on sodium channels (11.33% on rNav1.2/SCN2A, 15.96% on mNav1.4/SCN4A and 5.04% on hNav1.5/SCN5A). When expressed with the pET-28a vector, this toxin has higher inhibitory activities (44.12% on rNav1.2/SCN2A, 25.40% on mNav1.4/SCN4A and 65.34% on hNav1.5/SCN5A).

name: Insectotoxin-I3
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity).

name: Toxin PgKL2
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin inhibits cardiac sodium channels and voltage-gated T-type calcium channels (Cav3.3/CACNA1I) (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor tigerin-3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor nigrescinin-4
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor nigrescinin-3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor nigrescinin-6
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor nigrescinin-5
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor superbin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Toxin TdII-2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). This toxin is active against mammals and crustaceans.

name: Toxin TdII-3
description: Binds voltage-independently to sodium channels (Nav) and shifts the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials (By similarity). This toxin is active against mammals and also affects neuromuscular preparations of frog.

name: Toxin TdII-4
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). This toxin is active against mammals and also affects neuromuscular preparations of frog.

name: Toxin II.9
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials (By similarity). This toxin is active on crustaceans.

name: Beta-toxin Cn9
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Beta-mammal toxin Css4
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on mammals.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like BmMP
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that inhibits platelet aggregation and degrades fibrinogen.

name: Cytotoxin 2c
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 4a
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. name: Cytotoxin 1
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Short neurotoxin SNTX26
description: This three-finger toxin binds and inhibits the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Beta-cardiotoxin CTX9
description: Acts as a beta-blocker by binding to beta-1 and beta-2 adrenergic receptors (ADRB1 and ADRB2). It dose-dependently decreases the heart rate (bradycardia), whereas conventional cardiotoxins increases it. At 100 mg/kg, intraperitoneal injection into mice provokes labored breathing, impaired locomotion, lack of response to external stimuli, and death (after 30 min).

name: Beta-cardiotoxin CTX21
description: Acts as a beta-blocker by binding to beta-1 and beta-2 adrenergic receptors (ADRB1 and ADRB2). It dose-dependently decreases the heart rate (bradycardia), whereas conventional cardiotoxins increases it. At 100 mg/kg, intraperitoneal injection into mice provokes labored breathing, impaired locomotion, lack of response to external stimuli, and death (after 30 min).

name: Beta-cardiotoxin CTX23
description: Acts as a beta-blocker by binding to beta-1 and beta-2 adrenergic receptors (ADRB1 and ADRB2). It dose-dependently decreases the heart rate (bradycardia), whereas conventional cardiotoxins increases it. At 100 mg/kg, intraperitoneal injection into mice provokes labored breathing, impaired locomotion, lack of response to external stimuli, and death (after 30 min).

name: Beta-cardiotoxin CTX14
description: Acts as a beta-blocker by binding to beta-1 and beta-2 adrenergic receptors (ADRB1 and ADRB2). It dose-dependently decreases the heart rate (bradycardia), whereas conventional cardiotoxins increases it. At 100 mg/kg, intraperitoneal injection into mice provokes labored breathing, impaired locomotion, lack of response to external stimuli, and death (after 30 min).

name: Muscarinic toxin MTX6
description: Binds to the muscarinic acetylcholine receptor (CHRM).

name: Muscarinic toxin 38
description: Binds to the muscarinic acetylcholine receptor (CHRM).

name: Weak neurotoxin WNTX34
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme RP34
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that displays clotting activity on fibrinogen. Shows both arginine-ester hydrolase and amidase activities on synthetic substrates. Also shows proteolytic activity toward casein.

name: Alpha-conotoxin GIC
description: Alpha-conotoxins bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and inhibit them. This toxin reversibly blocks neuronal nAChRs (alpha-3/beta-2 = alpha-6 or -3/beta-2 or -3 > alpha-3/beta-4 = alpha-4/beta-2).

name: Met-lysine-1b
description: Shows no antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacterium B.subtilis B-501 or Gram-negative bacterium E.coli DH5-alpha at concentrations up to 20 ug/ml. Shows no toxicity towards insect (S.carnaria) larvae.

name: Cytoinsectotoxin-2a
description: Insecticidal and antimicrobial peptide. Has insecticidal activity against larvae of flesh fly S.carnaria. Has antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacterium B.subtilis B-501 (MIC=1.25 uM) and Gram-negative bacterium E.coli DH5alpha (MIC=2.5 uM).

name: Met-lysine-1a
description: Shows no antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacterium B.subtilis B-501 or Gram-negative bacterium E.coli DH5-alpha at concentrations up to 20 ug/ml. Shows no toxicity towards insect (S.carnaria) larvae.

name: Cytoinsectotoxin-4
description: Insecticidal and antimicrobial peptide. Has insecticidal activity against larvae of flesh fly S.carnaria. Has antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacterium B.subtilis B-501 (MIC=2.5 uM) and Gram-negative bacterium E.coli DH5alpha (MIC=10 uM).

name: Cytoinsectotoxin-3
description: Insecticidal and antimicrobial peptide. Has insecticidal activity against larvae of flesh fly S.carnaria. Has antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacterium B.subtilis B-501 (MIC=0.63 uM) and Gram-negative bacterium E.coli DH5alpha (MIC=2.5 uM).

name: Cytoinsectotoxin-2c
description: Insecticidal and antimicrobial peptide. Has insecticidal activity against larvae of flesh fly S.carnaria. Has antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacterium B.subtilis B-501 (MIC=1.25 uM) and Gram-negative bacterium E.coli DH5alpha (MIC=2.5 uM).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like atrase-B
description: Snake venom zinc protease that inhibits the classical and alternative pathways of complement by cleaving factor B, C6, C7, and C8. Also slowly and selectively degrades alpha-chain of fibrinogen (FGA), and shows edema-inducing activity.

name: A.superbus venom factor 1
description: Complement-activating protein in snake venom. It is a structural and functional analog of complement component C3b, the activated form of C3. It binds factor B (CFB), which is subsequently cleaved by factor D (CFD) to form the bimolecular complex AVF/Bb. AVF/Bb is a C3 convertase that cleaves complement component C3, but not C5 (as does CVF/Bb).

name: Crotamine
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism. As a cell-penetrating peptide, crotamine has high specificity for actively proliferating cells, and interacts inside the cell with subcellular and subnuclear structures, like vesicular compartments, chromosomes and centrioles. It penetrates into the cells as fast as five minutes after its addition to cell culture medium (PubMed:18662711). In vivo, after intraperitoneal administration, it is found in cells of peritoneal fluid and bone marrow, demonstrating preferential nuclear and perinuclear localization. To enter the cell, it interacts with the chains of heparan sulfate membrane proteoglycan (HSPG), and is endocytosed (in complex with HSPG) in vesicles which are transported into the cell with the help of clathrin. Inside the cell, crotamine accumulates in lysosomal vesicles. As soon as the peptide accumulates in endosomes/lysosomes vesicles, these compartments are disrupted and their contents released into the cytosol. This loss of lysosomal content induces cell death at high concentrations, or promotes the distribution of crotamine in cytoplasmic compartments, which is a step before crotamine nuclear uptake (PubMed:15231729, PubMed:17491023). As a potassium channel inhibitor, this toxin selectively inhibits Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2 and Kv1.3/KCNA3 channels with an IC(50) of 369, 386 and 287 nM, respectively (PubMed:22498659). The inhibition of Kv1.3/KCNA channels induced by this toxin occurs rapidly and is voltage-independent. The channel inhibition is reversible after washing, suggesting a pure and classical channel blockage effect, without effects in potassium channel kinetics (PubMed:22498659). As an antimicrobial peptide, crotamine shows antibacterial activity against E.coli and B.subtilis, and antifungal activity against Candida spp., Trichosporon spp. and C.neoformans. It kills bacteria through membrane permeabilization.

name: Snaclec lebecin subunit alpha
description: Inhibits the adhesion of MDA-MB231 human breast cancer cells to fibrinogen and fibronectin, MDA-MB231 cell migration, and the MDA-MB231 cell proliferation. This inhibition may be due to the binding to receptors of the integrin family, probably alpha-v/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) (40% inhibition of cell adhesion) and alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) (by comparison with lebectin).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2o
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Cytotoxic linear peptide IsCT
description: Cytotoxic linear peptide IsCT: shows weak hemolytic activity and antibacterial activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria probably by forming pores in the cell membrane. IsCT adopts an amphipathic alpha-helical structure.

name: C-type lectin 1
description: Lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Venom protein 13b
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide with hemolytic activity. Exhibits potent chemotactic activity for polymorphonucleated leukocytes (PMNL).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB1bi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6.15
description: Blocks rat voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2 and Kv1.3/KCNA3 expressed in Xenopus oocytes with IC(50) values of 13 nM, 16 nM and 2 nM respectively.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.13
description: Selective inhibitor of voltage-gated potassium channels, blocks the Kv1.2/KCNA2 (Kd=1.3 nM) and Kv1.3/KCNA3 (Kd=7.2 nM) channels. Association and dissociation rates of the toxin are slower for Kv1.2/KCNA2 than for Kv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Conotoxin ar11a
description: Both natural (L-Leu form) and synthetic (D-Leu from) peptides equally cause sensitivity to touch and body tremor. Neither L-Leu form nor D-Leu form is active on nerve-muscle preparation.

name: Oxiana weak toxin
description: Binds to nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Mu-conotoxin cal12a
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods (tested on squid giant-fiber-lobe neurons) with an inhibitor constant (Ki) of 15 nmol/l, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation. Has no effect on sodium channels of the two gastropod S.luhuanus and A.californica (which are not natural prey).

description: Gamma-conotoxins may act on voltage-gated non-specific cation pacemaker channels (HCN).

name: Snake venom serine protease BthaTL
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 9a
description: This peptide inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) by a preferential interaction with its C-domain. May also potentiate the hypotensive effects of bradykinin.

name: Crassipeptide cce9a
description: Crassispirid snail peptide that induces sleep-like symptoms in young mice (12 and 14 days) and hyperactivity in older mice (16 days), when intracranially injected.

name: Disintegrin leucogastin-A
description: Inhibits ADP-induced human platelet aggregation.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 2
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase bothrojaractivase
description: Prothrombin (F2) activator that is cofactor-independent. Also has fibrinolytic and fibrinogenolytic activity. It degrades the Aalpha-chain and more slowly the Bbeta-chain of fibrin and fibrinogen, while the gamma-chain is only partially and slowly affected. A dose-dependent procoagulant activity is shown in human plasma.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein natrin-1
description: Inhibits calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa1.1/KCNMA1), voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.3/KCNA3, and the calcium release channel/ryanodine receptor (RyR). Binds specifically to type 1 RyR (RyR1) from skeletal muscle. Inhibit both the binding of ryanodine to RyR1, and RyR1's calcium-channel activity. Inhibits carbachol-induced muscle contraction and weakly blocks muscle contraction evoked by potassium.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 5
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent.

name: Alpha-conotoxin Cp20.3
description: Alpha-D-conopeptides act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7 (IC(50)=0.25 nM), alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 (IC(50)=2.8 nM), and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 (IC(50)=28.6 nM) subtypes. Has no effect on alpha-3-beta-4/CHRNA3-CHRNB4, alpha-4-beta-4/CHRNA4-CHRNB4 and alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND subtypes of nAChRs.

name: Alpha-conotoxin Ms20.3
description: Alpha-D-conopeptides act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha7/CHRNA7 (IC(50)=0.12 nM), alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 (IC(50)=1.08 nM), and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 (IC(50)=4.5 nM) subtypes. Has no effect on alpha-3-beta-4/CHRNA3-CHRNB4, alpha-4-beta-4/CHRNA4-CHRNB4 and alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND subtypes of nAChRs.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein pseudechetoxin-like
description: Blocks olfactory (CNGA2) and retinal (CNGA1) CNG channel currents. Does not affect neither depolarization- nor caffeine-induced contraction of smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin lebein-1-alpha
description: Strongly inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation on human platelet-rich plasma. Also avidly binds to the laminin-binding beta-1 integrins (alpha-3/beta-1, alpha-6/beta-1, and alpha-7/beta-1) in an RGD-independent manner.

name: M-oxotoxin-Ot2c
description: Disrupts biological membranes, particularly those rich in phosphocholine. Has antimicrobial activity against Gram-negative bacterium E.coli, Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis and S.aureus, and hemolytic activity against sheep, pig and guinea pig red blood cells. Has insecticidal activity against S.frugiperda ovarian cells by opening non-selective ion channels. Enhances the insecticidal activity of spider venom neurotoxic peptides.

name: M-oxotoxin-Ot2d
description: Disrupts biological membranes, particularly those rich in phosphocholine. Has antimicrobial activity against Gram-negative bacterium E.coli, Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis and S.aureus, and hemolytic activity against sheep, pig and guinea pig red blood cells. Has insecticidal activity against S.frugiperda ovarian cells by opening non-selective ion channels. Enhances the insecticidal activity of spider venom neurotoxic peptides.

name: Delta-amaurobitoxin-Pl1a
description: Binds at site 4 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the fast inactivation of cockroach channels. This toxin is active only on insects. Has a potent activity against S.litura larvae.

name: Delta-amaurobitoxin-Pl1b
description: Insecticidal toxin. Lethal to lepidopteran larvae. No adverse affects when intracerebroventricularly injected in mice at a dose of 0.2 ug but causes reversible paralysis of legs when injected intracerebroventricularly in mice at a dose of 2.0 ug. Binds to site 4 of insect voltage-gated sodium channel (Nav) and inhibits channel inactivation.

name: Disintegrin lebein-1-beta
description: Strongly inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation on human platelet-rich plasma. Also avidly binds to the laminin-binding beta-1 integrins (alpha-3/beta-1, alpha-6/beta-1, and alpha-7/beta-1) in an RGD-independent manner.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase fibrolase
description: Has fibrino(geno)lytic activity on the alpha and beta chains of fibrinogen (FGA and FGB). Inhibits human ADP- and collagen-induced platelet aggregation on platelet-rich plasma but does not affect the thrombin-induced aggregation of rabbit washed platelets. Slightly degrades plasminogen.

name: Delta-amaurobitoxin-Pl1c
description: Binds at site 4 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the fast inactivation of cockroach channels. This toxin is active only on insects (By similarity). Has a potent activity against S.litura larvae.

name: Delta-amaurobitoxin-Pl1d
description: Binds at site 4 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the fast inactivation of cockroach channels. This toxin is active only on insects (By similarity) Has a potent activity against S.litura larvae.

name: Calglandulin
description: May be involved in the cellular control mechanism of the secretion of toxins from the gland into the venom.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 73
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 57
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme cerastobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease, that cleaves both alpha-chain (FGA) and beta-chain (FGB) of fibrinogen. Partially degrades factor X (F10), and release bradykinin from kininogen (KNG). Potently induces platelet aggregation. Shows a proteolytic activity towards protein constituents of the platelets cytoskeleton. Hydrolyzes actin, actin-binding protein, and P235.

name: Alpha-conotoxin PeIVA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin has higher affinity for the fetal (alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta subunits) subtype (IC(50)=<5 nM) of the receptor than for the adult (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) subtype (IC(50)=4000 nM). It blocks the elicited currents completely and dissociates very slowly from the fetal muscle receptor.

name: Cytotoxin 5
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Alpha-conotoxin RVIIIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin provokes a nearly complete and slowly reversible inhibition of both the human adult (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) and human fetal (alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta) neuromuscular nAChRs. It also reversibly blocks the neuromuscular alpha-7 nAChR, the alpha-3/beta-2 nAChR, the chimeric alpha-6 or -3/beta-3 or -2 nAChR and with a low potency the alpha-4/beta-2 nAChR.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like MIB
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like MIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ca1.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Cytotoxin 2
description: This protein lyses red blood cells, has cytotoxic activity and induces hypotension, but is not neurotoxic. In addition, it induces direct paralysis of the muscle fiber.

name: Cytotoxin 3
description: This protein lyses red blood cells and has cardiotoxic and hypotensive activities.

name: Alpha-conotoxin VxXXA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 (IC(50)=370 nM) and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes. VxXXB inhibits alpha-7/CHRNA7 and alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 nAChR subtypes with the highest efficiency, followed by VxXXA and VxXXC. VxXXB and VxXXC inhibit the alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 nAChR subtype more efficiently than VxXXA.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like S1.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 CH-E6'
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows high lipolytic and weak ADP-induced platelet aggregation activities. Also shows weak anticoagulant activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Neurotoxin Cex2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Cex3
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Cex1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Venom prothrombin activator porpharin-D
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This protein is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa (By similarity).

name: Venom prothrombin activator oscutarin-C non-catalytic subunit
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This non-catalytic subunit is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor V. It serves as a critical cofactor for the prothrombinase activity of the catalytic subunit, which is similar to the blood coagulation factor X.

name: Venom prothrombin activator omicarin-C non-catalytic subunit
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This non-catalytic subunit is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor V. It serves as a critical cofactor for the prothrombinase activity of the catalytic subunit, which is similar to the blood coagulation factor X (By similarity).

name: Venom prothrombin activator oscutarin-C catalytic subunit
description: Snake prothrombin (F2) activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This catalytic subunit is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa. For prothrombin activation, it requires a non-catalytic subunit present in the venom, which is similar to coagulation factor Va, to be fully active. In contrast to the 8 other snake venoms tested, this protein is the only one to also activate factor VII (F7). However, in contrast to prothrombin activation, the factor Va-like subunit is not essential for this activation.

name: Venom prothrombin activator omicarin-C catalytic subunit
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This catalytic subunit is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa. It requires a non-catalytic subunit present in the venom, which is similar to coagulation factor Va, to be fully active (By similarity).

name: Venom prothrombin activator notecarin-D2
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This protein is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 S16-19
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 S12-65J
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Nicotinic acetylcholine receptor-binding protein Mnn-4
description: Binds and may inhibit nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR).

name: Nicotinic acetylcholine receptor-binding protein Mnn-3C
description: Binds and may inhibit nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 S17-58
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like VMP-III
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Conotoxin Vc6.11
description: Inhibits voltage-gated ion channels.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like botrocetin
description: Metalloproteinase that binds to von Willebrand factor (VWF) and induces its interaction with GPIb (GP1BA), resulting in platelet aggregation.

name: Snaclec botrocetin subunit alpha
description: Snaclec that binds to von Willebrand factor (VWF) and induces its interaction with GPIbalpha (GP1BA) (via the vWF A1 domain), resulting in platelet aggregation.
