description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Conotoxin Vc6.9
description: Inhibits voltage-gated ion channels.

name: Disintegrin VLO5B
description: Poor inhibitor of platelet aggregation. The disintegrin inhibits the adhesion of the alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) integrin to VCAM-1. Inhibition on alpha-2b/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) is low.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase homolog-disintegrin albolatin
description: The function of this complete protein has not been studied, but it may be similar to the function of the disintegrin domain. A recombinant protein of this domain (409-484) inhibits collagen-induced human platelet aggregation, without having effect on ADP-induced aggregation. It may act either by blocking the binding of fibrinogen to the platelet receptor GPIIb/GPIIIa (ITGA2B/ITGB3) or by blocking the binding of collagen to the integrin alpha-2/beta-1 complex (ITGA2/ITGB1).

name: Disintegrin schistatin-like subunit B
description: May bind to both alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) and alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) integrins, and may inhibit platelet aggregation.

name: Disintegrin schistatin-like subunit A
description: May bind to both alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) and alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) integrins, and may inhibit platelet aggregation.

name: Toxin TdNa7
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin TdNa1
description: Inhibits the sodium (Nav) currents in an apparent irreversible manner. Produces small depolarization and induces repetitive firing in squid axons. Is specific for arthropods (crickets, triatomides, crabs and squids), but is non-toxic to mice (By similarity).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide
description: Antimicrobial peptide (By similarity). May also inhibit angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and potentiate bradykinin (BK).

name: C-type lectin APL
description: Beta-galactoside lectin that agglutinates rabbit and human erythrocytes in a calcium-dependent fashion (MHC is 0.21 ug/ml on rabbit erythrocytes). Galactose (15 mM), lactose (20 mM), rhamnose (20 mM) and EGTA strongly inhibit this activity.

name: Ectatomin subunit B
description: Algogenic for animals, human and insects. Pore-forming protein that forms nonselective cation channels both in cell and artificial membranes. Weakly selective for cation over anions channel conductance is identical in both directions.

name: Ectatomin subunit A
description: Algogenic for animals, human and insects. Pore-forming protein that forms nonselective cation channels both in cell and artificial membranes. Weakly selective for cation over anions channel conductance is identical in both directions.

name: Crotamine-IV-3
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, and hind limb paralysis (By similarity). It also induces potent blockade of neuromuscular transmission in young chicken biventer cervicis preparation and potent myotoxic effect. In mice, it induces myonecrosis, upon intramuscular or subcutaneous injections.

name: Crotamine-IV-2
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, and hind limb paralysis (By similarity). It also induces potent blockade of neuromuscular transmission in young chicken biventer cervicis preparation and potent myotoxic effect. In mice, it induces myonecrosis, upon intramuscular or subcutaneous injections.

name: Snaclec alboaggregin-D subunit alpha
description: Snaclec that induces human platelet aggregation in the absence of any cofactor with the EC(50) of 0.25 nM and causes tyrosine phosphorylation in human platelets. Antibodies against either platelet GPIbalpha (GP1BA) or GPVI (GP6) inhibit alboaggregin D-induced platelet aggregation. Only the combination of these two antibodies completely inhibit aggregation, suggesting that it acts through both GPIbalpha (GP1BA) and GPVI (GP6).

name: Snaclec alboaggregin-D subunit beta
description: Snaclec that induces human platelet aggregation in the absence of any cofactor with the EC(50) of 0.25 nM and causes tyrosine phosphorylation in human platelets. Antibodies against either platelet GPIbalpha (GP1BA) or GPVI (GP6) inhibit alboaggregin D-induced platelet aggregation. Only the combination of these two antibodies completely inhibit aggregation, suggesting that it acts through both GPIbalpha (GP1BA) and GPVI (GP6).

name: Crotamine CRO1
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor conotoxin Cal9.1c
Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor conotoxin Cal9.1d
Conotoxin Vc6.7
description: Inhibits voltage-gated ion channels.

name: Con-Ins G2b
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase HT-2
description: This protein is a zinc protease from snake venom that induces hemorrhage.

name: Non-toxic venom protein
description: Does not cause intoxication, paralysis or death in insects (A.domestica).

name: Venom protein
description: Causes mild intoxication and transient paralysis in insects (A.domestica).

name: Con-Ins F2
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BmooMPalpha-I
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that cleaves the alpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA) first followed by the beta chain (FGB) and shows no effect on the gamma chain. Cleaves only the beta chain of fibrin, leaving the gamma-dimer untouched. Shows proteolytic activity towards azocasein. Causes defibrinogenation when intraperitoneally administered on mice.

name: Antimicrobial peptide AcrAP2
description: Has antimicrobial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus (MIC=8 uM) and the yeast C.albicans (MIC=16 uM). Causes hemolysis on horse erythrocytes (64 uM for 100% hemolysis). Minimum bactericidal concentrations have also been tested against S.aureus and is four-fold higher (MBC=32 uM).

name: Potassium channel blocker alpha-KTx 26.1
description: Recombinant toxin that reversibly inhibits the potassium current of mKv1.3/KCNA3 channel stably expressed in COS7 cells (IC(50)=150 nM).

name: Con-Ins G3b
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. It is the smallest known insulin found in nature and lacks the C-terminal segment of the B chain that, in human insulin, mediates engagement of the insulin receptor and assembly of the hormone's hexameric storage form. Despite lacking this segment, it both binds and activates human insulin receptor (B isoform) with only a 10-fold reduced potency. In vivo, intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In addition, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 14.x
description: Potassium channels inhibitor.

name: Alpha-conotoxin CnIC
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Mn1.4
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Br1.4
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Pu1.4
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Pu1.5
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor stephenin-1
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Antimicrobial peptide 2
description: Has antibacterial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus (MIC=48 uM), the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli (MIC=120 uM), and the yeast C.albicans (MIC=64 uM). Causes hemolysis on horse erythrocytes.

name: Antimicrobial peptide 1
description: Has antibacterial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus (MIC=20 uM), the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli (MIC=150 uM), and the yeast C.albicans (MIC=64 uM). Causes hemolysis on horse erythrocytes.

name: Insulin-like peptide-1
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor
description: This protein inhibits trypsin and kallikrein.

name: Hainantoxin-XVIII-5
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1f
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1e
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 18
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 17
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1i
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like VAP2A
description: Heterodimeric zinc metalloprotease VAP2 that induces apoptosis in endothelial cells, without triggering cell detachment.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1g
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 19
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase fibrolase
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that exhibits direct fibrinolytic activity.

name: Cystatin-2
description: Inhibits various C1 cysteine proteases including cathepsin L, papain and cathepsin B. This protein has no toxic activity and its function in the venom is unknown. It may play a role as housekeeping or regulatory protein (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin SmIIIA
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). This toxin blocks rNav1.5/SCN5A (IC(50) is 1.3 uM), rNav1.6/SCN8A (IC(50) is 160 nM), rNav1.7/SCN9A (IC(50) is 1.3 uM), rNav1.1/SCN1A (K(d) is 3.8 nM), rNav1.2/SCN2A (K(d) is 1.3 nM), rNav1.4/SCN4A (K(d) is 0.22 nM), rNav1.6/SCN8A (K(d) is 69 nM), and rNav1.7/SCN9A (K(d) is 260 nM). This toxin is very potent but weakly discriminating among sodium channels. The block of these channels is modified when beta-subunits are coexpressed with alpha subunits. Hence, blocks of channels containing beta-1 and beta-3 subunits are more potent (compared to channels without beta subunits), whereas blocks of channels containing beta-2 and beta-4 subunits are less potent (compared to channels without beta subunits).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 15.3
description: Blocker of A-type voltage-gated potassium channels of striated neurons (PubMed:12473099). Has been shown to block ERG1/Kv11.1/KCNH2 potassium channels (IC(50)=7.9 uM) (PubMed:18687312). In adult rat brain, it binds to sites in the striatum, and cerebellum. It shares the same target in rat brain than AaTX1 (AC Q867F4) and BmTX3 (AC Q8I0L5).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 9.4
description: Blocker of human potassium channel Kv1.1/KCNA1.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like daborhagin-K
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that possesses high hemorrhagic activity (minimum hemorrhagic dose (MHD)=0.82 ug) when subcutaneously injected into mice. May also potently degrade alpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA).

name: Sigma-conotoxin GVIIIA
description: Sigma-conotoxins bind and inhibit serotonin-gated ion channels. This peptide selectively and reversibly inhibits 5-hydroxytryptamine 3 receptor (HTR3A) through competitive antagonism.

name: Mu-conotoxin PIIIA
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). This toxin potently blocks rNav1.4/SCN4A. It also moderately blocks rNav1.1/SCN1A, rNav1.2/SCN2A, rNav1.3/SCN3A, mNav1.6/SCN8A, and h/rNav1.7/SCN9A. This inhibition is reversible. The block of SCN1A, SCN2A, and SCN8A is modified when beta-subunits are coexpressed with alpha subunits. Hence, blocks of channels containing the beta-1 and beta-3 subunits are more potent (compared to channels without beta subunits), whereas blocks of channels containing the beta-2 and beta-4 are less potent (compared to channels without beta subunits). This peptide causes flaccid paralysis in both mice and fish.

name: Mu-conotoxin PnIVA
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Blocks reversibly sodium channels in molluskan neurons, but has no effect on sodium currents in bovine chromaffin cells or in rat brain synaptosomes. Induces paralysis in bivalve mollusks (Mytilus). No effect are observed on fish (Gambusia) and fly larvae (Sarcophaga). PnIVB is approximately 6 times more potent than PnIVA in blockade of the sodium current in Lymnaea neurons.

name: Mu-conotoxin PnIVB
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Blocks reversibly sodium channels in molluskan neurons, but has no effect on sodium currents in bovine chromaffin cells or in rat brain synaptosomes. Induces paralysis in bivalve mollusks (Mytilus). No effect are observed on fish (Gambusia) and fly larvae (Sarcophaga). Is approximately 6 times more potent than PnIVA in blockade of the sodium current in Lymnaea neurons.

name: Omega-conotoxin CVID
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels. This toxin inhibits neurotransmitter release, it blocks N-type calcium channels, probably a N-type (Cav2.2/CACNA1B) calcium channel variant.

name: Conotoxin TVIIA
description: By structural similarity with conotoxin GS, may inhibit the sodium channel (Nav). No effect was observed upon intracranial injections into mice and intraperitoneal injections into goldfish (25 ug).

name: Conotoxin CcTx
description: May specifically activate neuronal voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) at the resting membrane potential. Causes a marked contraction and extension of the caudal and dorsal fins in fish and noticeable spontaneous contractions of isolated frog neuromuscular preparations.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit B
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit A
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Dendrotoxin B
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv). This is the slowly inactivating phase of potassium efflux which is blocked by this toxin.

name: Dendrotoxin A
description: Inhibits acetylcholinesterase (By similarity). Has been described to inhibit both the slowly and the rapidly inactivating phases of potassium efflux (PubMed:1304870).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that exhibits an indirect hemolytic activity, a low myotoxicity, and induces edema. In addition, this enzyme has been shown to induce the release of some pro- and anti-inflammatory cytokines from human PBMC (IL12B, TNF-alpha, IL1B and IL6 but not variation has been observed for IL-8 and IL-10). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Nigwaprin-b
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Venom prothrombin activator trocarin-D
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This protein is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa. Induces cyanosis and death in mice at 1 mg/kg body weight during blood clotting.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1h
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits both serine proteases and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein 1
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Thaicobrin
description: Neurotoxin.

name: Toxin-like peptide AaF1CA26
description: Probable neurotoxin that inhibits ion channels.

name: Beta-toxin KAaH2
description: Weakly inhibits the vertebrate potassium channel Kv1.1/KCNA1.

name: Beta-insect toxin AaBTxL1
description: Shifts the voltage of activation of para/tipE voltage-dependent sodium channels (Nav) toward more negative potentials.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.2
description: Potent inhibitor of voltage-gated potassium channels such as Kv1.1/KCNA1 (IC(50)=0.144 nM), Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=0.675 nM), Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=0.23 nM) and Shaker (Kd=160 nM).

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Putative protein-glutamate O-methyltransferase
description: Putative O-methyltransferase that methylates glutamate residues of target proteins to form gamma-glutamyl methyl ester residues.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Ba1b
description: Inhibits voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav) in rat cerebellar granule cells (By similarity). Has insecticidal activity (Ref.1).

name: Mu-thomitoxin-Hme1a
description: Blocks the Nav1.2/SCN2A, Nav1.4/SCN4A, and Nav1.6/SCN8A sodium channels. Reduces the peak amplitude of the sodium current and negatively shifts the steady-state inactivation process. Does not shift the threshold potential of activation or the voltage corresponding to maximal current. Does not change the reversal potential of the sodium current. May act on site 1 of the receptor.

name: Mu-thomitoxin-Hme1b
description: Blocks the Nav1.2/SCN2A, Nav1.4/SCN4A, Nav1.5/SCN5A and Nav1.6/SCN8A sodium channels. Shows a slight preference for the Nav1.2 and Nav1.4 channels. Reduces the peak amplitude of the sodium current and negatively shifts the steady-state inactivation process. Does not shift the threshold potential of activation or the voltage corresponding to maximal current. Does not change the reversal potential of the sodium current. May act on site 1 of the receptor.

name: Delta-theraphotoxin-Hm1a
description: Gating modifier toxin that principally inhibits inactivation of the mammalian voltage-gated sodium channel Nav1.1/SCN1A. When tested against human Nav1.1/SCN1A-Nav1.8/SCN10A alpha subunits heterologously expressed in Xenopus oocytes, the toxin inhibits inactivation of Nav1.1 (EC(50)=38 nM), with substantially weaker effects on Nav1.2/SCN2A (EC(50)=236 nM) and Nav1.3/SCN3A (EC(50)=220 nM). The toxin inhibits several subtypes of voltage-gated potassium channels with significantly lower potency than its effects on Nav1.1/SCN1A (PubMed:27281198). It is a moderately potent blocker of Kv2.1/KCNB1, Kv2.2/KCNB2, Kv4.1/KCND1, Kv4.2/KCND2 and Kv4.3/KCND3 and has little effect on Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, Kv1.3/KCNA3, Kv1.4/KCNA4, Kv1.5/KCNA5, Kv1.6/KCNA6 and Kv3.4/KCNC4 (PubMed:12065754). The binding affinity and subtype selectivity of the toxin is determined by residues within both the S1-S2 and S3-S4 loops of the domain IV voltage sensor (PubMed:27281198). Intracerebroventricular injection into mice elicits convulsions, spasms, tremors and rapid death (PubMed:12065754). When injected into mouse hindpaw, the toxin elicits an immediate and robust response to pain (PubMed:27281198). Intraplantar injection of toxin does not cause neurogenic inflammation or alter sensitivity to heat, indicative of a modality-specific effect on mechanosensitive neurons (PubMed:27281198).

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Hm2a
description: Inhibitor of voltage-gated potassium channels. It specifically inhibits Kv2.1/KCNB1 channels.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Sc1a
description: Acts as a gating-modifier to inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels. It inhibits delayed Kv2.1/KCNB1 (IC(50) is 12.7 nM), Kv2.1/Kv9.3 (IC(50) is 7.2 nM) (KCNB1/KCNS3), Kv2.2/KCNB2 (IC(50) is 21.4 nM), and transient Kv4.2/KCND2 (IC(50) is 1.2 nM) channels.

name: Phospholipase D LspaSicTox-alphaIA2iv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin tergeminin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA1ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA1iii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.2a
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspaSicTox-alphaIA1i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin eristicophin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Disintegrin barbourin
description: Inhibitor of ligand binding to the integrins alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3). Competition with fibrinogen for the RGD recognition sites on the alpha-IIb/beta-3 integrin results in the inhibition of platelet aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1h
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: OcyC3
description: Amphipathic peptide with probable antimicrobial activity.

name: Toxin Tb2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active on mammals (By similarity).

name: Toxin Tb3
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). Is lethal to mice (PubMed:8611151).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 VRV-PL-V
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has a low enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Neurotoxin-like protein STR1
description: This protein is not toxic.

name: U2-ctenitoxin-Pr1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: Vascular endothelial growth factor A
description: Growth factor active in angiogenesis, vasculogenesis and endothelial cell growth. Induces endothelial cell proliferation, promotes cell migration, inhibits apoptosis and induces permeabilization of blood vessels. Binds to heparan sulfate and heparin.

name: Delta-ctenitoxin-Pr2d
description: Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Causes rapid general spastic paralysis and death when injected in mice at dose levels of less than 2 ug per mouse.

name: U2-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: U8-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: No toxic effects on mice at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse. May be toxic to insects.

name: U1-ctenitoxin-Pr1a
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). Causes rapid general flaccid paralysis followed by death in 10-30 minutes when injected in mice at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse.

name: U8-ctenitoxin-Pr1a
description: No toxic effects on mice at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse. May be toxic to insects.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor scutellin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor scutellin-1
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor microlepidin-1
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor tigerin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor tigerin-1
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor carinatin-1
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor mulgin-4
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor mulgin-3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme bilineobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that has coagulant activity by releasing fibrinopeptides A and B from fibrinogen alpha (FGA) and beta (FGB), with a preference for beta chain.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 14.5
description: Inhibits potassium channels. May be active towards small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCNN, SK), and less active towards voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv/KCN).

name: Toxin BmCa-1
description: Putative ryanodine receptor inhibitor (RYR). May also inhibits potassium channels.

name: Phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-, ADP-, thrombin-, ionophore-, adrenaline-, ristocetin-, and arachidonic acid-induced platelet aggregation. Inhibits serotonin release. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2 superbin a
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. In terms of inhibition of platelet aggregation, superbin a is more potent as superbin b, c, and d. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays edema-inducing and moderate anticoagulant activities. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 GL1-1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lack enzymatic activity. Displays myotoxin and edema-inducing activities.

name: Phospholipase A2 superbin c
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. In terms of inhibition of platelet aggregation, superbin c is more potent as superbin d. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like ACLD
description: Is a potent activator of prothrombin (F2). Does not elicit any hemorrhagic response. Barely inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. Binds neither collagen, nor the jararhagin-monoclonal antibody MAJar3. Hydrolyzes the Aalpha-chain of fibrin and fibrinogen, without affecting the Bbeta- and gamma-chains. Is capable of triggering endothelial proinflammatory and procoagulant cell responses, but fails to trigger apoptosis. Induces von Willebrand factor release, and the expression of both ICAM1 and E-selectin (SELE) (without increase in VCAM1) in endothelial cells (HUVEC). Is also able to up-regulate the synthesis of the coagulation factor TF (F3). Enhances nitric oxide (NO) generation, prostacyclin production and interleukin-8 release (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 3.3
description: Potent inhibitor of shaker potassium channels as well as the mammalian homologs of shaker.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 3.4
description: Potent inhibitor of the Shaker potassium channel (Ki=0.16 nM) and its mammalian homologs (Kv1.3/KCNA3 (Ki=1.7 nM), Kv1.1/KCNA1 (Ki=136 nM), Kv1.6/KCNA6 (Ki=149 nM)).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 3.2
description: Potent inhibitor of the Shaker potassium channels and its mammalian homologs (Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.3/KCNA3, Kv1.6/KCNA6) (Ki<1 nM for all channels) (PubMed:8204618, PubMed:20007782). Also blocks Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=26.8 nM) (PubMed:8204618, PubMed:20007782).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 4.1
description: Potently blocks Kv1.1/KCNA1 (85%), Kv1.2/KCNA2 (91%), Kv1.3/KCNA3 (89%), Kv1.6/KCNA6 (94%), and Shaker (97%).

name: Phospholipase A2 crotoxin basic chain CBa2
description: Heterodimer CA-CB: Crotoxin is a potent presynaptic neurotoxin that possesses phospholipase A2 (PLA2) activity and exerts a lethal action by blocking neuromuscular transmission. It consists of a non-covalent association of a basic and weakly toxic PLA2 subunit (CBa2, CBb, CBc, or CBd), with a small acidic, non-enzymatic and non-toxic subunit (CA1, CA2, CA3 or CA4). The complex acts by binding to a specific 48-kDa protein (R48) receptor located on presynaptic membranes, forming a transient ternary complex CA-CB-R48, followed by dissociation of the CA-CB complex and release of the CA subunit. At equilibrium, only the CB subunits remain associated with the specific crotoxin receptor. In addition to neurotoxicity, crotoxin has been found to exert myotoxicity, nephrotoxicity, and cardiovascular toxicity (PubMed:20109480). Moreover, anti-inflammatory, immunomodulatory, anti-tumor and analgesic effects of crotoxin have also been reported (PubMed:20109480).

name: Beta-mammal Tt1g
description: Beta toxins modify sodium channel function in two ways: an excitatory effect (shifting the activation process to more negative potential) and/or a depressant effect (reducing the peak current). At concentration of 500 nM this toxin produces channel opening at more negative potentials in hNav1.2/SCN2A and hNav1.3/SCN3A, which shows the biggest effect. On the other hand the peak current is decreased in hNav1.4/SCN4A and hNav1.5/SCN5A channels, without apparent modification of the activation gate. This toxin is active against mammals.

name: U17-barytoxin-Tl1d
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U14-lycotoxin-Ls1b
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1f
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U14-lycotoxin-Ls1a
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: C-type lectin BfL-1
description: Galactose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1d
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U2-lycotoxin-Ls1c
description: Antagonist of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). Blocks insect neuromuscular transmission presynaptically (By similarity).

name: Toxin ICK-18
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U10-barytoxin-Tl1a
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Toxin ICK-8
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: C-type lectin BML-1
description: Recombinant C-type lectin BML-1 is able to agglutinate erythrocytes. May be a calcium-dependent lectin.

name: Frontoxin VI
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Frontoxin III
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Frontoxin IV
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Binds to the muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: U14-lycotoxin-Ls1c
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U14-lycotoxin-Ls1a
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Iota-conotoxin-like R11.13
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like R11.15
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like R11.16
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like R11.11
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like R11.1
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like R11.10
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like R11.12
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: U1-agatoxin-Ta1c
description: Toxin that paralyzes insects. May have a direct effect on the insect central nervous system.

name: Beta-insect excitatory toxin 2
description: Excitatory insect beta-toxins induce a spastic paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: U1-agatoxin-Ta1a
description: Toxin that paralyzes insects. May have a direct effect on the insect central nervous system.

name: U1-agatoxin-Ta1b
description: Toxin that paralyzes insects. May have a direct effect on the insect central nervous system.

name: Disintegrin
description: Inhibits adhesion of cells expressing alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) and alpha-4/beta-7 (ITGA4/ITGB7) integrins to the natural ligands vascular cell adhesion molecule 1 (VCAM-1) and mucosal addressin cell adhesion molecule 1 (MADCAM-1).

name: Phospholipase A1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A2 (EC 3.1.1.4) and phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activities.

name: Kappa-hexatoxin-Hv1a
description: This excitatory toxin inhibits insect calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channels (Slo-type).

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin Im-3
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). Induces paralysis in cricket A.domestica but does not induce death.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BjussuMP-2
description: This metalloproteinase displays proteolytic activity on fibrin, fibrinogen, collagen, casein and gelatin. It inhibits ADP- and collagen-induced platelet aggregation and displays a very low edema inducing activity.

name: Hemorrhagic metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like kaouthiagin
description: Snake venom zinc protease that inhibits hemostasis by binding and cleaving the vWF in humans. Has also and inhibitory effect on the collagen-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Ponericin-W-like 32.1
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Antimicrobial peptide 143
description: Cationic host defense peptide that have antibacterial activity by breaking membranes. Is more effective on Gram-positive than on Gram-negative bacteria.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 25.12
description: Inhibits angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE), but does not serve as substrate for the enzyme. Potentiates bradykinin (BK) on the isolated guinea pig ileum as well as the isolated rat uterus for contraction. Also potentiates in vivo the depressor effect of BK on arterial blood pressure in the normotensive anesthetized rat.

name: Ponericin-W-like 32.2
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating and C-type natriuretic peptides
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 5a: modestly inhibits ACE (with highest affinity for the N-site) and reveals strong bradykinin-potentiating activity. Induces nitric oxide (NO) production depended on muscarinic acetylcholine receptor M1 subtype (CHRM1) and bradykinin B2 receptor (BDKRB2) activation. Both these receptors contribute to the vasodilation induced by this peptide that may have an indirect action on BDKRB2 and a direct agonistic action on CHRM1.

name: U21-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 4
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U21-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 3
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U21-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 1
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Probable phospholipase A1 magnifin
description: Has phospholipase activity, induces dose-dependently platelet aggregation at nanomolar concentration and induces thrombosis in vivo.

name: Disintegrin saxatilin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3). Also inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. Inhibits basic fibroblast growth factor (bFGF)-induced proliferation of human vascular endothelial cell (HUVEC), and vitronectin-induced migration of smooth muscle cells (SMC). It also regulates platelet activation associated with HUVEC migration and invasion, suppresses TNF-alpha-induced ovarian cancer cell proliferation and invasion, and inhibits angiogenesis and tumor progression.

name: Three-finger toxin Mnn I
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: U5-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Causes spastic paralysis and death in mice in 4-6 min after intracerebroventricular injection at dose levels of 1.5 ug per mouse.

name: U5-ctenitoxin-Pk1b
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Causes spastic paralysis and death in mice in 4-6 min after intracerebroventricular injection at dose levels of 1.5 ug per mouse.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 16.2
description: Alpha-KTx 16.2: inhibits large conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa1.1/Slo-beta4 KCNMA1/KCNMB4). It appears to block channel activity by a simple bimolecular inhibition process. Shows a fast association rate and a slow dissociation rate of binding on rat brain synaptosome (PubMed:18199674). Significantly inhibits voltage-dependent sodium current and voltage-dependent delayed rectifier potassium currents (PubMed:14632928).

name: U12-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: Toxin Cn11
description: First blocker of sodium channels (Nav) found in scorpions. Is lethal to crustaceans (Cambarellus montezumae), less toxic to insects (crickets) and non-toxic to mammals (mice) at the doses assayed.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hs2a
description: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hs2a blocks voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav) in adult cockroach DUM neurons. Reversibly paralyzes locusts and cockroaches, and causes death at high doses,.

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1h
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.25 mg/kg body weight (By similarity).

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1f
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.25 mg/kg body weight (By similarity).

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1g
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.25 mg/kg body weight (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Cobra venom factor
description: Complement-activating protein in cobra venom. It is a structural and functional analog of complement component C3b, the activated form of C3. It binds factor B (CFB), which is subsequently cleaved by factor D (CFD) to form the bimolecular complex CVF/Bb. CVF/Bb is a C3/C5 convertase that cleaves both complement components C3 and C5. Structurally, it resembles the C3b degradation product C3c, which is not able to form a C3/C5 convertase. Unlike C3b/Bb, CVF/Bb is a stable complex and completely resistant to the actions of complement regulatory factors H (CFH) and I (CFI). Therefore, CVF continuously activates complement resulting in the depletion of complement activity.

name: Cytotoxin homolog 5
description: Has low cytotoxic activity.

name: Cytotoxin I-like T-15
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Disintegrin DisBa-01
description: This recombinant disintegrin antagonizes integrins alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) and alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3). On ITGA2B/ITGB3, it interferes with the outside/-in phosphorylation of the focal adhesion kinase (PTK2 / FAK) downstream of the integrin. It strongly inhibits platelet aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, and collagen, abolishes and reverses dynamic platelet recruitment to immobilized fibrinogen. In vivo, it induces a dramatic increase in the tail bleeding time, and has a strong antithrombotic activity (PubMed:18508682). On ITGAV/ITGB3, it inhibits the adhesion of ITGAV/ITGB3-expressing human microvascular endothelial cell line and murine melanoma cell line to vitronectin (IC(50) = 555 nM and 225 nM, respectively), and transiently inhibits their proliferation without direct cell toxicity. In vivo, it potently inhibits angiogenesis and metastasis (PubMed:17952617), probably due to its capability to strongly inhibit the expression of VEGF and its receptors in endothelial cells (PubMed:22561350). It also inhibits tumor cell migration in vitro (PubMed:22069567).

name: Toxin Aam1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Toxin Aam2
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Thrombostatin
description: Inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation and inhibits the binding of purified platelet fibrinogen receptor alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) to immobilized fibrinogen.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 3.7
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 (IC(50)=0.6nM), Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=5.4nM), Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=0.014nM) potently, and moderately block intermediate conductance calcium-activated potassium channels KCa3.1/KCNN4 (IC(50)=225nM). At high concentration (2 mM), is also active on Kv1.6/KCNA6 and Shaker IR.

name: Delta-conotoxin-like Bt6.4
description: This toxin activates voltage-gated sodium channels. It shifts the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized potentials but has only little effect on channel inactivation. It is active on Nav1.3/SCN3A (EC(50)=3.98 nM), Nav1.4/SCN4A (EC(50)=4.99 nM), Nav1.6/SCN8A (EC(50)=1.27 nM) and Nav1.7/SCN9A (EC(50)=2.42 nM) voltage-gated sodium channels. In vivo, it induces nocifensive or pain-like behaviors in mice when injected intraplantarly.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme acutin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Has arginyl esterase and fibrinogen clotting activities.

name: U17-barytoxin-Tl1a
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1c
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.11
description: Blocks Kv1.3/KCNA3 voltage-gated potassium channels of human T-lymphocytes (Kd=0.98 nM).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.12
description: Weakly blocks Kv1.3/KCNA3 voltage-gated potassium channels (Kd is estimated to be 69 nM).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6.12
description: High affinity blocker of Kv1.3/KCNA3 channels of human T cells. Blocks Kv1.2/KCNA2 with an order of magnitude smaller than for Kv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 1.4
description: Blocks selectively the high conductance calcium-activated (maxi-K) potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.8
description: Blocks Kv1.3/KCNA3 voltage-gated potassium channels of human T-lymphocytes (Kd=0.71 nM).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.9
description: Blocks Kv1.3/KCNA3 voltage-gated potassium channels of human T-lymphocytes (Kd=0.25 nM).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.10
description: Weakly blocks Kv1.3/KCNA3 voltage-gated potassium channels (Kd is estimated to be 366 nM).

name: Disintegrin CC8A
description: Inhibits integrins alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3), alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3), and alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1).

name: Disintegrin CC5
description: Binds and inhibits integrins alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3), alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) and alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1).

name: Contryphan-Vn
description: Affects both voltage-gated and calcium-dependent potassium channel activities, with composite and diversified effects in invertebrate and vertebrate systems. Intramuscular injection in freshwater fishes (Poecelia pinnata) causes secretion of mucous substances, a reaction already observed in fish with other contryphans.

name: Disintegrin CC8B
description: Inhibits integrins alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3), alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3), and alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1).

name: Natriuretic peptide DNP-2
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Mu-agatoxin-Hc1a
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces irreversible neuromuscular blockade in the cricket A.domestica. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons.

name: Omega-agatoxin-1A
description: Omega-agatoxin are antagonist of voltage-gated calcium channels. They block insect neuromuscular transmission presynaptically. This toxin is a blocker of L-type calcium channels (Cav/CACNA1).

name: Mu-agatoxin-Hc1c
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces irreversible neuromuscular blockade in the cricket A.domestica. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme gloshedobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. The recombinant form clots fibrinogen by cleaving fibrinogen Aalpha chain (FGA), and slowly Bbeta chain (FGB). Has amidolytic activities.

name: Snake venom serine protease 1
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Weak toxin DE-1 homolog 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like ArMKLT1-011
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Short neurotoxin A
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Myotoxin-2
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SdSicTox-betaIIB1bi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Myotoxin-3
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin horrdistatin-2
description: Disintegrin horrdistatin-1: inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation (IC(50) is 16.2 nM) by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3).

name: Disintegrin mojastin-2
description: Disintegrin mojastin-1: inhibits the three processes involved in platelet function (adhesion, activation and aggregation). It inhibits platelet adhesion to fibronectin with an IC(50) of 58.6 nM. It inhibits ATP release from platelet induced by ADP with an IC(50) of 19.5 nM on platelet-rich plasma, probably by binding to ADP receptors (P2RY1 and P2RY12). Finally, it inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation with IC(50) of 44.7 nM on platelet-rich plasma and 19.3 nM on whole blood, probably by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) (PubMed:20598348).

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin BjIT2
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Ryncolin-4
description: Initiates complement activation and/or interferes in platelet aggregation and/or blood coagulation.

name: Myotoxin-4
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Waglerin-3
description: Waglerin-1 selectively blocks the epsilon subunit of muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR). Has also effects on rodent ionotropic GABA(A) receptors (GABR), since it potentiates I(GABA) in some neurons and depresses I(GABA) in others. In mice, it elicits tachypnea, ocular proptosis, rapid collapse and spasms, whereas no toxic effects on respiration and blood pressure are observed in rats.

name: Mu-agatoxin-Aa1c
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons.

name: Delta-conotoxin Am2766
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process.

name: Snake venom serine protease HS112
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Babycurus-toxin 1
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits both the activation and inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Beta-toxin Cii1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin BomPI
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Toxin Cll2b
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). This toxin had also a depressive action on the classical calcium current activated at high membrane potentials. This toxin is active on mammals.

name: Beta-toxin Cll2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Conotoxin mr3g
description: Intracranially injection into mice does not elicit symptoms.

name: Conotoxin mr3b
description: Intracranial injection into mice causes scratching and hyperactivity.

name: Conotoxin mr3d
description: Intracranially injection into mice does not elicit symptoms.

name: Conotoxin tx3b
description: Intracranial injection into mice causes scratching, hyperactivity and circular motion.

name: Neurotoxin 8-related gene product 1/2/3
description: Binds voltage-dependently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Cp20.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Cp20.4
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Cp20.5
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ms20.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ms20.4
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

Also inhibits apamin-sensitive small conductance calcium-activated potassium (SK/KCNN) channels, and inhibits intermediate conductance calcium-activated potassium KCa3.1/KCNN4 channels (IC(50)=1 nM).

name: Omega-lycotoxin-Gsp2671a
description: Modulates P-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) in rat cerebellar Purkinje cells and hippocampal CA1-CA3 neurons. At saturating concentrations (>10 nM) the toxin decelerates activation kinetics and slightly increases peak amplitude without affecting deactivation kinetics.

description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).
