description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Muscarinic toxin 4
description: Binds to the muscarinic acetylcholine receptor (CHRM).

name: C-type lectin PAL
description: Galactose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. This is a calcium-dependent lectin (PubMed:8593494). Shows high hemagglutinating activity (MHC is 0.25 ug/ml on rabbit erythrocytes) (PubMed:10484740).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor textilinin-7
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Phospholipase A1 4
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 HTe
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that blocks neuromuscular transmission, but that does not produce blockade by virtue of a selective action on nerve endings. Instead, the toxin acts both on nerve and on muscle. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor microlepidin-5
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase HT-1
description: Zinc protease from snake venom that induces hemorrhage.

name: Neurotoxin 3
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 ammodytoxin A
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that acts as a presynaptic neurotoxin, an inhibitor of blood coagulation, and has been found to bind with high affinity to intracellular proteins. The response of indirectly stimulated neuromuscular preparations to ammodytoxin (Atx) is triphasic. The first phase, the transient inhibition of the acetylcholine (ACh) release, starts soon after the addition of Atx and lasts for several minutes. This phase is probably independent of Atx enzymatic activity. The effect may be due to the specific binding of the toxin to presynaptic receptors. These receptors, called N-type receptors, are still unidentified. It is noteworthy that a neuronal isoform of the M-type PLA2 receptor (R180) has been identified as a high-affinity receptor for Atx in neuronal plasma membranes. It was demonstrated however that this receptor is not essential for expression of neurotoxicity by Atx. The second phase corresponds to an augmentation of neurotransmitter release. A peak is reached 10-20 min after exposure of the preparation to Atx and is followed by a gradual reduction. In this phase, the enzymatic activity of Atx of the mammalian is not significant. It is speculated that the increased release of neurotransmitter in this phase is induced by the interference of Atx with voltage-gated potassium channels. Measurements of ionic currents showed however that voltage-gated potassium channels are not affected by Atx. The third phase of the response of neuromuscular preparations to Atx, which corresponds to a complete and irreversible paralysis, is clearly dependent on the hydrolytic activity of the toxin. In addition to its presynaptic neurotoxicity, Atx shows an anticoagulant activity by binding with high affinity to activated coagulation factor X (F10) thus inhibiting the formation of the prothrombinase complex (FX/FV) and its activity (IC(50) is 20 nM). Surprisingly, Atx was discovered to bind intracellular proteins such as calmodulin (CaM) (IC(50) is 6 nM), 14-3-3 proteins gamma (YWHAG) and epsilon (YWHAE) (by similarity with AtxC), as well as R25 (by similarity with AtxC), a mitochondrial integral membrane protein found in cerebral cortex. These findings raised a doubt about the dogma of the exclusively extracellular action of PLA2s, defended by the potential instability of these molecules in the reducing environment of the eukaryotic cytosol coupled with their possible inability to act as enzymes in this cellular compartment, due to too low concentration of calcium ions. This hypothesis was challenged efficiently by demonstrating the internalization of AtxA into a culture cells, but still remains to be directly demonstrated in vivo. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 6
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme barnettobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that releases only fibrinopeptide A from human Aalpha chain of fibrinogen (specific coagulant activity was 251.7 NIH thrombin units/mg). Also shows fibrino(geno)lytic activities in vitro and defibrinogenating effects in vivo.

name: Alpha-conotoxin Mr1.7a
description: Alpha-conotoxin MrIC: acts as a co-agonist with PNU (an alpha-7 nAChR-selective allosteric modulator) at the endogenous alpha-7/CHRNA7 nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) when tested in human SH-SY5Y neuroblastoma cells. Is the third alpha-conotoxin that acts as an agonist (after alpha-conotoxin SrIA/SrIB). Also acts as an antagonist at human alpha-7 nAChRs heterologously expressed in Xenopus oocytes.

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1a
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Suppresses the excitatory postsynaptic potentials evoked in lobster neuromuscular synaptic preparations, possibly by blocking the presynaptic calcium channel. Induces instantaneous reversible paralysis when injected into crickets. Does not show effect on mammalian Cav2.1/CACNA1A, Cav2.2/CACNA1B and Cav2.3/CACNA1E (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1f
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1e
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1d
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1c
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 11.3
description: Binds and inhibits voltage-sensitive potassium channels. Inhibits the vertebrate potassium channel Kv1.1/KCNA1 with low affinity.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Ps1a
description: Potently blocks A-type potassium currents. Specifically blocks Kv4.2/KCND2 and Kv4.3/KCND3 channels by altering the gating properties of these channels.

name: Hainantoxin-X-3
description: Reversibly blocks N-type calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B) in rat dorsal root ganglion cells. Elicits no toxic symptoms in either vertebrates or invertebrates during a period of 48 hours post-injection, when it was assayed in vivo by direct injection into mice and cockroaches (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like agkihagin
description: Strongly inhibits the collagen-induced human platelet aggregation. Hydrolyzes the Aalpha-chain of fibrinogen (FGA), without cleavage of Bbeta- and gamma-chains. Induces apoptosis and strongly inhibits proliferation of endothelial cells as well as adhesion of the cells to extracellular matrix proteins (By similarity).

name: Hainantoxin-X.3
description: Reversibly blocks N-type calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B) in rat dorsal root ganglion cells. Elicits no toxic symptoms in either vertebrates or invertebrates during a period of 48 hours post-injection, when it was assayed in vivo by direct injection into mice and cockroaches (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin Mr1.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin inhibits rat alpha-7 and weakly alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-2 and alpha-3-beta-2 nAChR. In vivo, this toxin shows analgesic effect.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Qc1.1a
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Qc1.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and inhibit them. This synthetic peptide (10 uM) selectively, but weakly inhibits both rat neuronal alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 (63%) and alpha-3-beta-4/CHRNA3-CHRNB4 (37%) subtypes of nAChR.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Lp1.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Sarafotoxin-D
description: Vasoconstrictor activity. These toxins cause cardiac arrest probably as a result of coronary vasospasm. May act by displaying agonistic activities towards endothelin-1 and -2 receptors (EDNRA and EDNRB).

name: Hainantoxin-X.2
description: Reversibly blocks N-type calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B) in rat dorsal root ganglion cells. Elicits no toxic symptoms in either vertebrates or invertebrates during a period of 48 hours post-injection, when it was assayed in vivo by direct injection into mice and cockroaches (By similarity).

name: Alpha-toxin Ac3
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Anti-insect Ac4
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). This protein is weakly toxic against insects (ED(50)>2 ug per 100 mg of blowfly larvae), but is inactive against mammalian sodium channels (rNav1.2a, and rNav1.4) (PubMed:20018978).

name: Alpha-toxin Ac1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-toxin Ac2
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 KPA2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows anticoagulant and neurotoxic activities. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 16.4
description: Weak inhibitor of voltage-gated potassium channel hKv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides. Cytotoxic in Ehrlich ascites carcinoma model in mice and towards human cancer cell line U937 (IC(50)=610 ug/ml).

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Pc1a
description: Possess strong antiplasmodial activity against the intra-erythrocyte stage of P.falciparum in vitro. IC(50) for inhibiting P.falciparum growth is 1.59 uM. Interacts with infected and healthy erythrocytes. Does not lyse erythrocytes, is not cytotoxic to nucleated mammalian cells, and does not inhibit neuromuscular function. Has neither antibacterial nor antifungal activity.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 5.3
description: Blocks small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCNN, SK).

name: U2-theraphotoxin-Pc1a
description: Possess strong antiplasmodial activity against the intra-erythrocyte stage of P.falciparum in vitro. IC(50) for inhibiting P.falciparum growth is 1.15 uM. Specifically interacts with infected erythrocytes. Does not lyse erythrocytes, is not cytotoxic to nucleated mammalian cells, and does not inhibit neuromuscular function. Has neither antibacterial nor antifungal activity.

name: U-theraphotoxin-Aju1a
description: Has strong antifungal activity against C.albicans MDM8, C.krusei IOC 4559 (MIC=2.5-5 uM), C.glabrata IOC 45658 (MIC=2.5-5 uM), C.albicans IOC 45588 (MIC=2.5-5 uM), C.parapsilosis IOC 456416 (MIC=2.5-5 uM), C.tropicalis IOC 45608 (MIC=2.5-5 uM), C.guilliermondii IOC 455716 (MIC=2.5-5 uM) and A.niger (MIC=5-10 uM). Lacks antifungal activity against B.bassiana. Has no antibacterial effect against Gram-positive bacteria M.luteus, S.epidermidis, S.aureus or against Gram-negative bacteria E.coli and P.aeruginosa. Has no hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. Probable ion channel inhibitor (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Neutral phospholipase A2 homolog taipoxin beta chain 2
description: Heterotrimer: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) heterotrimer that acts as a potent presynaptic neurotoxin by blocking synaptic transmission and synaptic vesicle recycling. May act by binding in a calcium-dependent fashion to neurotonal pentraxin-1 (NPTX1) and neurotonal pentraxin-2 (NPTX2), but not to neuronal pentraxin receptor (NPTXR). Also binds to taipoxin-associated calcium binding protein 49 (RCN2), a protein localized in the lumen of endoplasmic reticulum.

name: Phospholipase A2 crotoxin basic subunit CBb
description: Heterodimer CA-CB: Crotoxin is a potent presynaptic neurotoxin that possesses phospholipase A2 (PLA2) activity and exerts a lethal action by blocking neuromuscular transmission. It consists of a non-covalent association of a basic and weakly toxic PLA2 subunit (CBa2, CBb, CBc, or CBd), with a small acidic, non-enzymatic and non-toxic subunit (CA1, CA2, CA3 or CA4). The complex acts by binding to a specific 48-kDa protein (R48) receptor located on presynaptic membranes, forming a transient ternary complex CA-CB-R48, followed by dissociation of the CA-CB complex and release of the CA subunit. At equilibrium, only the CB subunits remain associated with the specific crotoxin receptor. In addition to neurotoxicity, crotoxin has been found to exert myotoxicity, nephrotoxicity, and cardiovascular toxicity (PubMed:20109480). Moreover, anti-inflammatory, immunomodulatory, anti-tumor and analgesic effects of crotoxin have also been reported (PubMed:20109480).

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Hs1f
description: Blocks neuromuscular transmission. Acts cooperatively to potentiate the activity of huwentoxin-I. Paralyzes locusts and kills mice following intracerebroventricular injection.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Intracisternal injection paralyzes mice.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Intracerebroventricular injection paralyzes mice. Has no effect on voltage-gated sodium currents.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Blocks neuromuscular transmission. Acts cooperatively to potentiate the activity of huwentoxin-I. Paralyzes locusts and kills mice following intracerebroventricular injection.

name: U6-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Binds to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor. Blocks neuromuscular transmission.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Reversibly blocks N-type calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B) in rat dorsal root ganglion cells (IC(50)=40 nM). Elicits no toxic symptoms in either vertebrates or invertebrates during a period of 48 hours post-injection, when it was assayed in vivo by direct injection into mice and cockroaches.

name: Kunitz-type kappaPI-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits both serine proteases (trypsin) and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv). The toxin is more active on Kv1.1/KCNA1 (78% inhibition), than on Kv1.2/KCNA2 (10% inhibition), and Kv1.3/KCNA3 (28% inhibition), although a high dose (5 uM) is needed. The inhibition of potassium channels is voltage-dependent.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like HV1
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like that potently activates prothrombin (F2). Does not elicit any hemorrhagic response. Barely inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. Hydrolyzes the alpha-chain of fibrin and fibrinogen (FGA), without affecting the Bbeta- and gamma-chains (By similarity). Induces apoptosis in cultured vascular endothelial cells.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1h
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1g
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 8.6
description: Inhibits Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv3/KCNC and Shaker potassium channels.

name: Neurotoxin MeuClTx
description: Inhibits Kv1.2/KCNA2 potassium channels. On glioma cells, may interact with chloride channels (probably Clc-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex may be then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation.

name: Neurotoxin MeuClTx-1
description: Inhibits Kv1.2/KCNA2 potassium channels. On glioma cells, may interact with chloride channels (probably Clc-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex may be then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation.

name: Neurotoxin MeuNaTx-2
description: Inhibits Nav1.4 and DmNav1 sodium channels. Has antibacterial activity.

name: Neurotoxin MeuNaTx-4
description: Inhibits DmNav1 sodium channels (Nav).

name: Neurotoxin MeuNaTx-5
description: Inhibits sodium channels (Nav). Has antimicrobial activity.

name: Neurotoxin MeuNaTx-6
description: Inhibits sodium channels (Nav). Has antimicrobial activity.

name: Meucin-49
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Alpha-toxin PgKL1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin inhibits cardiac sodium channels and voltage-gated T-type calcium channels (Cav3.3/CACNA1I).

name: Three-finger toxin 3FTx-2
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A3 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A1 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

description: Heterotrimer: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) heterotrimer that acts as a potent presynaptic neurotoxin by blocking synaptic transmission and synaptic vesicle recycling. May act by binding in a calcium-dependent fashion to neurotonal pentraxin-1 (NPTX1) and neurotonal pentraxin-2 (NPTX2), but not to neuronal pentraxin receptor (NPTXR). Also binds to taipoxin-associated calcium binding protein 49 (RCN2), a protein localized in the lumen of endoplasmic reticulum.

name: Neutral phospholipase A2 homolog taipoxin beta chain 1
description: Heterotrimer: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) heterotrimer that acts as a potent presynaptic neurotoxin by blocking synaptic transmission and synaptic vesicle recycling. May act by binding in a calcium-dependent fashion to neurotonal pentraxin-1 (NPTX1) and neurotonal pentraxin-2 (NPTX2), but not to neuronal pentraxin receptor (NPTXR). name: Basic phospholipase A2 taipoxin alpha chain
description: Heterotrimer: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) heterotrimer that acts as a potent presynaptic neurotoxin by blocking synaptic transmission and synaptic vesicle recycling. Also binds to taipoxin-associated calcium binding protein 49 (RCN2), a protein localized in the lumen of endoplasmic reticulum.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 4
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 3
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has several activities. It is myotoxic, has weak anticoagulant activity and inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Alpha/kappa-conotoxin-like fe14.1
description: Highly inhibits both nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (neuronal (alpha-3/beta-4) and neuromuscular (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) subtypes) and the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.6/KCNA6 subtype.

name: Alpha/kappa-conotoxin-like pl14.3
description: Highly inhibits both nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (neuronal (alpha-3/beta-4) and neuromuscular (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) subtypes) and the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.6/KCNA6 subtype.

name: Alpha/kappa-conotoxin-like pl14.2
description: Highly inhibits both nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (neuronal (alpha-3/beta-4) and neuromuscular (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) subtypes) and the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.6/KCNA6 subtype.

name: Alpha/kappa-conotoxin-like pl14.1
description: Highly inhibits both nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (neuronal (alpha-3/beta-4) and neuromuscular (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) subtypes) and the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.6/KCNA6 subtype.

name: Alpha/kappa-conotoxin-like fe14.2
description: Highly inhibits both nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (neuronal (alpha-3/beta-4) and neuromuscular (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) subtypes) and the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.6/KCNA6 subtype.

name: Alpha/kappa-conotoxin pl14a
description: Highly inhibits both nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (neuronal (IC(50)=8.7 uM for alpha-3/beta-4) and neuromuscular (IC(50)=0.54 uM for alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta) subtypes) and the voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.6/KCNA6 subtype (IC(50)=1.59 uM).

name: Protopolybiakinin-1
description: Causes constriction of the isolated rat ileum muscles (is 13-fold less potent than bradykinin (BK)), as well as degranulation of mast cells (is 7-fold more potent than BK). In vivo, causes algesic effects. Muscle constriction and algesic effects are partially mediated by bradykinin receptors B2 (BDKRB2).

name: Protopolybiakinin-2
description: Shows a high potency in mast cell degranulation (is 10-fold more potent than bradykinin).

name: Disintegrin accutin
description: Inhibit human platelet aggregation induced by ADP, collagen, thrombin or the thromboxane analog U46619 in platelet suspension with IC(50) values of 66-267 nM. Acts by inhibiting fibrinogen interaction with platelet receptors GPIIb/GPIIIa (ITGA2B/ITGB3) (PubMed:9838213). It also inhibits angiogenesis in vivo and in vitro by blocking integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) of endothelial cells and by inducing apoptosis (PubMed:9787163).

name: Insecticidal toxin LaIT1
description: Affects the activity of both ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channels RyR1 and RyR2 with high potency. At lower concentrations the toxin increases full openings of the RyRs, and at higher concentrations it inhibits full openings and induce openings to subconductance levels and reduces the number of full conductance openings. The different actions may be attributed to the toxins binding at different sites on the RyRs, with binding at a high-affinity site mediating the increase in full openings and the induction of subconductance states evoked upon binding to a lower-affinity site (By similarity). Shows insect lethality against crickets and common cutworms (only shows paralysis against cockroaches), but no toxicity is observed in mice.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase brevilysin L4: metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal (By similarity). Shows autoproteolysis dependent on pH and temperature. Does not show hemorrhagic activity.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin (Ki=3520 nM).

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Hs1b
description: Lethal neurotoxin that blocks neuromuscular transmission. Acts cooperatively to potentiate the activity of huwentoxin-I.

name: Adrenergic toxin rho-elapitoxin-Dp1b
description: Highly potent on various alpha-adrenoceptors (ADRA) (subnanomolar affinity for ADRA1A). Order of potency is the following: ADRA1A > ADRA1B > ADRA1D > ADRA2C. Were also found to reversibly bind to muscarinic acetylcholine receptors (CHRM), but the affinity is much weaker (micromolar range).

name: Alpha-delta-bungarotoxin-2
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Bc2a
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission (By similarity). Competitive antagonist of nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. Binds reversibly to chick and mouse muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. Preferentially binds to alpha-delta subunit interface of the adult mouse muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Bc2c
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Cytotoxin 5
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes (PubMed:8182052). In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1d
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1c
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1a 4
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1a 3
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1a 6
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1a 5
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1b 2
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1b 1
description: Agglutinates erythrocytes.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1i
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1j
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like RgIB
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. Is a specific blocker of the alpha-3/beta-4 nAChR and may also block alpha-3/beta-4/alpha-5 channels. Causes hyperactivity and behavioral disorders in mice following intracranial injection.

name: Kappa-scoloptoxin-Ssm2e
description: Toxin that inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Kappa-scoloptoxin-Ssm1e
description: Toxin that inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Translationally-controlled tumor protein homolog
description: Venom protein that causes edema, enhances vascular permeability and is likely related to the inflammatory activity of the venom.

name: Phospholipase A1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1o
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Sarafotoxin-i1
description: Vasoconstrictor activity. These toxins cause cardiac arrest probably as a result of coronary vasospasm (By similarity).

name: U10-ctenitoxin-Pr1a
description: Non-toxic to mice and insects.

name: U3-ctenitoxin-Asp1a
description: Possible neurotoxin.

name: Toxin ICK-15
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic activity, but has myotoxic and cytolytic activities.

name: Neutral phospholipase A2 RVV-PFIIc'
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows enzymatic, indirect hemolytic and anticoagulant activities. Interestingly, anti-PFIIc'serum completely inhibits anticoagulant activity, partially inhibits the indirect hemolytic activity, but does not inhibit enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme Cdc SII
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that coagulates human plasma and bovine fibrinogen by hydrolysis of the alpha chains (FGA) (minimum coagulation dose is 60 ug on fibrinogen). Has fibrinogenolytic activities, and degrades preferentially the Aalpha chain (FGA). Shows amidolytic activity toward N-benzoyl-L-Arg-p-nitroanilide, has a higher activity than Cdc SI. In vivo, intravenous injection induces defibrin(ogen)ation and a loss of the righting reflex and opisthotoxins, together with a typical gyroxin-like effect (18-20 minutes). Subcutaneous injection into the footpads induces moderate edema. Potentiates local hemorrhagic activity induced by metalloproteinases (BaP1).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme Cdc SI
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that coagulates human plasma and bovine fibrinogen by hydrolysis of the alpha chains (FGA) (minimum coagulation dose is 120 ug on fibrinogen). Has fibrinogenolytic activities, and degrades preferentially the Aalpha chain (FGA). Shows amidolytic activity toward N-benzoyl-L-Arg-p-nitroanilide, has a lower activity than Cdc SII. In vivo, intravenous injection induces defibrin(ogen)ation and a loss of the righting reflex and opisthotoxins, together with a typical gyroxin-like effect (18-20 minutes). Subcutaneous injection into the footpads induces moderate edema. Potentiates local hemorrhagic activity induced by metalloproteinases (BaP1).

name: Hyaluronidase
description: Spider venom endo-hyaluronidase that is able to degrade purified hyaluronic acid (HA) and chondroitin sulfate (CS). Has no activity on dermatan sulfate (DS) and heparan sulfate (HS). Also increases the dermonecrotic effect of the dermonecrotic toxin (AC P0CE80), when injected in rabbit skin, supporting the hypothesis that venom hyaluronidases are spreading factors.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase leucurolysin-A
description: Non-hemorrhagic metalloproteinase that hydrolyzes the alpha chains of fibrinogen, as well as fibrin, fibronectin and casein. Beta and gamma chains are also hydrolyzed, but more slowly. Thrombolytic activity is also observed. Induces detachment of endothelial cells followed by death, and inhibits endothelial cell adhesion to fibronectin. Induces edema in mouse paw. Inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation on human platelet-rich plasma with an IC(50) of 2.8 uM.

name: Snaclec lebecin subunit beta
description: Inhibits the adhesion of MDA-MB231 human breast cancer cells to fibrinogen and fibronectin, MDA-MB231 cell migration, and the MDA-MB231 cell proliferation. This inhibition may be due to the binding to receptors of the integrin family, probably alpha-v/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) (40% inhibition of cell adhesion) and alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) (by comparison with lebectin).

name: Putative neurotoxin
description: Causes intoxication, paralysis and death in insects (A.domestica).

name: Anti-neuroexcitation peptide 2
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits them (By similarity). Recombinant ANEP delays the convulsion seizure of insect models by 18% and shows anti-neuroexcitatory activity.

name: Anti-neuroexcitation peptide 3
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits them (By similarity). Recombinant ANEP delays the convulsion seizure of model animals by 18% and shows anti-neuroexcitatory activity.

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx34.1
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: 2.4 kDa venom peptide
description: Not lethal to mice by intraperitoneal or intracerebroventricular injections in doses up to 150 micrograms.

name: 2.39 kDa venom peptide
description: Not lethal to mice by intraperitoneal or intracerebroventricular injections in doses up to 100 micrograms.

name: Weak neurotoxin 8
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Weak neurotoxin 6
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Weak neurotoxin 7
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 10.2
description: Blocks Shaker B potassium-channels (Kv1.1/KCNA1 sub-family).

name: Toxin BmKK16
description: Blocker of potassium channels (Kv).

name: Toxin BmKK12
description: Blocker of potassium channels (Kv).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase brevilysin L6: shows weak degradation of alpha-fibrinogen, but has no activity on beta- and gamma-chains. Digests luteinizing hormone-releasing hormone (LH-RH) and oxidized insulin at X-Leu, X-Phe, and X-Val bonds as well as X-His bond. Does not show fibrinogen-clotting activity. Does not show hemorrhagic activity.

name: Snake venom serine protease KN4 homolog
Snake venom serine protease KN6
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease KN1
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease KN2
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease KN9
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 DAV-N6
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Three-finger muscarinic toxin 7
description: Binds irreversibly and specifically to an allosteric site of the muscarinic acetylcholine M1 receptor (CHRM1).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 jerdoxin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays edema-inducing activities, exhibits indirect hemolytic activity, and inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 S1E6-b
description: Snake venom phospholipase that inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme okinaxobin-1
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that releases specifically fibrinopeptide B from fibrinogen (FGB) to form fibrin clots.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 H1E6
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog G6K49
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that lacks enzymatic activity. Displays myotoxic activities (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 1.15
description: Potent blocker of both large-conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa1.1/KCNMA1) and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv1.3/KCNA3).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx BmKcug1a
description: Potent blocker of both large-conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa1.1/KCNMA1) and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv1.3/KCNA3 and ERG1/Kv11.1/KCNH2).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 5.5
description: Blocks small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels.

name: Venom dipeptidyl peptidase 4
description: Venom dipeptidyl-peptidase which removes N-terminal dipeptides sequentially from polypeptides having unsubstituted N-termini provided that the penultimate residue is proline. May process venom proteins into their active forms and/or modulate the chemotactic activity of immune cells after the insect sting.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Its effect on platelets is controversial, since it either induces aggregation or inhibits agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: Toxin Aah4
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neoverrucotoxin subunit beta
description: Has hemolytic and lethal activities. Its hemolytic activity is inhibited by anionic lipids, especially potently by cardiolipin.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase leucurolysin-B
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that acts as a potent hemorrhagic toxin. Hydrolyzes the insulin B chain at the 14-Ala-|-Leu-15 bond but not the 16-Tyr-|-Leu-17 bond. Degrades the alpha-chain of fibrin and hydrolyzes the Aalpha-chain of fibrinogen (FGA) while leaving the beta and gamma chains unaffected. Degrades type-I collagen and its gelatin. Degrades the alpha-1 chain of type-IV collagen and its gelatin but not the alpha-2 chain. Degrades plasma fibronectin, plasma vitronectin and basement membrane enactin. It inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Three-finger toxin MS3
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Binds to and inhibits the endogenous nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) in human rhabdomyosarcoma TE 671 cell line with an IC(50) of 346 mM. This neurotoxin is lethal to mice by intraperitoneal injection and to zebrafish by injection at the back of the dorsolateral region.

name: Long neurotoxin MS2
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Very weak inhibitor of the endogenous nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) in the human rhabdomyosarcoma TE 671 cell line. Not toxic to mice by intraperitoneal injection or to zebrafish by injection at the back of the dorsolateral region.

name: Three-finger toxin MS1
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Binds to and inhibits the endogenous nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) in human rhabdomyosarcoma TE 671 cell line with an IC(50) of 48.2 mM. This neurotoxin is lethal to mice by intraperitoneal injection and to zebrafish by injection at the back of the dorsolateral region.

name: Short neurotoxin MS11
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Binds to and inhibits the endogenous nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) in the human rhabdomyosarcoma TE 671 cell line with an IC(50) of 266 mM. Not toxic to mice by intraperitoneal injection or to zebrafish by injection at the back dorsolateral region.

name: Long neurotoxin MS5
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Very weak inhibitor of the endogenous nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) in the human rhabdomyosarcoma TE 671 cell line. This neurotoxin is lethal to zebrafish by injection at the back of the dorsolateral region, but is not toxic to mice by intraperitoneal injection.

name: Long neurotoxin MS4
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Weak inhibitor of the endogenous nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) in the human rhabdomyosarcoma TE 671 cell line with an IC(50) of 690 mM. This neurotoxin is lethal to zebrafish by injection at the back of the dorsolateral region, but is not toxic to mice by intraperitoneal injection.

name: U5-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: U11-ctenitoxin-Co1b
description: Neurotoxin.

name: U7-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: U8-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: U2-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: U14-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: U3-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Antagonist of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1).

name: U4-ctenitoxin-Co1b
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Potassium channel toxin Meg-beta-KTx1
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Reg1f
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin RegIIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin inhibits alpha-3-beta-2 (IC(50)=33 nM), alpha-3-beta-4 (IC(50)=97 nM), and alpha-7 (IC(50)=103 nM) nAChRs. It also shows a very weak inhibition of alpha-9-alpha-10 nAChR.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Reg1d
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Reg1e
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Conophan vil-M
description: May act as a neurotoxin.

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA1i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 12.5
description: This recombinant toxin inhibits the mammalian voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.3/KCNA3 in vitro with an IC(50) of 28 nM. Kv1.1/KCNA1 and Kv1.2/KCNA2 potassium channels are also weakly inhibited (IC(50)= 1.73 uM and IC(50)=12.63 uM).

name: Conotoxin de7b
description: May inhibit sodium (Nav) or calcium channels (Cav).

name: Conotoxin mr1e
description: Shows excitatory effect on mice by intracranial injection, followed by rigid paralysis of the rear legs and recovering after 30 min.

name: Conotoxin pr3a
description: Intraperitoneal injection into fish (1 nmol) provokes paralysis after 5 min.

name: Mu-conotoxin-like pr3b
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) (By similarity). Intraperitoneal injection into fish (1 nmol) provokes weakening and difficulty in swimming after 20 min.

name: Conotoxin pr6a
description: Intraperitoneal injection into fish (1 nmol) provokes hyperactivity and erratic swimming in various directions after 14 min.

name: Conotoxin pr6b
description: Intraperitoneal injection into fish (0.5 nmol) provokes vertical suspension and paralysis after 6 min.

name: U6-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA1iv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.1.3a
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.1.3b
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Depressant insect toxin BmK ITa1
description: Depressant insect toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently to sodium channels (Nav) and block action potentials, primarily by depolarizing the axonal membrane and suppressing the sodium current (By similarity).

name: Snake venom serine protease IVa
description: Snake venom serine protease that potently induces platelet aggregation. Its aggregatory activity is partially inhibited by monoclonal antibodies against GPIb and the thrombin receptor. Its ability to induce intracellular Ca(2+) release is blocked by pretreating platelets with thrombin. Hydrolyzes thrombin chromogenic substrate CBS 34.47, but shows very weak coagulant activity. Can hydrolyze fibrinogen alpha-chains.

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1r
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating and C-type natriuretic peptides isoform 2
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 10c: peptide with several activities. It inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) by a preferential interaction with its C-domain (PubMed:11994001). It evokes transient hypotension (-14 mmHg) similar to that evoked by 0,5 ug of bradykinin, when injected alone into rats. It has a high bradykinin-potentiating effect (120%), when 60 nmol of BPP-10c are coinjected with 0.5 ug of bradykinin into rats (PubMed:22869554). Does not affect angiotensin-1 pressor effects. Shows potent and long-lasting antihypertensive activity as well as a reduction of the heart rate (PubMed:17475904). It also binds and dose-dependently promotes the activation of cytosolic argininosuccinate synthase (ASS1), an enzyme that catalyzes the conversion of citrulline, L-aspartate and ATP to argininosuccinate, AMP and pyrophosphate. It also enhances ASS1-dependent arginine production in HEK 293 cells, as well as in spontaneous hypertensive rat (SHR) and Wistar rat plasma. In addition, it induces the production of nitric-oxide (NO) by HUVEC cells via the endothelial nitric-oxide synthase (NOS3), which use arginine as a substrate and produce NO. It has been shown to be internalized by ASS1-expressing endothelial (HUVEC) and kidney (HEK 293) cells, and is detected homogenously distributed within the cell cytoplasm for up to 2 hours (PubMed:19491403).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1u
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1t
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1x
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1w
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1z
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1y
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Beta-mammal toxin Tpa2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is lethal to mice.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 13.3
description: Reversibly blocks Shaker B potassium channels, with a dissociation constant of 200 nM.

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin HF
description: Induces angiogenesis, probably through VEGF receptor (KDR/VEGFR-2) signaling, as well as drastic hypotension. The hypotension is mediated by nitric oxide (NO), which is produced by VEGF-activated endothelium NO synthase. Increases capillary permeability when injected intradermally into rat.

name: Alpha-latrotoxin associated low molecular weight protein 2
description: May increase the toxicity of alpha-latrotoxin and/or other venom components. Is non-toxic to mice and to the cockroach Periplaneta americana.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A-AL2 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A-AL3 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A-AL4 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 homolog textilotoxin D chain
description: Snake venom oligomeric phospholipase A2 that has potent presynaptic neurotoxicity. Chain D is not itself neurotoxic, but it is essential for the neurotoxicity of textilotoxin. Chain D possesses a very low phospholipase activity.

name: Beta-bungarotoxin B chain-like
description: Beta-1-bungarotoxin is a presynaptic neurotoxin of the venom. The B chain is homologous to venom basic protease inhibitors but has no protease inhibitor activity and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv) (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A-AL1 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Snake venom serine proteinase
description: Cleaves a kininogen analog with the release of kallidin (lysyl-bradykinin). Completely cleaves fibrinogen Aalpha chain, partially cleaves Bbeta chain and has no activity on gamma chain.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog textilotoxin B chain
description: Snake venom oligomeric phospholipase A2 that has potent presynaptic neurotoxicity. Chain B is not itself neurotoxic, but it is essential for the neurotoxicity of textilotoxin. Subunit B possesses a very low phospholipase activity.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 textilotoxin A chain
description: Snake venom oligomeric phospholipase A2 that has potent presynaptic neurotoxicity. Chain A possesses a very low toxcicity, but is essential for neurotoxicity. Possess a low enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor blackelin-3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 bothropstoxin-2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows a moderate enzymatic activity. It induces indirect hemolytic, anticoagulant, and cytotoxic activities. In vivo, it induces muscle necrosis, accompanied by polymorphonuclear cell infiltration, and edema in the mouse paw. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.4
description: Blocks voltage-gated non-inactivating potassium channels (Kv) and unblocks inactivating potassium channels blocked by alpha-dendrotoxin in synaptosomes. It is not toxic to mice and crustaceans, but has a paralysing effect on crickets.

name: Venom peptide isomerase heavy chain
description: Peptide isomerase that inverts the chirality at the Ser-81 of omega-Aga IVB. Acts cofactor-independently.

name: Vejovine
description: Displays significant potent antimicrobial activity against clinical isolates of Gram-negative multidrug resistant strains of E.coli, P.aeruginosa and A.baumanii with MIC values as low as 4.4 uM. Additionally, it displays low cytolytic and hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes reaching 50% hemolysis at 100 uM.

name: Ponericin-G6
description: Has activity against Gram-positive bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has non-hemolytic activity.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase ACLH
description: This zinc hemorrhagic metalloproteinase has fibrino(geno)lytic activities. It causes hemorrhage and has myonecrotic activity on both fiber types I and II. The recombinant enzyme, without post-translational modifications, also has proteolytic activity, but does not show any hemorrhagic activity.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase ACLF
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that has fibrinolytic activity. The recombinant enzyme cleaves both alpha- and beta-chains of fibrinogen, but not the gamma-chain. The recombinant protein does not produce hemorrhage in mice.

name: C-type lectin 1
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Long neurotoxin 2
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Acetylcholinesterase
description: In muscle, it terminates signal transduction at the neuromuscular junction by rapid hydrolysis of the acetylcholine released into the synaptic cleft. In liver, its function is unclear: it could serve as a safeguard against any diffusion of acetylcholine from synapses into the circulation. In venom, its toxic role is unclear: It could result in less musculatory control by rapidly hydrolyzing acetylcholine, or that it works synergistically with alkaline phosphatase (ALP) in paralyzing prey through hypotension.

name: Three finger toxin MALT0051C
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Three finger toxin MALT0052C
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Three finger toxin MALT0054C
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Three finger toxin MALT0057C
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Three finger toxin MALT0058C
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Alpha-fibrinogenase A1
description: Snake venom serine protease that completely cleaves fibrinogen Aalpha chain (FGA), partially cleaves Bbeta chain (FGB) and has no activity on gamma chain. Is more potent that A2 and A3 alpha-fibrinogenases. Very active within 5 minutes.

name: Snaclec rhinocetin subunit beta
description: Antagonist of the alpha-2 subunit of the integrin alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1) on human platelets and endothelial cells. This protein inhibits collagen-stimulated activation of human platelets in a dose-dependent manner. In addition, it antagonizes the binding of monoclonal antibodies against the alpha-2 subunit of integrin alpha-2/beta-1 to platelets and it coimmunoprecipitates with this integrin.

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog
description: Has cytotoxic activities against HUVEC cells (LC(50)=4.9 uL) and human lung adenocarcinoma A549 cells (LC(50)=3.5 uL).

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog
description: Has cytotoxic activities against HUVEC cells (LC(50)=12.2 uL) and human lung adenocarcinoma A549 cells (LC(50)=8.5 uL).

name: Melittin
description: Main toxin of bee venom with strong hemolytic activity. Integrates into cell membranes and has multiple effects, probably, as a result of its interaction with negatively charged phospholipids. It inhibits well known transport pumps such as the Na(+)-K(+)-ATPase and the H(+)-K(+)-ATPase. Increases the permeability of cell membranes to ions, particularly Na(+) and indirectly Ca(2+), because of the Na(+)-Ca(2+)-exchange (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog beta-bungarotoxin B2 chain
description: Beta-2-bungarotoxin is a presynaptic neurotoxin of the venom. The B chain is homologous to venom basic protease inhibitors but has no protease inhibitor activity and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog beta-bungarotoxin B1 chain, major component
description: Beta-1-bungarotoxin is a presynaptic neurotoxin of the venom. The B chain is homologous to venom basic protease inhibitors but has no protease inhibitor activity and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv) (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor dendrotoxin E
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin (Kd=1 nM) and chymotrypsin (Kd=100 nM). May also inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv). Binds transition metal ions such as copper and cobalt.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog dendrotoxin B
description: Highly selective blocker of voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv). Inhibits trypsin weakly.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog delta-dendrotoxin
description: Serine protease inhibitor homolog that blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog dendrotoxin K
description: Serine protease inhibitor homolog that selectively blocks voltage-gated potassium channels homooligomer Kv1.1/KCNA1 (EC(50)=0.6 nM) and Kv1.1-containing heterooligomer.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog alpha-dendrotoxin
description: Serine protease inhibitor homolog that blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, and Kv1.6/KCNA6) (IC(50)=0.4-150 nM) and facilitates neurotransmitter release.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Potassium channel toxin ImKTx88
description: Recombinant toxin selectively inhibits Kv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channels with an IC(50) of 91 pM.

name: Neuropeptide Y2-like conopeptide
description: Causes huperactivity such as jumping, rapid circling and tail flicking, when intraventicular injection into mice brain.

name: Neuropeptide Y1-like conopeptide
description: Causes hyperactivity such as jumping, rapid circling and tail flicking, when intraventricularly injected into mice brain.

name: Beta-toxin Cl13
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). Inhibits sodium channels Nav1.4/SCN4A, Nav1.5/SCN5A and Nav1.6/SCN8A (PubMed:27871874). Also has a weak inhibitory effect on Nav1.2/SCN2A (PubMed:27871874). Is lethal to mice (PubMed:27871874).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 12b
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptides both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: Venom peptide SjAPI
description: Recombinant protein inhibits both alpha-chymotrypsin (Ki=97.1 nM) and elastase (Ki=3700 nM).

name: Venom peptide SjAPI-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Venom peptide CtAPI
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Phospholipase A2 neuwieditoxin-2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows presynaptic neurotoxicity. 10 ug/ml of this protein produce complete neuromuscular blockade up to 70 minutes, without inhibiting the responses to acetylcholine (ACh), but with a partial inhibition (67%) of the response to potassium chloride (KCl).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 BnpTX-1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2). In vitro, shows anticoagulant activity and induces cytotoxicity when tested on C2C12 myoblasts/myotubes. In vivo, when tested on mice, induces myotoxicity (intramuscular injection), edema (injection in the subplantar region) and lethality. Also induces neurotoxic effect on mouse neuromuscular preparations and has bactericidal activity on the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli (ATCC29648) and the Gram-positive S.aureus (ATCC 25923). The catalytic and anticoagulant activities of BnpTX-I are higher than those of BnpTX-II. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 BnpTX-2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2). In vitro, shows anticoagulant activity and induces cytotoxicity when tested on C2C12 myoblasts/myotubes. In vivo, when tested on mice, induces myotoxicity (intramuscular injection), edema (injection in the subplantar region) and lethality. The catalytic and anticoagulant activities of BnpTX-II are lower than those of BnpTX-I. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: C-type lectin galatrox
description: Lectin that displays hemagglutinating activity on all types of trypsinized human erythrocytes (A+, B+, AB+, and O+), with a higher sensitivity to AB+ type. Is inhibited by different carbohydrates with alpha-lactose displaying the most potent ability to block agglutination (followed by D-fucose, D-galactose, D-rhamnose, D-mannose, and D-sucrose). Is also inhibited by EDTA and pretreatment with heat. In addition, it induces significant cell death in HL-60 cells in a dose-dependent manner, with an IC(50) close to 250 ug/ml. Is a calcium-dependent lectin.

name: Toxin CsE8
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Beta-toxin CsE3
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin E1x
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Acetylcholinesterase toxin C
description: Inhibits acetylcholinesterase.

name: Weak toxin CM-10
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Toxin S4C8
description: This specific blocker of the L-type calcium channel (Cav1/CACNA1) is a smooth muscle relaxant and an inhibitor of cardiac contractions.

name: Toxin S6C6
description: May enhance presynaptic acetylcholine release.

name: Toxin C10S2C2
description: This specific blocker of the L-type calcium channel (Cav1/CACNA1) is a smooth muscle relaxant and an inhibitor of cardiac contractions.

name: Toxin MIT1
description: Potent agonist for both PKR1/PROKR1 and PKR2/PROKR2 (PubMed:12054613). Potently contracts gastrointestinal (GI) smooth muscle (PubMed:10567694).

name: Phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 APC-D49
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Natriuretic peptide
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein Mr30
description: Has no proteolytic activity.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BpirMP
description: Zinc metalloprotease that preferentially degrades Aalpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA) (at a dose of 5 ug, whereas at a dose of 10 ug, both FGA and FGB are completely degraded). Degrades fibrin gel in a dose-dependent manner, as well blood clots formed in vitro (thrombolytic activity). Induces hemorrhage (in the dorsal skin of mice), with an MHD of 50 ug. The basal membrane components collagen (all chains of type IV) (COL4A4), fibronectin (FN1), laminin and nidogen are all degraded by this toxin.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 4
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that exhibits strong anticoagulant activity, which is not due to the catalytic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2
description: Phosholipase toxin, which catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides. Inhibits both skeletal (RYR1) and cardiac (RYR2) ryanodine receptors (calcium release channels). Probably blocks ryanodine receptors by generating a lipid product (By similarity). Shows hemolytic activity, but it is not know if it is direct or indirect.

name: Putative calcium channel toxin Tx758
description: Potassium channel inhibitor and putative ryanodine receptor inhibitor (RYR).

name: Long neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor (By similarity), thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission (PubMed:17906946).

name: Long neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 8
description: Binds with high affinity to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and hinders acetylcholine binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission. Causes muscle paralysis, spasms and increased respiration.

name: Long neurotoxin 2
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Toxin Pg8
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Amphipathic peptide OcyC2
description: Amphipathic peptide with probable antimicrobial activity.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like batroxstatin-1
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading the extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. Has also fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 BlatPLA2
description: Acidic phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that only causes a mild edema, when subcutaneously injected in the mice foot. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1s
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1v
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U17-barytoxin-Tl1d
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Its effect on platelets is controversial, since it either induces aggregation or inhibits agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions.

name: Delta-ctenitoxin-Asp2e
description: Inhibits the inactivation of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: Serine protease sp-Eoc49
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: U1-ctenitoxin-Asp1a
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). They block neuromuscular transmission presynaptically (By similarity).

name: Snaclec CTL-Eoc125
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec CTL-Eoc124
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Antimicrobial peptide UyCT1
description: Antimicrobial peptide UyCT1: inhibits the growth of Gram-positive (S.aureus, MIC=15 uM) and Gram-negative bacteria (E.coli, MIC=10 uM and P.aeruginosa, MIC=10 uM). It also shows 26% of hemolysis when 15 uM are tested (81% at 50 uM) (PubMed:23182832).

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog
description: Has cytotoxic activities against HUVEC cells (LC(50)=5.0 uL) and human lung adenocarcinoma A549 cells (LC(50)=5.2 uL).

name: Mu-hexatoxin-Mg2a
description: Competes for binding at site 3 of the insect voltage-gated sodium channel (Nav). Insecticidal neurotoxin. Causes temporary paralysis to lepidopteran larvae when injected at 10.3 nmol/g. Is not toxic to mice when injected intracranially at 20 pmol/g.

name: Mu-hexatoxin-Mg1a
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin. Shows competition for site 3 of insect voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Induces flaccid paralysis when injected into lepidopteran larvae. Is not toxic to mice when injected intracranially at 20 pmol/g.

name: Mu-hexatoxin-Mg1b
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin. Shows competition for site 3 of insect voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 6
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has high lipolytic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide AP
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 7c
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 7b
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 12d
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: Conantokin-R1-C
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. This toxin has antagonist activity on NR2B/GRIN2B (IC(50)=1.4 uM) and NR2A/GRIN2A (IC(50)=2.9 uM) subunits, when tested on rat receptors.

name: Conantokin-R1-B
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. This toxin has antagonist activity on the NR2B/GRIN2B subunit (IC(50)=0.1 uM), when tested on rat receptors. In vivo, when delivered into the brain, is active has anticonvulsant activity in the model of epilepsy in mice.

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 12e
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 8a
description: This peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as edema, antibacterial (E.coli, and P.aeruginosa) and antiparasitic activities, as well as induction of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions. This protein may also have activities in hemorrhage, hemolysis, and apoptosis.

name: Cobrotoxin-b
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission. Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Has a lower toxicity than cobrotoxin.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
