description: The heterodimer bitisgabonin-1 is a potent inhibitor of the adhesion of the RGD-dependent integrin alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) to immobilized fibronectin.

name: Disintegrin gabonin-2
description: The heterodimer bitisgabonin-2 preferentially inhibits the adhesion of the alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) and alpha-9/beta-1 (ITGA9/ITGB1) integrins to VCAM-1 and acts also as a strong antagonist of alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1).

name: Long neurotoxin 77
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin 73
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin 31
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin 469
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor vestiginin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Phospholipase D LiSicTox-alphaIA2ai
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Its effect on platelets is controversial, since it either induces aggregation or inhibits agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LiSicTox-alphaIA1bi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation. Both C5a and the membrane attack complex may play a role in the induction of dermonecrosis. MMP-9 and MMP-2 produced by skin fibroblasts can also contribute to proteolytic tissue destruction.

name: Venom nerve growth factor 2
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Venom nerve growth factor 3
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor vestiginin-4
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Venom nerve growth factor 1
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein LIO1
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein LEI1
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein ENH2
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein ENH1
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein DIS3
description: Weakly blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein DIS2
description: Weakly blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein DIS1
description: Weakly blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein VAR8
description: Blocks ryanodine receptors, and potassium channels.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A chain
description: Beta bungarotoxin is a presynaptic neurotoxin. The A chain has phospholipase activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Three-finger hemachatoxin
description: This protein lyses red blood cells and has cardiotoxic and hypotensive activities.

name: Snaclec jerdonibitin subunit alpha
description: Snaclec that dose-dependently inhibits platelet aggregation induced by ristocetin or low-dose thrombin, but not by high-dose thrombin. Binds to GPIbalpha (GP1BA). In vivo, also dose-dependently induces thrombocytopenia of mice and platelet counts remains at very low level even after 18 hours intravenous injection.

name: Snaclec jerdonibitin subunit beta
description: Snaclec that dose-dependently inhibits platelet aggregation induced by ristocetin or low-dose thrombin, but not by high-dose thrombin. Binds to GPIbalpha (GP1BA). In vivo, also dose-dependently induces thrombocytopenia of mice and platelet counts remains at very low level even after 18 hours intravenous injection.

name: Purotoxin-2
description: Enhances the high-affinity desensitization of P2RX3 receptors. At 50 nM, decreases the IC(50) for ambient ATP from 2.67 nM to 0.77 nM in human P2RX3. Does not affect mouse P2RX2 or P2RX2/P2RX3 receptors.

name: Disintegrin viridin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Disintegrin lutosin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Disintegrin cereberin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelet. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Disintegrin molossin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Conantokin-G
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. This toxin is selective for the NR2B/GRIN2B subunit. Induces sleep-like symptoms in young mice and hyperactivity in older mice.

name: Disintegrin basilicin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Disintegrin cotiarin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Antimicrobial peptide ctriporin
description: Antimicrobial peptide that acts by breaking the cell wall. Is active against Gram-positive bacteria, fungi and antibiotic-resistant pathogens: S.aureus (MIC=5 ug/ml), M.luteus (MIC=5 ug/ml), B.thuringiensis (MIC=10 ug/ml), B.subtilis (MIC=10 ug/ml), C.albicans (MIC=20 ug/ml), methicillin-resistant S.aureus (MIC=5-10 ug/ml), and penicillin-resistant S.epidermidis (MIC=10 ug/ml). Is efficient in curing staphylococcal skin infection in mice, when externally applied.

name: Alpha-conotoxin RgIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically inhibits the alpha-9-alpha-10 (CHRNA9-CHRNA10) nAChR (PubMed:16445293, PubMed:21888386, PubMed:22774872, PubMed:25740413, PubMed:18242183, PubMed:18295795). It interacts with the alpha-10(+)/alpha-9(-)interface of the receptor (PubMed:25740413). It shows a two order of magnitude species difference potency for the rat versus human alpha-9-alpha-10 nAChR, due to the Thr-86 located in the alpha-9 nAChR subunit (PubMed:22774872). This toxin also shows inhibition of high voltage-activated (HVA) calcium channels by acting on GABA(B) receptors (GABBR1 and GABBR2) (PubMed:18945902, PubMed:21888386). In vivo, this toxin produces an acute antinociceptive effect in peripheral nerve-injured rats, which may be related to the inhibition of immune cell buildup at the site of nerve injury (PubMed:17101979). In addition, when intramuscularly injected into rats following chronic constriction injury of the sciatic nerve, this toxin protects peripheral nervous tissues as well as prevents central maladaptive plasticity by inhibiting glial cell activation (PubMed:25008370).

name: Snake venom metalloprotease inhibitor 02A10
description: pEKW peptides may serve as metalloproteinase inhibitors during glandular storage. Their inhibition may be instantly disengaged, by dilution or physiochemical change, when venom is injected into tissue of the victim.

name: U14-lycotoxin-Ls1a
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Snake venom metalloprotease inhibitor 02D01
description: pEKW and poly-His-poly-Gly peptides may serve as metalloproteinase inhibitors during glandular storage. Their inhibition may be instantly disengaged, by dilution or physiochemical change, when venom is injected into tissue of the prey.

name: Jingzhaotoxin F7-10.36
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Cg2a 2
description: Inhibits TTX-sensitive sodium currents (IC(50) is 1.77 uM) but has no effect on TTX-insensitive sodium currents on rat dorsal root ganglion (DRG) neurons. Inhibits TTX-insensitive sodium currents on rat cardiac myocytes (IC(50) is 0.9 uM).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Cg2a 3
description: Inhibits TTX-sensitive sodium currents (IC(50) is 1.77 uM) but has no effect on TTX-insensitive sodium currents on rat dorsal root ganglion (DRG) neurons. Inhibits TTX-insensitive sodium currents on rat cardiac myocytes (IC(50) is 0.9 uM).

name: Potassium channel toxin MeuTXKbeta3
description: MeuTXKbeta3 inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Jingzhaotoxin F4-32.60
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Inhibits TTX-sensitive sodium currents (IC(50)=85 nM). Also inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv) in rat DRG neurons. May also inhibit mammalian sensory neuronal sodium channels (Nav) through a mechanism similar to HWTX-IV by trapping the IIS4 voltage sensor in the resting conformation, but their binding sites should not overlay completely.

name: Jingzhaotoxin F6-27.63
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U18-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Inhibits TTX-sensitive and TTX-insensitive sodium currents (IC(50) is 0.6 uM and 0.95 uM respectively) on rat dorsal root ganglion (DRG) neurons (PubMed:18581053, PubMed:19409400). Inhibits muscular subtypes sodium channels Nav1.4/SCN4A and Nav1.5/SCN5A transiently transfected in to HEK293 cells (IC(50) is 5.42 uM and 0.45 uM respectively). Also blocks Kv2.1/KCNB1 potassium channels expressed in X.laevis oocytes with an IC(50) of 604 nM. Injection of the toxin in mice was immediately followed by general ataxia, lack of response to stimuli and semiparalysis (PubMed:19409400).

name: Toxin ICK-23
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase atrolysin-D
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that causes hemorrhage by provoking the degradation of the sub-endothelial matrix proteins (fibronectin, laminin, type IV collagen, nidogen, and gelatins).

name: U20-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 1
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Meucin-25
description: This synthetic cationic peptide inhibits the development of Plasmodium berghei ookinetes, kills intraerythrocytic P.falciparum, and is cytotoxic to the Drosophila S2 cell at micromolar concentrations. No antibacterial, antifungal and hemolytic activities have been found at micromolar concentrations.

name: Hainantoxin F1-31.97
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U2-lycotoxin-Ls1d
description: Antagonist of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). Blocks insect neuromuscular transmission presynaptically (By similarity).

name: Toxin ICK-13
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Basic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: U2-lycotoxin-Ls1b
description: Antagonist of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). Blocks insect neuromuscular transmission presynaptically (By similarity).

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids (highly active against L-Leu followed by L-Phe and L-Ile and not active against L-Pro, L-Asn, L-Gly, L-Ser and L-Cys), thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities such as antibacterial activity (Minimal inhibitory concentrations (MIC) are 9.0 ug/ml against S.aureus, 144.0 ug/ml against P.aeruginosa and 288.0 ug/ml against E.coli) and inhibition of ADP- and TMVA-induced platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions. Unlike other snake venom L-amino acid oxidases, does not induce hemorrhage. This protein may also induce hemolysis, edema, apoptosis and have antiparasitic activities.

name: U11-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: Frontoxin V
description: Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site. Binds to the muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: C-type lectin BfL-2
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIII1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaII1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LapSicTox-alphaII1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaII1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Hypotensin-1
description: Agonist of the B2 bradykinin receptor (BDKRB2). Potentiates the hypotensive effect of bradykinin (BK) and induces a direct vasorelaxing effect, independently of BK, by endothelium- and nitric oxide (NO)-dependent mechanisms in rat aortic ring preparations.

name: Phospholipase D LruSicTox-alphaIC2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LruSicTox-alphaIC1a
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LruSicTox-alphaIC1d
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Beta-cardiotoxin CTX27
description: Acts as a beta-blocker by binding to beta-1 and beta-2 adrenergic receptors (ADRB1 and ADRB2). It dose-dependently decreases the heart rate (bradycardia), whereas conventional cardiotoxins increases it. At 100 mg/kg, intraperitoneal injection into mice provokes labored breathing, impaired locomotion, lack of response to external stimuli, and death (after 30 min).

name: Phospholipase D LruSicTox-alphaIC1b
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Frontoxin I
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Frontoxin II
description: Neurotoxin. Blocks muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR).

name: U13-hexatoxin-Mg1a
description: No toxicity is observed upon intracranial injection into mice and intrathorax injection into crickets.

name: U14-hexatoxin-Mg1a
description: No toxicity is observed upon intracranial injection into mice and intrathorax injection into crickets.

name: Delta-hexatoxin-Mg1b
description: Inhibits tetrodotoxin-sensitive sodium channels (Nav) (By similarity). Intracranial injection into mice causes strong convulsions and death. Intrathorax injection into crickets causes paralysis prolonged for 2 min, followed by recovery.

name: Phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase D LiSicTox-alphaII2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor NACI
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin (Ki=25 nM).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin ussurin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase ussurin: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Translationally-controlled tumor protein homolog
description: Venom protein that causes edema, enhances vascular permeability and is likely related to the inflammatory activity of the venom.

name: Beta-pompilidotoxin
description: Inhibits sodium channel (Nav) inactivation. Shows two types of inhibitory activities on channels. Inhibition of insect DmNav1/para and hNav1.6/SCN8A shows a large increase in the steady-state current component without any increase in the slow component, whereas inhibition of hNav1.1/SCN1A, hNav1.2/SCN2A, hNav1.3/SCN3A and hNav1.7/SCN9A shows a large increase in the slow component with only a small steady-state component (PubMed:20059541). Is 5-fold more potent than alpha-PMTX for inducing repetitive action potentials in lobster neuromuscular junctions.

name: Alpha-pompilidotoxin
description: Inhibits sodium channels (Nav) inactivation. Shows two types of inhibitory activities on channels. Inhibition of hNav1.6/SCN8A shows a large increase in the steady-state current component without any increase in the slow component, whereas inhibition of hNav1.1/SCN1A, hNav1.2/SCN2A, hNav1.3/SCN3A and hNav1.7/SCN9A shows a large increase in the slow component with only a small steady-state component (PubMed:20059541). Is 5-fold less potent than beta-PMTX for inducing repetitive action potentials in lobster neuromuscular junctions.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein Cau1
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Anoplin
description: Exhibits potent activity in stimulating degranulation from rat peritoneal mast cells but not from RBL-2H3 cells. Exhibits broad-spectrum antimicrobial activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity towards human erythrocytes.

name: Gamma-conotoxin PiVIIA
description: Micromolar concentrations of PiVIIA increase the magnitude of the macroscopic calcium current in DRG neurons from rat. An increase, even modest of the calcium current, may have a significant impact in the excitability and electrical activity of neurons, and may set up PiVIIA as a member of the pharmacological family of the gamma-conotoxins.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin VMP-II
description: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin VMP-II: inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation (probably by binding integrin alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3)) and degrades fibrinogen.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme TL-BJ 3
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Causes the specific clotting of fibrinogen (FGA) with release of fibrinopeptide A. The aberrant fibrinogen is then incapable of being cross-linked, forming easily dispersible clots.

name: Conotoxin mr3a
description: Intracranial injection into mice causes circular motion, barrel rolling and convulsions.

name: Conomap-Vt
description: Is a potent and mollusk specific excitatory peptide. Most potent excitatory effect are observed on the buccal mass. It interacts with non-cholinergic receptors. As this peptide is a major component of the venom, it may play an important role in prey capture.

name: Conotoxin r7a
description: Induces a sleep-like state in mice.

name: Phaiodotoxin-3
description: Sodium channel (Nav) specific neurotoxin.

name: Phaiodotoxin
description: Sodium channel (Nav) specific neurotoxin. Causes impairment of movement and mild paralysis in crickets at a dose of 0.5 ug per animal. A dose of 0.8 ug per cricket causes clear flaccid paralysis. A dose of 1.0 ug per cricket causes death within 2 hours.

name: Phaiodotoxin-2
description: Sodium channel (Nav) specific neurotoxin.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Alpha-toxin
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-toxin Amm3
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like as14b
description: Blocks potassium channels (By similarity). When intracranially injected, elicits scratching and grooming activity in mice, and causes body and rear limb extension and tail curling immediately upon injection.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A7 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Long neurotoxin 13
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1k
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits both serine proteases and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor HNTX-852
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits both serine proteases and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like brevilysin H2b
description: Non-hemorrhagic metalloproteinase that degrades fibrinogen. The alpha chain (FGA) is rapidly degraded, the beta chain (FGB) is degraded very slowly, while the gamma chain is left intact.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor OMI
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits plasma kallikrein (Ki=1.7 nM), and plasmin (Ki=33.0 nM).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor HNTX-03141017
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits both serine proteases (trypsin) and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin BA-5A
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that possesses hemorrhagic activity and degrades alpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA) (By similarity). May inhibit alpha-2/beta-1 integrin (ITGA2/ITGB1).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme BjussuSP-1
description: Thrombin-like enzyme that shows clotting activity upon human plasma. Shows specific fibrinogenolytic activity for Aalpha chain (FGA). Hydrolyzes fibrin, BAPNA and TAME, as well as chromogenic artificial substrates of the blood coagulation cascasde: S-27654 for factor X (F10), S-2302 for kallikrein (KLK), factor XIa (F11), and XIIa (F12), and S-2266 for kallikrein and factor XIa (F11). Subcutaneous injection into mice induces a mild edema. Intravenous and intramuscular injection reduce plasma fibrinogen concentration and increase the levels of fibrin(ogen) degradation products. Intramuscular injection also promotes an increase in the expression of proMMP-9, but is unable to activate it.

name: Kappa 1b-bungarotoxin
description: Postsynaptic neurotoxin that binds and inhibits neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) with high affinity (IC(50)<100 nM). Is a selective, and slowly reversible antagonist of alpha-3/CHRNA3-containing and some alpha-4/CHRNA4-containing AChRs.

name: Kappa 1a-bungarotoxin
description: Postsynaptic neurotoxin that binds and inhibits neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) with high affinity (IC(50)<100 nM). Is a selective, and slowly reversible antagonist of alpha-3/CHRNA3-containing and some alpha-4/CHRNA4-containing AChRs.

name: Weak toxin 2
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Weak toxin 1
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Lebetin-2-alpha
description: Lebetins inhibit platelet aggregation induced by thrombin, collagen and PAF-acether. Human platelet aggregation induced by thrombin is inhibited by synthetic lebetin-1-alpha, lebetin-1-beta, lebetin-1-gamma, lebetin-2-alpha and lebetin-2-beta with IC(50) values of 140, 32, 5, 2.5 and 2.8 nM, respectively. Lebetins also inhibit fibrinogen-induced aggregation of alpha-chymotrypsin-treated platelets as well as in vivo collagen-induced thrombocytopenia in rats. Lebetins are not toxic upon intravenous injection into mice and rats.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 ammodytin I1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has enzymatic activity but is non-toxic. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: C-type lectin galactose-binding isoform
description: Galactose-binding lectin that binds to and agglutinates erythrocytes in a calcium-dependent manner.

name: Kappa-scoloptoxin-Ssm1b
description: Toxin that inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Kappa-scoloptoxin-Ssm2c
description: Toxin that inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Omega-scoloptoxin-Ssm1a
description: Toxin that increase voltage-gated calcium channel (Cav) currents in DRG neurons by 70% and 120%, when 1 uM and 10 uM are tested, respectively.

name: Alpha-toxin Bu1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Since the experiments have been done on F11 cells (immortalized cell line derived from rat DRG neurons mainly expressing Nav1.3/SCN3A, but also Nav1.7/SCN9A and Nav1.2/SCN2A), it is supposed to act on these channels. The slow of inactivation process is partially reversible. Is lethal to mice.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Hhn1f 4
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog TM-N49
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that exhibits potent myotoxic activity causing inflammatory cell infiltration, severe myoedema, myonecrosis and myolysis in the gastrocnemius muscles of BALB/c mice.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Lsp1b
description: Is toxic to mice but not to insects.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Lsp1c
description: Is toxic to mice but not to insects.

name: Kunitz-type U15-theraphotoxin-Hhn1g
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin and blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Bromoheptapeptide Im
description: Does not elicit gross behavioral symptoms when injected centrally or peripherally in mice.

name: Short neurotoxin D
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Con-Ins Me1
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: C-type lectin lectoxin-Lio3
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like kaouthiagin-like
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that cleaves the membrane-bound precursor of TNF-alpha (TNF) into its mature soluble form showing the same digestion pattern than ADAM17.

name: Beta-insect excitatory toxin BmK IT-AP
description: Excitatory insect beta-toxins induce a spastic paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This insect toxin is also active on mice, showing an analgesic effect.

name: Bombolitin-2
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide.

name: Bombolitin-3
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide.

name: Bombolitin-4
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide.

name: Bombolitin-5
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BaP1
description: Zinc metalloprotease that exhibits a weak hemorrhagic activity (with a minimum hemorrhagic dose of 20 ug by intradermal and intramuscular injection into mice). The basal membrane components collagen (all chains of type IV) (COL4A4), laminin and nidogen are all degraded by this toxin (PubMed:23385358). Rapidly degrades the Aalpha-chain (FGA) of fibrinogen, and later on, degrades the Bbeta-chain (FGB) of fibrinogen (PubMed:7778126). Also activates the complement system, and induces rat neutrophil chemotaxis (PubMed:11200361). Induces edema in mouse food pad and a mild myotoxicity (PubMed:7778126).

name: C-type lectin BJcuL
description: Galactose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. Calcium-dependent lectin. Shows high hemagglutinating activity. When injected into mouse hind paws, (10-100 ug/paw) causes edema and increases vascular permeability. In anesthetized rats, decreases the blood pressure by approximately 15%, with a rapid return to the resting level (PubMed:16309723). Is an effective inhibitor of cell growth in some cancer cell lines, especially against renal and pancreatic cancer cell lines, human breast and ovarian carcinoma, glioblastoma and a bovine brain microvascular endothelial cell line (PubMed:10628348, PubMed:11478954).

name: Toxin Plt
description: Shows moderate insect toxicity coupled with mild effect on mice.

name: Mammal toxin PlMT
description: Binds to sodium channels and affects the channel activation process (By similarity). Has high toxic effect on mice but no effect on B.fusca and C.partellus larvae.

name: Insect toxin PlIT
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). Causes prolonged contractile paralysis in C.partellus larvae. It also has significant toxic effects on B.fusca larvae but not on mice.

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin Lqh-dprIT3h
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and block action potentials, primarily by depolarizing the axonal membrane and suppressing the sodium current. This depressant toxin is active only on insects. It is found in a relatively small amount in the venom.

name: Putative sodium channel alpha-toxin Acra7
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin Oh9-1
description: This toxin binds and inhibits rat muscle alpha-1-beta-1-delta-epsilon (adult) (IC(50)=3.1 uM) and alpha-1-beta-1-gamma-delta (fetal) (IC(50)=5.6 uM) and rat neuronal alpha-3-beta-2 nAChR (IC(50)=50.2 uM) nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) (PubMed:12056805, PubMed:26448325). It binds to the acetylcholine-binding pocket (competitive antagonist) (PubMed:26448325).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hs2a
description: This lethal neurotoxin acts selectively on tetrodotoxin-sensitive (TTX-S) voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), with an IC(50) of 30 nM in rat DRG neurons. Preferentially inhibits neuronal voltage-gated sodium channel subtype hNav1.7/SCN9A (IC(50) is 26 nM), rNav1.2/SCN2A (IC(50) is 150 nM), and rNav1.3/SCN3A (IC(50) is 338 nM), compared with muscle subtypes rNav1.4/SCN4A and hNav1.5/SCN5A (IC(50) is > 10 uM). Inhibits activation of sodium channel by trapping the voltage sensor of domain II of the site 4 in the inward, closed configuration.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating and C-type natriuretic peptides
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity). Neither synthetic Tf1, nor synthetic Tf2 show bradykinin-potentiating effects.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating and C-type natriuretic peptides
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity). Tg1 does not show bradykinin-potentiating effects.

name: Crotamine CRO3
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase Mt-b: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Beta-fibrinogenase brevinase
description: Snake venom serine protease that has fibrinogenolytic activities. Preferentially cleaves the Bbeta-chain (FGB) and more slowly the Aa-chain (FGA) of fibrinogen, but does not affect the gamma-chain. Has also fibrinolytic activity. May play a role in antithrombotic reaction as well as thrombolytic reaction.

name: Synergistic-type venom protein C9S3, chain 2
description: This protein shows a synergetic toxic effect in that it enhances the toxicity of other D.angusticeps toxins.

name: Synergistic-type venom protein C9S3, chain 1
description: This protein shows a synergetic toxic effect in that it enhances the toxicity of an angusticeps type toxin.

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog
description: Has cytotoxic activities against HUVEC cells (LC(50)=2.5 uL) and human lung adenocarcinoma A549 cells (LC(50)=2.9 uL).

name: Neurotoxin BmKAEP2
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects. Has potential anti-epilepsy effect (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels in smooth muscle.

name: Weak toxin CM-11
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Weak toxin S4C11
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Toxin F-VIII
description: Is cytotoxic against A549 cells (LC(50)=106 ug/ml).

name: Synergistic-type venom protein S2C4
description: This protein shows a synergetic toxic effect in that it enhances the toxicity of an angusticeps type toxin.

name: Waprin-Thr1
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like batroxstatin-2
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading the extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. Has also fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin trigramin-beta-2
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to the alpha-IIb/beta-3 receptor (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like crotastatin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading the extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. Has also fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like lachestatin-2
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading the extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. Has also fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like lachestatin-1
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading the extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. Has also fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like batroxstatin-3
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading the extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. Has also fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities (By similarity).

name: Venom antimicrobial peptide-9
description: Amphipathic peptide that exhibits extensive cytolytic activities against both prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells. Is more potent against Gram-positive bacteria (lethal concentration (LC)=1.5-10.9 uM) than against Gram-negative bacteria (LC=6.2->50 uM), and fungi (LC=25.1-8.3 uM). Is lethal to the fungus Beauveria sp (LC=1.9 uM), a highly lethal pathogenic fungus to insects and resistant to many AMPs. Shows hemolytic activity against rabbit erythrocytes (37.7% of inhibition at 6.25 uM) and cytolysis against rat dorsal root ganglions. In vivo, intravenous injection into mice tail provokes uncomfortable symptoms with a death rate of 12.5%.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase aculysin-2: snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Beta/kappa-theraphotoxin-Pm2a
description: Spider venom neurotoxin that blocks voltage-gated sodium channel Nav1.3/SCN3A in human (IC(50)=1 uM) and rat (IC(50)=1 uM). Partially inhibits human Kv11.1/KCNH2/ERG (40% at 10 uM).

name: Snake venom serine protease PTLE1
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Beta/kappa-theraphotoxin-Hlv1a
description: Spider venom neurotoxin that blocks voltage-gated sodium channel Nav1.3/SCN3A in human (IC(50)=80 nM) and rat (IC(50)=160 nM). Partially inhibits human Kv11.1/KCNH2/ERG (25% at 175 uM).

name: Beta-theraphotoxin-Hlv1a
description: Spider venom neurotoxin that blocks voltage-gated sodium channel Nav1.3/SCN3A in human (IC(50)=1 uM) and rat (IC(50)=1 uM).

name: Neurotoxin BmK CT
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, inhibits chloride currents in a voltage-dependent manner (when tested on gliomas cells) (PubMed:17166663). Also interacts with MMP2 and significantly inhibits its catalytic activity (PubMed:21424168). May be internalized with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide NDBP6
description: Amphipathic peptide that shows bradykinin potentiating activity and antimicrobial activities against bacteria and fungi. Has higher antibacterial activities against Gram-negative than against Gram-positive bacteria. Also inhibits NADPH oxidase-dependent superoxide production (IC(50) is 0.4 uM on granulocytes stimulated with PMA, IC(50) is 0.51 uM on HL-60 cells undifferentiated and IC(50) is 0.53 uM on HL-60 cells treated with DMSO). The C-terminal peptide shows a higher bradykinin potentiating activity than the complete peptide.

name: Neurotoxin beta-KTx 12
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channel.

name: Neurotoxin alpha-KTx 26.2
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: U1-cyrtautoxin-As1b
description: Is both paralytic and lethal, when injected into lepidopteran larvae.

name: Mu-cyrtautoxin-As1a
description: The recombinant mu-cyrtautoxin-As1a potently and voltage-independently blocks voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) of insects. It acts by pluging the outer vestibule of the channel. It acts in combination with a weak (30%) voltage-independent block of insect voltage-gated calcium (Cav) channels (low-voltage and high-voltage channels). Tested on DUM neurons, it inhibits sodium currents with an IC(50) of 540 nM (and a Hill coefficient >1, reflecting an incomplete block at higher concentrations). It induces flaccid paralysis in adult Australian sheep blowfly Lucilia cuprina (PubMed:23473802). Is both paralytic and lethal, when injected into lepidopteran larvae. Is a slower acting toxin, being lethal at 24 hours, but not paralytic at 1 hour post-injection (PubMed:1440641).

name: Spasmodic peptide tx9a
description: Intracranial injection into mice of 10 pmol/g of the peptide induces running in circles and hyperactivity. At higher doses (50 pmol/g), the mice exhibit running and climbing symptoms for close to one hour. Between 130 and 150 pmol/g, characteristic "spasmodic" symptomatology is elicited. A hand clap would make mice jump high and start running rapidly. When exposed to a loud hand clap, or if the cage cover were dropped, the mice lose motor control and exhibit seizure-like symptoms from which they eventually recover. At the highest doses tested (over 250 pmol/g), after the characteristic spasmodic symptomatology, lethality occurs. Injection of a similar dose range intramuscularly into Siamese fighting fish elicited no unusual symptomatology.

name: Conotoxin Gm9.1
description: Elicits "spasmodic" symptomatology.

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1aii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1aiii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1avi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1ai
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1biii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1biv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1bi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1bii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LvSicTox-alphaIC1bv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LamSicTox-alphaIC1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein catrin
description: Catrin-2 weakly blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. Catrin-1 has no significant effect. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein ophanin
description: Weakly blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle.

name: U13-theraphotoxin-Cg1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 4
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv2.1/KCNB1 > Kv4.2/KCND2 > Kv4.1/KCND1). Also inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels of subtype Nav1.5/SCN5A (in cardiac myocytes). The toxin shifts activation towards more depolarized potentials and is suggested to bind to the extracellular S3-S4 loop of the channel.

name: U12-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg3a 1
description: Gating modifier of Kv2.1/KCNB1, Kv2.2/KCNB2 and Kv4.3/KCND3 channels.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg3a 2
description: Gating modifier of Kv2.1/KCNB1, Kv2.2/KCNB2 and Kv4.3/KCND3 channels.

name: U13-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U10-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 2
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Cg1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 13.4
description: Blocks the potassium channel Shaker B.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Oh2a
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Latartoxin-2b
description: Insect toxin.

name: Phospholipase D SpaSicTox-betaIIA2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpaSicTox-betaIIA1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIIA2iii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIIA2i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIIA2iv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIIA2v
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIIA1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Toxin BmKT
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). Tested on mice, has antitumor effect and strong inhibitory effect on pain.

name: Toxin ICK-12
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U1-ctenitoxin-Pn1a
description: This neurotoxin reversibly inhibits the N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA)-subtype of ionotropic glutamate receptor. It is highly toxic to house fly (Musca domestica), cockroach (Periplaneta americana), and cricket (Acheta domesticus).

name: Toxin ICK-17
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Toxin ICK-22
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Delta-hexatoxin-Hv1b
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Slows the inactivation of tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) by binding to site 3 of the channel, resulting in repetitive firing in autonomic and motor nerve fibers.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme TL-BJ 1
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Causes the specific clotting of fibrinogen (FGA) with release of fibrinopeptide A. The aberrant fibrinogen is then incapable of being cross-linked, forming easily dispersible clots.

name: Opiscorpine-3
description: Has antimicrobial activity against yeasts and bacteria.

name: Disintegrin eristostatin
description: Is a potent inhibitor of ADP-induced platelet aggregation. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) receptor on the platelet surface. Binds with the same high affinity to resting and activated platelets. Also binds the alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) integrin. Is a potent inhibitor of human and murine melanoma metastases in mouse model systems, also due to the inhibition of binding between the alpha-4/beta-1 integrin and the vascular cell adhesion protein VCAM1. Reacts neither with the integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) vitronectin receptor nor with the integrin alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) fibronectin receptor. Has no effect on cell proliferation or angiogenesis. Specifically inhibits cell migration on fibronectin, but not that on collagen IV or laminin. May involve fibronectin-binding integrins that mediate cell migration.

name: Jararafibrase-3
description: May have both metalloproteinase and lectin activities. Induces local hemorrhage in the skin of rats. Degrades type-IV collagen, gelatin, laminin and fibronectin. Has hemagglutinating activity on red blood cells.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase jararafibrase-4
description: The metalloproteinase is a probable venom zinc protease that induces local hemorrhage in the skin of rats. Degrades type-IV collagen, gelatin, laminin and fibronectin. Has fibrinolytic activities. Has high hemagglutinating activity on red blood cells. Cleaves insulin B chain at 29-His-|-Leu-30, and 38-Ala-|-Leu-39 bonds (PubMed:8087204).

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BnP1
description: This protein is a zinc protease from snake venom that is devoid of significant myotoxic and hemorrhagic activities. It hydrolyzes the Aalpha-chain and more slowly the Bbeta-chain of fibrin and fibrinogen, without affecting the gamma-chains. It induces cell detachment and a apoptosis (anoikis) in endothelial cells.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BnP2
description: This protein is a zinc protease from snake venom that is devoid of significant myotoxic and hemorrhagic activities. It hydrolyzes the Aalpha-chain and more slowly the Bbeta-chain of fibrin and fibrinogen, without affecting the gamma-chains. It induces cell detachment and a apoptosis (anoikis) in endothelial cells (By similarity).

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like as14a
description: Blocks potassium channels (By similarity). When intracranially injected, elicits scratching and grooming activity in mice.

name: Opiscorpine-4
description: Has antimicrobial activity against yeasts and bacteria.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like stejnihagin-A
description: This metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like stejnihagin-B
description: This metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: U2-sicaritoxin-Li1a
description: Toxin active against S.frugiperda larvae. May act on sodium channels (Nav).

name: U1-sicaritoxin-Li1a
description: Toxin active against insects (S.frugiperda larvae). May act on sodium (Nav) or calcium channels (Cav).

name: U1-sicaritoxin-Li1b
description: Toxin active against insects (S.frugiperda larvae). May act on sodium (Nav) or calcium (Cav) channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 1.3
description: Has no effect on potassium channels.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like Vn2
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav) (By similarity). Has strong insecticidal properties at a dose of only 100 pmol/g of body weight (when injected into the haemocoel of the wax moth G. mellonella larvae). Provoques tremor and uncontrolled movements in insect larvae, that are typical symptoms caused by neurotoxins (PubMed:22728460). On fish G.niger, intraperitoneal injection of the toxin causes full extension of the fins, change in posture, breathing difficulties (at 30 and 100 pmol/g body weight) and death (at 100 pmol/g body weight) (PubMed:22728460).

name: Conopeptide Y-Pl1
description: Tyrosine-rich conopeptide that targets several channels/receptors that are expressed in Xenopus oocytes. These targets are the voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.6/KCNA6 (IC(50) is 170 nM) and Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50) is 2.0 uM), Nav1.2/SCN2A (30% of inhibition), and N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptor (GRIN1/GRIN2A/GRIN3B and GRIN1/GRIN2B/GRIN3B) (15% of inhibition). In vivo, causes the marine worm N.virens to move very slowly in contrast to control worms, and causes seizures (at 5 nmol) and death (20 nmol) to mice when intracranially injected.

name: Conopeptide Y-Fe1
description: Tyrosine-rich conopeptide that specifically targets voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.6/KCNA6 (IC(50) is 8.8 uM) that is expressed in Xenopus oocytes. In vivo, causes seizures (at 5 nmol) and death (20 nmol) when intracranially injected into mice, and causes paralysis (at 10 pmol) to C.elegans.

name: Disintegrin schistatin
description: May bind to both alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) and alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) integrins, and may inhibit platelet aggregation.

name: Cyphokinin
description: Cyphokinin: inhibits angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) with a Ki of 2.2 uM and targets B2 bradykinin receptor (BDKRB2). Also provokes contraction of smooth muscle preparation (ileum). In vivo, induces hyperalgesic effects in living rats after intraplantar injection.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase adamalysin-2
description: Has no significant hemorrhagic activity, but inactivates serpins by limited proteolysis of their reactive-site loops.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like Im11.3
description: Inhibits the vertebrate voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 and Kv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Chi-conotoxin CMrVIA
description: Chi-conotoxins inhibit the neuronal noradrenaline transporter (NET/SLC6A2).

name: Conantokin-R
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. This toxin is potent in the following order of preference: NR2B approximately NR2A/GRIN2A > NR2C/GRIN2C >> NR2D/GRIN2D. Induces sleep-like symptoms in young mice. Is a highly potent anticonvulsant compound.

name: Conorfamide-Sr1
description: Causes hyperactivity in mice.

name: Bromosleeper peptide
description: Induces sleep-like symptoms in mice of all ages.

name: Chi-conotoxin CMrX
description: Chi-conotoxins inhibit the neuronal noradrenaline transporter (NET/SLC6A2) (By similarity). Induces flaccid paralysis, when injected intra-cerebroventricularly into mice.

name: Chi-conotoxin MrIA
description: Chi-conotoxins inhibit the neuronal noradrenaline transporter (NET/SLC6A2).

name: Snaclec aspercetin subunit beta
description: Snaclec that binds to von Willebrand factor (VWF) and induces its interaction with GPIbalpha (GP1BA) (via the vWF A1 domain), resulting in platelet aggregation. Intramuscular and intravenous injections in mice induce a dose-dependent drop in platelet count (thrombocytopenia). Pretreatment by intravenous injection by this protein in mice potentiates the hemorrhagic lesion in the skin provoked by the metalloproteinase BaP1 intradermally injected. This result is not observed when both BaP1 and this protein are injected simultaneously.

name: Snaclec aspercetin subunit alpha
description: Snaclec that binds to von Willebrand factor (VWF) and induces its interaction with GPIbalpha (GP1BA) (via the vWF A1 domain), resulting in platelet aggregation. Intravenous injection in mice induces a dose-dependent drop in platelet count (thrombocytopenia). Pretreatment by intravenous injection by this protein in mice potentiates the hemorrhagic lesion in the skin provoked by the metalloproteinase BaP1 intradermally injected. This result is not observed when both BaP1 and this protein are injected simultaneously.

name: Phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has a high indirect hemolytic activity and a potent inhibitory effect on platelet aggregation induced by ADP and collagen. Also produces a significant paw edema reaction in rats. This edematous response is abolished by pretreatment with either indomethacin or dexamethasone, suggesting the involvement of cyclo-oxygenase. May be myotoxic. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays a potent enzymatic activity as measured by indirect hemolysis of red blood cells. Is neither lethal when injected into mice nor does it present anticoagulant activity. Displays a moderate inhibitory activity on the aggregation of platelets induced by low levels of ADP, thrombin and arachidonate. In contrast, strongly inhibits platelet aggregation induced by high doses of collagen. Shows myotoxic activity, increases the plasma creatine-kinase activity and induces edema and myonecrosis of mouse skeletal muscles. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Eumenitin
description: Cationic linear alpha-helical antimicrobial peptide that binds preferentially to charged lipid membranes as compared with zwitterionic ones. It exhibits inhibitory activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, and moderately stimulates degranulation from the rat peritoneal mast cells. Does not show hemolytic activity. May play a role in preventing infection by microorganisms during prey consumption by their larvae.

name: Snaclec bothroinsularin subunit beta
description: Thrombin and prothrombin (F2) inhibitor. The IC(50) of thrombin-induced platelet aggregation and fibrinocoagulation is 62 and 35 nM, respectively. Its inhibitory activity is at least 10-fold lower than that observed for other thrombin inhibitors.

name: Putative insect toxin Acra6
description: Depressant insect toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently to sodium channels (Nav) and block action potentials, primarily by depolarizing the axonal membrane and suppressing the sodium current.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Dpp2b
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor LmKTT-1b
description: Dual-function toxin that completely inhibits trypsin activity at a molar ratio of 1:1 (dissociation constant of 160 nM) and that inhibits mKv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channel currents (1 uM inhibits 50% of currents). It is thermostable.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor LmKTT-1a
description: Dual-function toxin that completely inhibits trypsin activity at a molar ratio of 1:1 (Ki=140 nM) and that inhibits mKv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channel currents (1 uM inhibits 50% of currents) (IC(50)=1.58 uM). Shows also weak inhibition on Kv1.1/KCNA1 (1 uM inhibits 25% of currents) and Kv1.2/KCNA2 (1 uM inhibits 25% of currents).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor BmKTT-3
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits 85% of the activity of trypsin at a molar ratio of 4:1 with a dissociation constant of 760 nM, and that inhibits mKv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channel currents, but very weakly.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 4.1
description: Potassium channel inhibitor (Kv).

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 5.1
description: Blocker of potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 (EC(50)=9.9 uM) and Kv1.6/KCNA6. Acts by binding to the pore and occluding it. Has a voltage-dependent mode of action, which can be explained by a high content of basic residues causing repulsions at higher membrane voltages.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase crotalin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that inhibits ristocin-induced platelet aggregation by abolishing the binding of von Willebrand factor (vWF) to platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha (GPIBA) through the cleavage of both GP1BA and vWF. Also has fibrinogenolytic activities by degrading the alpha- (FGA) and beta-chain (FGB) of fibrinogen. In vivo, induces a slight hemorrhage when applied to chick chorioallantoic membrane and has potent antithrombic effect.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like mikarin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that calcium-independently catalyzes the conversion of prothrombin (F2) to alpha-thrombin through the formation of a thrombin intermediate.

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin ICPP
description: Induces capillary permeability and angiogenesis through VEGF receptor (KDR/VEGFR-2) signaling. Induces DNA synthesis in human umbilical vein endothelial cells, and promotes mouse embryonic stem cell proliferation and differentiation.

name: Alpha-conotoxin Lo1a
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This peptide is active on neuronal nAChRs alpha-7/CHRNA7 (IC(50) of 3.24 uM), alpha-3-beta-4/CHRNA3-CHRNB4, alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2, and alpha-4-beta-4/CHRNA4-CHRNB4. 10 uM of this peptide inhibits these receptors by 85%, 40%, 19%, and 13%, respectively.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor BmKTT-1
description: Dual-function toxin that completely inhibits trypsin activity at a molar ratio of 1:1 (dissociation constant of 136 nM) and that inhibits mKv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channel currents with an IC(50) of 129.7 nM.

name: Long neurotoxin 2
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Neurotoxin BM10-1-like
description: Binds and inhibits muscular and neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein pseudechetoxin-like
description: Blocks olfactory (CNGA2) and retinal (CNGA1) CNG channel currents. Does not affect neither depolarization- nor caffeine-induced contraction of smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Conotoxin qc16a
description: Causes reversible depression symptom in mice when injected intracranially.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 pseudexin B chain
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 pseudexin A chain
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein ablomin
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. Since high potassium-treatment activates voltage-gated channels and caffeine exposure activates ryanodine receptors, this toxin may target L-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav) (and not ryanodine receptors) on smooth muscle (PubMed:12047379). This toxin also shows a little inhibition on cyclic nucleotide-gated CNGA1 channel (PubMed:12646276).

name: Toxin Acra1
description: Probable neurotoxin that inhibits ion channels (By similarity). Is toxic to mice. Is about 2.8% of the total protein in the venom.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PA-3
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PA-1G
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-9C
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-5
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-12A
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-10A
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-15
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-12C
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: C-type lectin mannose-binding isoform
description: Mannose-binding lectin that binds to and agglutinates erythrocytes in a calcium-dependent manner.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase partitagin
description: Zinc metalloproteinase that causes hemorrhage in mice following intradermal injection and impairs hemostasis in its prey. In skin tissues, it degrades components of the basement membrane surrounding blood vessels and capillaries. In muscle tissu, it degrades the extracellular matrix, thus causing muscle necrosis. However, it lacks direct toxicity on myocytes. Hydrolyzes alpha-2 chain (COL4A2) of type IV collagen more slowly than the alpha-1 chain (COL4A1). Hydrolyzes fibronectin (FN1). It also impairs hemostasis by acting on fibrin(ogen) and platelets. Shows fibrinolytic activity, with a selective degradation of gamma-dimer (FGG). Shows fibrinogenolytic activity by preferentially cleaving the Bbeta chain, and later gamma-chain. Aalpha-chain remains resistant to proteolytic digestion. Weakly inhibits collagen-triggered platelet aggregation of human plasma rich platelet.

name: C-type lectin galactose-binding isoform
description: Galactose-binding lectin that binds to and agglutinates erythrocytes in a calcium-dependent manner.

name: Clarkitoxin-1
description: Not toxic to mice when injected intravenously or intraperitoneally.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 ColTx-1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows edema-inducing activity and local and systemic myotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase aculysin-1
description: This protein is an alkaline zinc metalloprotease from snake venom that possesses weak hemorrhagic activity.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx Tx773
description: May block potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 9.8
description: Potassium channel inhibitor.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx Tx790
description: May block potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin BuTXK-beta
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 16.6
description: Inhibits potassium channel.

name: Omega-agatoxin-Aa3d
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels. This toxin blocks calcium channels in insect central neurons but not at peripheral neuromuscular junctions. In vertebrates, it is broadly active against all high-threshold Cav1/CACNA1 channels and Cav2.2/CACNA1B channels.

name: Omega-agatoxin-Aa3b
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels. This toxin blocks calcium channels in insect central neurons but not at peripheral neuromuscular junctions. In vertebrates, it is broadly active against all high-threshold Cav1/CACNA1 channels and Cav2.2/CACNA1B channels.

name: Omega-agatoxin-Aa3c
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Disintegrin EMF10A
description: Extremely potent and selective inhibitor of integrin alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1). Partially inhibits adhesion of cells expressing alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3), alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3), and alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) to appropriate ligands only at concentration higher than 500 nM. Weakly inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Disintegrin EMF10B
description: Extremely potent and selective inhibitor of integrin alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1). Partially inhibits adhesion of cells expressing alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3), alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3), and alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) to appropriate ligands only at concentration higher than 500 nM. Weakly inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog Tx-beta
description: Heterodimer: snake venom phospholipase that potently activates mouse H(+)-gated sodium channel ASIC1/ACCN2 (acid-sensitive ion channel 1) expressed in Xenopus oocytes. Both alternatively spliced isoforms ASIC1a and ASIC1b are activated, with a higher potency for ASIC1a (EC(50)=9.4 nM) vs ASIC1b (EC(50)=23 nM). The ASIC3/ACCN3 subtype is also sensitive to the heterodimer, but with a lower potency (EC(50)=830 nM). On ASIC2a/ACCN1, the toxin shows a very weak activation, but produces a remarkable potentiation (>100-fold) of protons when the extracellular pH drops below neutrality. The toxin interacts with the extracellular region of the channel, since responses are only observed in the outside-out configuration. In vivo, the heterodimer elicits robust pain-related behavior in mice by activation of ASIC1/ACCN2 channels on capsaicin-sensitive nerve fibers.

name: Conantokin-Oc
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors.

name: Myotoxin-2
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Myotoxin-1
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin TxIB
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. Alpha-conotoxin TxIB is a subtype-specific blocker of alpha-6/alpha-3 beta-2 beta-3 nAChRs nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChRs). It has an IC(50) of 28.4 nM.

name: Putative conotoxin
description: Acts as a neurotoxin.

name: U1-poneritoxin-Ae1a
description: Induces reversible paralysis in blowfly L.cuprina. Inhibits human L-type voltage-gated calcium channel Cav1 (CACNA1S, CACNA1C, CACNA1D, CACNA1F) (IC(50)=4.6 uM) in vitro.

name: C-type lectin 13
