description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Potassium channel toxin gamma-KTx 2.1
description: Blocks human and/or rat Kv11.1/KCNH2/ERG1, Kv11.2/KCNH6/ERG2 and Kv11.3/KCNH7/ERG3 by binding to channel outer vestibule (S5P domain) with a 1:1 stoichiometry. Inhibition data are the following: hERG1 (reversible, Kd=7.7 nM (PubMed:16497878), IC(50)=3.3 nM (PubMed:11136720), IC(50)=11.9 nM (PubMed:21205913)), rERG1 (reversible, Kd=19 nM) (PubMed:16497878), hERG2 (reversible, Kd=77 nM) (PubMed:16497878), rERG2 (irreversible, Kd=4.2 nM) (PubMed:16497878), hERG3 (reversible, Kd=11.5 nM) (PubMed:16497878) and rERG3 (reversible, Kd=747 nM) (PubMed:16497878) potassium channels. Has also a minimal effect on rat ELK1/KCNH4 potassium channels (9% inhibition at 100 nM (PubMed:15137031)). Both this toxin and CnErgTx1 (AC Q86QT3) share mechanism of action and have overlapping binding sites on ERG1 (PubMed:12719233). The potency of these two toxins is not affected by elevating potassium ion concentration from 2 to 98 mM (PubMed:12719233). In addition, at high toxin concentrations, block of ERG1 macroscopic currents by these two toxins is incomplete (88%) (PubMed:12719233). The blockade by this toxin is preferentially closed channel state-dependent, with a component of open, but not inactive state-dependent blockade (PubMed:12860380). This toxin produces a concentration-dependent prolongation of QTc in the isolated rabbit heart (16.3% at 100 nM) (PubMed:21205913).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 14.4
description: Selectively and reversibly inhibits small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCNN, SK).

name: Psi-conotoxin PIIIE
description: Psi-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, and act as non-competitive antagonist of nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR). Is more toxic than Psi-conotoxin PIIIF. Has paralytic activity when injected intraperitoneally into goldfish.

name: Calcium-channel toxin-like 20
description: Potently and reversibly modifies channel gating behavior of the type 1 ryanodine receptor (RYR1) by inducing prominent subconductance behavior. Binds a different site as ryanodine (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsSicTox-alphaIA1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase bothrolysin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 8.8
description: Selectively inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels rKv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=331 nM) and hKv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=503 nM). Partially inihibts rKv1.6/KCNA6 (IC(50)=9983 nM).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like VaH1
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that exhibits strong hemorrhagic activity. It also degrades alpha-chain of fibrinogen (FGA), but not the beta- and the gamma-chains. Possesses potent azocaseinolytic activity and cleaves insulin B-chain, hydrolyzing it at positions Ala(14)-Leu(15), followed by Tyr(16)-Leu(17) and His(10)-Leu(11). In vivo, subcutaneous injection into mice induces strong hemorrhage.

name: Pilosulin-1
description: Has strong cytotoxic and hemolytic activities. Is more potent against mononuclear leukocytes than against granulocytes. The synthesized peptide 57-76 shows a potent and broad spectrum antimicrobial activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria, and also against the fungus C.albicans. Adopts an alpha-helical structure.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor IX
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits both serine proteases (high activity on chymotrypsin (Ki = 18 nM), and low activity on elastase) and voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50) = 120.0 nM).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor LmKTT-1c
description: Dual-function toxin that completely inhibits trypsin activity at a molar ratio of 1:1 (dissociation constant of 124 nM) and that inhibits mKv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channel currents (1 uM inhibits 50% of currents).

name: Short neurotoxin 2
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 2
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 4
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 3
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChRs) and with low affinity to neuronal alpha-7 nAChRs and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission. Produces peripheral paralysis by blocking neuromuscular transmission at the postsynaptic site.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Omega-ctenitoxin-Pr1a
description: Inhibits high-voltage activated calcium channels. Shifts the voltage-dependence for activation towards hyperpolarized membrane potentials for L- (Cav1), P/Q- (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) and R-type (Cav2.3/CACNA1E) calcium currents. Causes immediate agitation and clockwise gyration, followed by the gradual development of general flaccid paralysis when injected intracerebroventricular into mice at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse.

name: Cardiotoxin-like basic polypeptide ah
description: Has hemolytic activity under low-lecithin conditions (PubMed:17277458). Has low cytotoxic activity (By similarity). Inhibits the expression of VEGF and bFGF in human non-small-cell lung cancer cell line NCI-H1299 in a dose-dependent manner (PubMed:17277458).

name: Snaclec mamushigin subunit beta
description: Binds to platelet GPIbalpha (GP1BA) and enhances platelet aggregation at low-shear stress. At high-shear stress, blocks platelet aggregation in a dose-dependent manner.

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hi1g
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Irditoxin subunit A
description: This bird and reptile-specific postsynaptic neurotoxin inhibits the chick muscle alpha-1/beta/gamma/delta (CHRNA1/CHRNB1/CHRNG/CHNRD) -nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) 100-fold more compared with the mouse receptor. In vivo, produces rapid flaccid paralysis, dyspnea and increased respiratory rate in geckos. At sublethal doses geckos were immobilized for up to three days and then recovered. Chicks injected with lethal doses showed rapid onset of inactivity, dyspnea and neck droop, and no extended paralysis with survival was seen.

name: Irditoxin subunit B
description: This bird and reptile-specific postsynaptic neurotoxin inhibits the chick muscle alpha-1/beta/gamma/delta (CHRNA1/CHRNB1/CHRNG/CHNRD) -nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) 100-fold more compared with the mouse receptor. In vivo, produces rapid flaccid paralysis, dyspnea and increased respiratory rate in geckos. At sublethal doses geckos were immobilized for up to three days and then recovered. Chicks injected with lethal doses showed rapid onset of inactivity, dyspnea and neck droop, and no extended paralysis with survival was seen.

name: Waprin-Phi2
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Glacontryphan-M
description: Inhibits high (L-type) voltage-activated calcium channels (Cav) in a calcium-dependent manner.

name: Waprin-Phi1
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-As2a
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Basic phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Natriuretic peptide AsNP-a
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Im-1
description: Causes cytolysis by the formation of pores in the membrane. Causes rapid and reversible paralysis in crickets. Has antibacterial activity on the Gram-negative bacterium E.coli (NBRC 3972) (MIC=0.4-0.8 uM), and the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus (NBRC 13276) (MIC=13-25 uM) and B.subtilis (NBRC 3009) (MIC=0.8-1.6 uM).

name: Bactridin-1
description: Shows antibacterial activity against both Gram-positive bacteria (B.subtilis, M.luteus, E.faecalis) and Gram-negative bacteria (P.aeruginosa, Y.enterocolitica, A.calcoaceticus). Modifies membrane sodium permeability on Y.enterocolitica. Is toxic to cockroaches and crabs, but is not to mice. Does not induce haemolysis in human erythrocytes.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Bactridin-2
description: Shows antibacterial activity against both Gram-positive bacteria (B.subtilis, M.luteus, E.faecalis) and Gram-negative bacteria (P.aeruginosa, Y.enterocolitica, A.calcoaceticus). Modifies membrane sodium permeability on Y.enterocolitica. Is toxic to mice, but is not to crabs. Induces concentration dependent haemolysis in human erythrocytes.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 DE-1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snaclec 1
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec 8
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec 27
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec 9
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has high affinity for muscarinic acetylcholine receptors mAChRs (CHRM) and has the ability to activate them. In guinea-pig ileum, produces an onset and dose-dependent contraction. Has also weak anticoagulant activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snaclec 4
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec 7
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PL-X'
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Alpha-fibrinogenase
description: Degrades alpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA), and has strong caseinolytic activity.

name: Disintegrin cerastin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme TLP
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Shows strong hydrolytic activity towards Boc-Asp(oBzl)-Pro-Arg-MCA, a synthetic substrate for thrombin.

name: Muscarinic toxin-like protein 1
description: Antagonist of muscle and neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) with highest affinity for neuronal alpha-7 nAChRs.

name: Cytotoxin 10
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity (By similarity). Has hemolytic activity towards human erythrocytes (EC(50)=0.162 uM) and cytolytic activity towards various cell lines (PubMed:26456928).

name: Cytotoxin 8
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity (By similarity). Has hemolytic activity towards human erythrocytes (EC(50)=0.074 uM) and cytolytic activity towards various cell lines (PubMed:26456928).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (Cav) (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A2 3
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 5
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Toxin Td8
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Td7
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Tz2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Td6
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Td5
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 18.3
description: Probable voltage-gated potassium channel inhibitor.

name: Ardiscretin
description: Inhibits the sodium (Nav) currents in an apparent irreversible manner. Produces small depolarization and induces repetitive firing in squid axons. Is specific for arthropods (crickets, triatomides, crabs and squids), but is non-toxic to mice.

name: Turripeptide PaIAa
description: Is lethal to drosophila larvae.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 18.2
description: Reversibly blocks Shaker B potassium channels.

name: Kunitz-type conkunitzin-S1
description: Blocks specifically voltage-activated potassium channels (Kv) of the Shaker family (IC(50)=1.33 nM).

name: Alpha-conotoxin PeIVB
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin selectively binds to the fetal (alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta subunits) mammalian muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR). It blocks the elicited currents completely and dissociates very slowly from the fetal muscle receptor.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like MIVA
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels (By similarity). This highly potent excitatory peptide elicits repetitive action potentials and causes the same spastic symptomatology as kappa-conotoxin SIVA.

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Natterin-P
description: Shows nociceptive, edema-inducing and kininogenase activity with release of kallidin from low molecular weight kininogen. The cleavage occurs at Met-Lys bonds (By similarity).

name: Galactose-specific lectin nattectin
description: Galactose specific lectin that exhibits hemagglutination activity (minumum hemagluttination concentration= 2.5 ug/well) in a calcium-independent fashion. Has remarkable pro-inflammatory activity, inducing neutrophil mobilization in mice. immune system, especially in neutrophil mobilization in mice.

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB3av
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB3aii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB3aiii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB3aiv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB1av
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB1avi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB3b
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB3ai
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like TSV-DM
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that hydrolyzes the alpha-chain (FGA) and more slowly the beta-chain (FGB) of fibrinogen. Inhibits cell proliferation and induces cell morphologic changes transiently on human umbilical vein endothelial cells.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen- and ADP-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Insect toxin LqhIT5
description: Excitatory insect beta-toxins induce a spastic paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). This toxin is active only on insects. It operates by inducing a fast contraction paralysis without depressant activity. It is more similar to the excitatory toxins in its mode of action and the depressant toxins in its primary structure.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Disintegrin echistatin-alpha
description: Potent inhibitor of ligand binding to the integrins alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3), alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) and alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3). Competition with fibrinogen for the RGD recognition sites on the alpha-IIb/beta-3 integrin (glyco-protein IIb/IIIa complex) results in the inhibition of platelet aggregation and other antithrombotic properties such as an ability to prevent coronary thrombosis in animal models. Is also a potent inhibitor of bone resorption. This results from the blocking of the interaction of alpha-V/beta-3 integrin on the surface of osteoclasts with bone extracellular matrix. In addition, interaction with alpha-V/beta-3 also inhibits adhesion of human umbilical vein endothelial cells (HUVEC) to immobilized vitronectin and fibronectin.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin VMP-II
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: has fibrinolytic activity. The recombinant enzyme cleaves both alpha- (FGA) and beta-chains (FGB) of fibrinogen, but not the gamma-chain. The recombinant protein does not produce hemorrhage in mice and does not have effect on ADP- or collagen-stimulated platelet aggregation.

name: Kappa-sparatoxin-Hv1d
description: Inhibitor of voltage-gated potassium channels of the Kv4/KCND family (By similarity). Blocks calcium channels (Cav).

name: Kappa-sparatoxin-Hv1e
description: Inhibitor of voltage-gated potassium channels of the Kv4/KCND family (By similarity). Blocks calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-sparatoxin-Hv1b
description: Blocks calcium channels (Cav).

name: Toxin AdTx1
description: Orthosteric antagonist of the alpha-1A adrenergic receptor (ADRA1A) with an affinity of 0.35 nM (PubMed:20015090). Has also affinity for ADRA1B > ADRA2C > ADRA1D (PubMed:23935897). Acts as a relaxant of smooth muscle. Reduces prostatic muscle tone as efficiently as tamsulosin (an antagonist presently used), but with fewer cardiovascular side effects (PubMed:23005263).

name: Short neurotoxin 2
description: Blocks both the muscle-twitch response to nerve stimulation and the response to exogenous acetylcholine.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase HR2a: zinc protease that induces hemorrhage.

name: Alpha-toxin Amm8
description: Binds voltage-dependently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin discriminates neuronal versus muscular sodium channel, as it is more potent on rat brain type II sodium channels alpha subunit (SCN2A) than on rat skeletal muscle type IV sodium channels alpha subunit (SCN4A).

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE2iii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE2ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE2i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LcsSicTox-betaIC1
description: Does not have sphingomyelinase but may act on other phosphatidyl esters.

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE4ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE4i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE3ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE3i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspiSicTox-betaIE1i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LafSicTox-betaIE2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Venom metalloproteinase antarease-like TtrivMP_A
description: Acts as a metalloprotease. Penetrates intact tissue and specifically cleaves the vesicle-associated membrane protein 2 (VAMP2) (part of the SNARE complex) involved in pancreatic secretion, thus disrupting the normal vesicular traffic (By similarity).

name: Alpha-colubritoxin
description: Potent postsynaptic neurotoxin. Displays readily reversible competitive antagonism at the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Venom metalloproteinase antarease-like TserMP_B
description: Acts as a metalloprotease. Penetrates intact tissue and specifically cleaves the vesicle-associated membrane protein 2 (VAMP2) (part of the SNARE complex) involved in pancreatic secretion, thus disrupting the normal vesicular traffic (By similarity).

name: Amphiphatic peptide CT1
description: Amphipatic peptide that shows antibacterial activities against both Gram-positive (MIC=10 uM, 20 uM and 20 uM against S.aureus, B.subtilis and S.agalactiae, respectively) and Gram-negative bacteria (MIC=25 uM, 5 uM, and 10 uM against E.coli, S.typhi, and P.aeruginosa, respectively). Is mildly hemolytic against human erythrocytes, with a maximum of 12% lysis, even at the highest concentration tested (50 uM).

name: Amphipathic peptide CT2
description: Amphipatic peptide that shows no antibacterial activity even at 50 uM but shows a low hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes.

name: Amphiphatic peptide CT2
description: Amphipatic peptide that shows antibacterial activities against both Gram-positive (MIC=10 uM, 20 uM and 20 uM against S.aureus, B.subtilis and S.agalactiae, respectively) and Gram-negative bacteria (MIC=20 uM, 10 uM, and 10 uM against E.coli, S.typhi, and P.aeruginosa, respectively). Is mildly hemolytic at its MIC range, but shows a strong cytotoxic activity at higher concentrations, reaching 84% lysis at 50 uM.

name: Amphipathic peptide CT1
description: Amphipatic peptide that shows no antibacterial activity even at 50 uM but shows a low hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes.

name: Kappa-scoloptoxin-Ssm1c
description: Toxin that inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 3
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Bombolitin-1
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snake venom serine protease 3
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Omega-conotoxin MVIID
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin blocks channels of the N-type as well as other types.

name: Snake venom serine proteinase 14
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like 8
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like 2d
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Cytotoxin SP15d
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin SP15c
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin SP15a
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin SP13b
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 1
description: Monomer: shows cytolytic activity.

name: Cytotoxin 1
description: Basic protein that binds to cell membrane and depolarizes cardiomyocytes. It also shows lytic activities on many other cells, including red blood cells. Interaction with sulfatides in the cell membrane induces pore formation and cell internalization and is responsible for cytotoxicity in cardiomyocytes. It targets the mitochondrial membrane and induces mitochondrial swelling and fragmentation (By similarity). It binds to the integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with a moderate affinity and inhibits protein kinases C (PubMed:8448165). It also binds with high affinity to heparin (PubMed:17685633). It also causes skeletal muscle necrosis after intramuscular injection into mice (PubMed:8342169).

name: Snake venom serine protease 2
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1e
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1f
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Cc1a
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin inhibits barium currents (IBa) mediated by L-type voltage-gated calcium channels Cav1.2/CACNA1C (IC(50)=825 nM) and Cav1.3/CACNA1C (IC(50)=2240 nM) (PubMed:24561180).

name: Alpha-latrotoxin-associated low molecular weight protein-2
description: May increase the toxicity of alpha-latrotoxin and/or other venom components. Is non-toxic to mice and to the cockroach Periplaneta americana.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 3
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1b
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 1
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 2
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Hs1f
description: Lethal neurotoxin that blocks neuromuscular transmission.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1g
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Hhn1h
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as slight hemorrhage, induction of platelet aggregation, edema in the mouse paw and bactericidal activity against both Gram-positive (S.aureus) and Gram-negative (E.coli) bacteria. May also induce hemolysis, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, and may have antiparasitic activities. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions.

name: Mast cell degranulating peptide
description: Potent anti-inflammatory agent. At low concentrations, mediates the degranulation of mast cells thus evoking an inflammatory response. Also acts as a neurotoxin capable of blocking a class of voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic activity. Is myotoxic, induces a dose-dependent edema in the mouse foot pad, and exhibits strong anticoagulant effects by binding to factor Xa (F10) and inhibiting the prothrombinase activity (IC(50) is 3 nM).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor TCI
description: Serine protease inhibitor that strongly inhibits chymotrypsin (Ki=84.6 nM) and trypsin (Ki=391 nM).

name: Bradykinin-potentiating and C-type natriuretic peptides
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 5a: modestly inhibits ACE (with highest affinity for the N-site) and reveals strong bradykinin-potentiating activity. Induces nitric oxide (NO) production depended on muscarinic acetylcholine receptor M1 subtype (CHRM1) and bradykinin B2 receptor (BDKRB2) activation. Both these receptors contribute to the vasodilation induced by this peptide that may have an indirect action on BDKRB2 and a direct agonistic action on CHRM1.

name: Snake venom 5'-nucleotidase
description: Hydrolyzes nucleotides into nucleosides (By similarity). Snake venom 5'-nucleotidases are widely distributed among venomous snake taxa, but there is a lack of information about their biological activities. They have been shown to inhibit platelet aggregation. This effect may be due to the liberation of inhibitory AMP or adenosine by its action on ADP released upon initiation of aggregation. Venom 5'-nucleotidases are also known to synergistically act in vivo with other toxins like ADPases, phospholipases, and disintegrins to exert a more pronounced anti-coagulant effect.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids (L-Leu), thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemolysis, edema, hemorrhage, apoptosis, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein natrin-2
description: Inhibits carbachol-induced muscle contraction and weakly blocks muscle contraction evoked by potassium.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme flavoxobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that clots fibrinogen (FGA) by releasing fibrinopeptide A. According to PubMed:8585090, only cleaves rabbit fibrinogen, whereas no specificity is described in PubMed:3910643 (tests done on bovine fibrinogen). Also acts as a C3 convertase that independently cleaves human C3 and kick-starts the complement cascade. Also increases urokinase-type plasminogen activator (PLAU) and plasminogen activator inhibitor (SERPINE1) in cultured bovine pulmonary artery endothelial cells. Dose-dependently inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Alpha-conotoxin Pu14.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. At 1 uM, the synthetic peptide reversibly blocks mammalian nAChR alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta and, to a lesser degree, alpha-6/alpha-3/beta-2, but has no effect on alpha-7. At 10 uM, it reversibly blocks nAChR alpha-3/beta-2, but has no effect on nAChR alpha-3/beta-4, alpha-4/beta-2, alpha-4/beta-4 or alpha-6/alpha-3/beta-4. Intramuscular injection of 10-20 ug of the synthetic peptide in goldfish causes death. Intravenous injection of the same doses in Kunming male mice causes unconsciousness. Does not inhibit potassium channels.

name: Snake venom serine protease ussurase
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease ussurin
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme contortrixobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that cleaves beta chain of fibrinogen (FGB), releasing fibrinopeptide B. Has a coagulant activity activating blood coagulation factors V (F5) and XIII (F13A1).

name: Basic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that does not inhibit platelet aggregation. Exhibits cytotoxic and anticoagulant activity. Induces Ehrlich tumor growth but not angiogenesis. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase barnettlysin-1
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that cleaves a number of protein substrates including fibrinogen and fibronectin.

name: C-type lectin BpLec
description: This lectin displays hemagglutinating activity on dog (128'000 HU/mg) and cat erythrocytes, that is inhibited by beta-galactosides (D-galactose, D-lactose, and N-acetyl-D-galactosamine) and EDTA. In addition, has been shown to hemagglutinate promastigote forms of Leishmania amazonensis. Also inhibits Gram-positive (S.aureus ATCC 25923) (MIC is 31.25 ug/ml) but not Gram-negative (E.coli ATCC 25922) bacteria. Is a calcium-dependent lectin.

name: Lepidopteran-selective toxin
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity). Induces flaccid paralysis in H.virescens larvae. Is not toxic to S.falculata larvae or mice.

name: Contryphan-Fia
description: Inhibits high voltage-activated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Cathelicidin-related peptide Pt_CRAMP2
description: Potent antimicrobial peptide against most of Gram-negative bacteria, some Gram-positive bacteria (Bacillus) and some fungi (C.albicans, P.pastoris, A.terreus, A.nidulans, and C.globosum). Adopts an amphipathic alpha helical conformation, that may allow to partition into the target membrane. No hemolytic and cytotoxic activities have been observed on mammalian cells.

name: Carwaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Stewaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Porwaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Nigwaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Notewaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Notewaprin-b
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit B2
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit B3
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit B1
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hi1a
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hf1a
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hi1c
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hi1b
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Kappa-hexatoxin-Hf1a
description: This excitatory toxin inhibits insect calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channels (Slo-type).

name: Delta-conotoxin-like TxMKLT1-0111
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process.

name: Mu-conotoxin-like PnMKLT1-014
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxO5
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Delta-conotoxin TxVIA
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process. Binding of this toxin is strongly calcium-dependent but not voltage-dependent. The binding site is most likely on the extracellular side of the sodium channel. Binds receptor sites on both mollusk and rat central nervous system, but despite its high affinity binding to rat sodium channel, it has no functional effect in vivo and in vitro on it. Has also no effect on Gambusia fish. Is important in mollusk for the paralysis of the prey. Upon injection of the peptide, a subordinate lobster assumes an exaggerated dominant posture (of a 'King-Kong' lobster!).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxMKLT1-0142
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxMKLT1-0141
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 BmooPLA2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits ADP- and collagen-induced platelet aggregation, has edema-inducing, anti-coagulant activity, antibacterial activity, and cytotoxic activity. In vivo, has a hypotensive effect. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snaclec agglucetin subunit beta-2
description: Agglucetin specifically causes platelet aggregation and surface exposure of integrin alpha-IIb/beta-3 with a GPIb-(GP1BA-) dependent manner in washed platelets. It binds to human platelets in a saturable manner, and its binding is specifically blocked by anti-GP Ib mAb. It regulates endothelial cell survival and promotes angiogenesis by activating integrin alpha-v/beta-3 signaling through FAK/phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase (PI3K)/Akt pathway.

name: Snaclec agglucetin subunit beta-1
description: Agglucetin specifically causes platelet aggregation and surface exposure of integrin alpha-IIb/beta-3 with a GPIb-(GP1BA-) dependent manner in washed platelets. It binds to human platelets in a saturable manner, and its binding is specifically blocked by anti-GP Ib mAb. It regulates endothelial cell survival and promotes angiogenesis by activating integrin alpha-v/beta-3 signaling through FAK/phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase (PI3K)/Akt pathway.

name: Snaclec agglucetin subunit alpha-2
description: Agglucetin specifically causes platelet aggregation and surface exposure of integrin alpha-IIb/beta-3 with a GPIb-(GP1BA-) dependent manner in washed platelets. It binds to human platelets in a saturable manner, and its binding is specifically blocked by anti-GP Ib mAb. It regulates endothelial cell survival and promotes angiogenesis by activating integrin alpha-v/beta-3 signaling through FAK/phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase (PI3K)/Akt pathway.

name: Snaclec mamushigin subunit alpha
description: Binds to platelet GPIbalpha (GP1BA) and enhances platelet aggregation at low-shear stress. At high-shear stress, blocks platelet aggregation in a dose-dependent manner.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 myotoxin III
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays local myotoxic activity and induces a dose-dependent edema. Myotoxic activity is probably related to a molecular region different from the catalytic site, although enzymatic activity greatly enhances myotoxin action. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has high lipolytic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Kappa-conotoxin RIIIJ
description: Kappa-conotoxins inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels. This toxin dose-dependently and reversibly inhibits the Kv1.2/KCNA2 channel in mammalia. Does not exert protective effect on cardiac tissue when administered after an ischemic event.

name: Conantokin-Br
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. This toxin inhibits NR2 subunits N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptor-mediated calcium influx in central nervous system neurons in the following order of preference: NR2B/GRIN2B (IC(50)=0.14 uM), NR2D/GRIN2D (IC(50)=0.31 uM), NR2A/GRIN2A (IC(50)=0.68 uM) and NR2C/GRIN2A (IC(50)=4.9 uM), when tested on rat receptors.

name: Tetrapandin-2
description: Specific inhibitor of store-operated non-voltage-gated calcium channels.

name: Tetrapandin-1
description: Specific inhibitor of store-operated non-voltage-gated calcium channels.

name: Con-Ins G2
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Con-Ins T3
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. It is the smallest known insulin found in nature and lacks the C-terminal segment of the B chain that, in human insulin, mediates engagement of the insulin receptor and assembly of the hormone's hexameric storage form. Despite lacking this segment, it both binds and activates human insulin receptor (B isoform) with only a 10-fold reduced potency. In vivo, intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In addition, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.1
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (mKv1.1/KCNA1 (Kd>25 nM), rKv1.2/KCNA2 (Kd=2 nM), mKv1.3/KCNA3 (Kd=1 nM), hKv1.5/KCNA5 (Kd>25 nM) and mKv3.1/KCNC1 (Kd>25 nM)) and calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa1.1/KCNMA1 and KCa3.1/KCNN4, Kd>25 nM).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 BjIV
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 has a high enzymatic activity and produces moderate myonecrosis in skeletal muscle, but shows no neuromuscular activity in mouse phrenic nerve-diaphragm preparations. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 CC-PLA2-1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits blood coagulation and platelet aggregation induced by ADP and arachidonic acid. Inhibits tumor cell adhesion and migration in a dose-dependent manner. Abolishes the attachment of human brain microvascular endothelial cells (HBMEC) to fibrinogen (IC(50)=0.12 uM) and dramatically reduces it adhesion to fibronectin (IC(50)=0.12 uM), whereas no effect is observed on type I collagen, vitronectin or laminin 1. Also blocks the cell migration toward fibronectin and fibrinogen. These effects are not dependent of the catalytic activity, but are mediated by alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) and alpha-v-containing (ITGAV) integrins. Also shows anti-angiogenic activity in chicken chorioallantoix membrane assay. Has a relatively high enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Its effect on platelets is controversial, since it either induces aggregation or inhibits agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity). This protein induces apoptosis of cultured HeLa cells.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor G1
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Short neurotoxin D1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin E1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Weak neurotoxin D2B
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Weak neurotoxin E3
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Venom protein E2
description: Neurotoxin. Blocks muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR).

name: Melittin
description: Main toxin of bee venom with strong hemolytic activity. Integrates into cell membranes and has multiple effects, probably, as a result of its interaction with negatively charged phospholipids. It inhibits well known transport pumps such as the Na(+)-K(+)-ATPase and the H(+)-K(+)-ATPase. Increases the permeability of cell membranes to ions, particularly Na(+) and indirectly Ca(2+), because of the Na(+)-Ca(2+)-exchange (By similarity).

name: Omega-sparatoxin-Hv1a
description: Blocks calcium channels (Cav).

name: Waprin-Enh1
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Waprin-Phi3
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin
description: Activates the vascular endothelial growth factor receptor-1 (VEGFR-1/FLT1), and consequently promotes the proliferation and tissue factor production of endothelial cells, the neovascularization in the chicken chorioallantoic membrane, and increases vascular permeability. Also stimulates tissue-factor production and human monocyte chemotaxis.

name: Long neurotoxin OH-17
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin-like OH-31
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChRs), whereas it binds with a low affinity to neuronal alpha-7/CHRNA7 nAChRs.

name: Short neurotoxin OH-32
description: This three-finger toxin binds and inhibits the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Short neurotoxin OH-26
description: This three-finger toxin binds and inhibits the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Long neurotoxin OH-34
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Pi-theraphotoxin-Pc1a
description: Potently and selectively blocks the acid-sensing ion channel ASIC1a/ACCN2. The blockade is rapid and reversible. Psalmotoxin 1 loses its capacity to block ASIC1a/ACCN2 as soon as this subunit is associated with another member of the family (ASIC2a/ACCN1 or ASIC3/ACCN3). The toxin can distinguish between the two ASIC1/ACCN2 splice variants ASIC1a/ACCN2 and ASIC1b/ACCN2.

name: Delta-conotoxin EVIA
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels and inhibit the inactivation process. This toxin inhibits sodium channel inactivation in neuronal membranes from amphibians and mammals (Nav1.2a/SCN1A, Nav1.3/SCN3A and Nav1.6/SCN8A) upon binding to receptor site 6.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxO2
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxO1
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Tx2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Tx1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Delta-conotoxin SVIE
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process (By similarity). However, this toxin interacts with a conserved hydrophobic triad (YFV) in the domain-4 voltage sensor of sodium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 10.1
description: Blocks Shaker B (Sh) and voltage-gated potassium-channels Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, Kv1.3/KCNA3. Also inhibits small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCNN) and intermediate conductance calcium-activated potassium channel (KCa3.1/KCNN4).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like SO-4
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin SO-3
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This peptide selectively targets Cav2.2/CACNA1B (IC(50)=160 nM) voltage-gated calcium channels (PubMed:26344359). When tested in mammals, this toxin displays an analgesic potency similar to MVIIA in a range of acute and chronic pain models in rodents, but has less adverse effects (tremor, diminution of spontaneous locomotor activity and bad coordinated locomotion) compared with identical dosages of MVIIA injected intrathecally.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like bothropasin
description: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like bothropasin: has caseinolytic activity. Causes hemorrhage on rabbit skin and causes myonecrosis in mouse tibialis anterior muscle.

name: Fasciculin-2
description: Interferes with neuromuscular transmission by inhibiting the enzyme acetylcholinesterase (AChE) present at the neuromuscular junction. It selectively binds and inhibits with a 1:1 stoichiometry the mammalian and electric fish AChE at picomolar concentrations. It is highly specific for the peripheral site of AChE and blocks the entry of acetylcholine into the active site of the enzyme (through the Met-33 residue), thereby preventing its breakdown. It has been called fasciculin since after injection into mice it causes severe, generalized and long-lasting (5-7 hours) fasciculations.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 2.2
description: OmTx1 decreases the amplitude of the potassium current of the rat channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 by 17% and Kv1.2/KCNA2 by 12% as well as human Kv1.3/KCNA3 by 24%.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 2.3
description: Decreases the amplitude of the potassium current of the rat channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 by 33% and Kv1.2/KCNA2 by 8% as well as human Kv1.3/KCNA3 by 70%.

name: Natterin-2
description: Shows nociceptive, edema-inducing and kininogenase activity with release of kallidin from low molecular weight kininogen. The cleavage occurs at Met-Lys bonds.

name: Natterin-1
description: Shows nociceptive, edema-inducing and kininogenase activity with release of kallidin from low molecular weight kininogen. The cleavage occurs at Met-Lys bonds.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase kistomin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that inhibits platelet aggregation by binding specifically to platelet glycoprotein VI (GP6) and platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha (GP1BA). It inhibits the interaction between collagen and platelet GP6 by cleaving GP6 (at '225-Glu-|-Ala-226' and '238-Val-|-Phe-239' bonds), and inhibits vWF-induced platelet aggregation by cleaving GP1BA and vWF. Cleavage of GP1BA occurs at two distinct sites to generate two soluble fragments. It also cleaves alpha- (FGA) and subsequently the gamma-chain (FGG) of fibrinogen, leaving the beta-chain unaffected. It also inhibits collagen-, convulxin- and ristocetin-induced platelet aggregation. It blocks the adhesion of platelet to immobilized collagen, but only exerts a slight inhibition to fibrinogen. In vivo, it exerts potent antithrombotic effect.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like 289
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like 291
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like Ai6.2
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like Ai6.3
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: C-type lectin lectoxin-Enh5
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Alkaline phosphatase
description: Has hemorrhagic activity.

name: C-type lection lectoxin-Enh3
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: C-type lectin lectoxin-Enh4
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like 2/7
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1f
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1d
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Gamma-conotoxin-like TxMEKL-0511
description: Gamma-conotoxins may act on voltage-gated non-specific cation pacemaker channels (HCN).

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 trimucrotoxin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays edema-inducing activities, as well as presynaptic neurotoxicity and low myotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Alpha-mammal toxin BmK-M8
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This acidic toxin has a weak toxicity and is active against mammals.

name: L-amino acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids (highly against L-Met, L-Leu, L-Phe and L-Ile), thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as antibacterial on both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and antiparasitic activities, as well as induction of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions. This protein may also have activities in hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, and apoptosis.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 nigexine
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows anticoagulant activity, has cytotoxic activity and affects neuromuscular transmission in vitro. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Long neurotoxin LNTX-2 homolog
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Haditoxin
description: Antagonist of muscle (alpha/beta/gamma/delta) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2, alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2) nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) with highest affinity for alpha-7 nAChRs.

name: Venom nerve growth factor 1
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems.
