name: Acidic phospholipase A2 Cvv-E6c
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that significantly inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation in platelet-rich plasma of human, rabbit and guinea pig. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snaclec A2
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1aiii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Snaclec dabocetin subunit alpha
description: Inhibits ristocetin-induced platelet aggregation via binding to platelet glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA).

name: Antimicrobial peptide HsAp3
description: Possesses antimicrobial activity against both Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria, as well as against the fungus C.tropicalis. Also possesses a relatively high hemolytic activity.

name: Toxin Boma6e
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor microlepidin-3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Toxin Boma6a
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Maurocalcin
description: Potently and reversibly modifies channel gating behavior of the type 1 ryanodine receptor (RYR1) by inducing prominent subconductance behavior. Binds a different site as ryanodine.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor microlepidin-4
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Toxin Boma6b
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Opicalcin-2
description: Potently and reversibly modifies channel gating behavior of the type 1 ryanodine receptor (RYR1) by inducing prominent subconductance behavior. Binds a different site as ryanodine (By similarity).

name: Antimicrobial peptide HsAp1
description: Possesses antimicrobial activity against both Gram-negative (MIC between 23.8 and 51.2 uM) and Gram-positive (MIC between 11.8 and 46.5 uM) bacteria, as well as against the fungus C.tropicalis (MIC of 48.6 uM). Also possesses a relatively high hemolytic activity.

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin BmKITb
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. However, this toxin has some characteristics of excitatory toxins such as bursts of activity after the membrane has been hyperpolarized. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Cytotoxin Vc-5
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like ecarin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that catalyzes the conversion of prothrombin (F2) to alpha-thrombin through formation of a thrombin intermediate. Has a low Km for prothrombin and a high kcat. Cleaves the 320-Arg-Ile-321 bond in prothrombin and produces meizothrombin which is ultimately converted to alpha-thrombin by autolysis.

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hv2a
description: Potent inhibitor of insect (bee brain), but not mammalian (rat trigeminal neurons), voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). As for omega-AcTx-Hv1a, the phenotypic effect of injection of this toxin into lone star ticks (Amblyomma americanum) is curling of all eight legs into closed loops, followed by death.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 1.2
description: Voltage-gated potassium channel blocker.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 1.1
description: Slows the activation kinetics of Kv1.3/KCNA3 currents, and blocks Kv1.3/KCNA3 and Kv1.2/KCNA2 potassium channels. This block is dose-dependent, voltage-independent, and reversible.

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog nigroviriditoxin acidic subunit A
description: Heterodimer A-B: Nigroviriditoxin possesses phospholipase A2 (PLA2) activity. It consists of a non-covalent association of a basic PLA2 subunit B with a non-enzymatic subunit A.

name: Neurotoxin Nk-3FTx
description: Possible voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) blocker. Decreases amplitude of compound action potential and conduction velocity in toad sciatic nerve. Has only mild anticoagulant activity even at a concentration of 5ug/ml. Shows no cytotoxicity towards human cell lines.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.17
description: Blocks human voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 (IC(50)=4.8 nM) and Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=2.9 nM).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.16
description: Blocks human voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=0.7 nM), Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=26.2 nM) and blocks intermediate conductance calcium-activated potassium channel KCa3.1/KCNN4 (IC(50)=56 nM).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.15
description: Blocks human voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=0.3 nM), Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=8.3 nM) and Shaker IR (with inactivation domain removed) (IC(50)=12 nM) and blocks intermediate conductance calcium-activated potassium channel KCa3.1/KCNN4 (IC(50)=6.4 nM).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 10.4
description: Blocks human voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=3.6 nM) and Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=72 nM).

name: Potassium channel gamma toxin gamma-KTx 1.9
description: Blocks human voltage-gated potassium channel Kv11.1/KCNH2/ERG1 (IC(50)=16.9 nM).

name: Natriuretic peptide TNP-b
description: Exhibits vasoactive (PubMed:15652496) and hypotensive activity (By similarity). Is only weakly active on natriuretic peptide receptor-C (NPR3).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 BthA-1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that induces edema (activity that is inhibited by EDTA and dexamethasone), inhibits phospholipid-dependent collagen/ADP-induced platelet aggregation, possess hypotensive as well as anticoagulant activities. In addition, this enzyme shows bactericidal activity against E.coli and S.aureus. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2j 2
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2j 1
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2l
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2k
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2a 3
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) with an IC(50) of 1.1 nM. Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels.

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2a 2
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) with an IC(50) of 1.1 nM. Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels.

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2a 5
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) with an IC(50) of 1.1 nM. Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels.

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2a 4
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) with an IC(50) of 1.1 nM. Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels.

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2n
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Mu-theraphotoxin-Hhn2m
description: Lethal neurotoxin. Selectively blocks tetrodotoxin-sensitive voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Does not affect tetrodotoxin-resistant voltage-gated sodium channels or calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase catroxase
description: Metalloprotease that is highly active against alpha-(FGA) and beta-chains (FGB) of fibrinogen molecules.

name: Hainantoxin-XVIII-2
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U3-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a 7
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Hainantoxin-XVIII
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: BmKBT-like peptide
description: Sodium channel inhibitor (By similarity). Possess potent toxicity in mice but induces only paralysis in cotton bollworm.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as antibacterial activity against both Gram-positive (B.subtilis) and Gram-negative (E.coli) bacteria, and inhibition of ADP- or collagen-induced platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions. This protein may also induce hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis, and have antiparasitic activities.

name: Iota-conotoxin-like L11.5
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like Fi11.6
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Iota-conotoxin-like Fi11.8
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog 4a
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that shows myotoxic activities.

name: Kappa-conotoxin SrXIA
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels. This toxin inhibits Kv1.2/KCNA2 and Kv1.6/KCNA6. Produces stiffening of body, limbs and tail when injected intracranially into mice.

name: Cathelicidin-related peptide crotalicidin
description: Potent antimicrobial peptide against Gram-negative (MIC=0.25 ug/mL against E.coli ATCC 25922, MIC=1 ug/mL against P.aeruginosa) and Gram-positive bacteria (MIC=32 ug/mL against E.faecalis, MIC=32 ug/mL against S.aureus) (PubMed:25100358). Adopts an amphipathic alpha helical conformation, that may allow to partition into the target membrane (By similarity). Low hemolytic activities have been observed on mammalian cells (PubMed:25100358).

name: Phospholipase A2 isozymes PA3A/PA3B/PA5
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Neurotoxin BmK AGP-SYPU1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). This toxin has a strong analgesic effect when administered to mice by intraperitoneal injection.

name: Alpha-insect toxin BjaIT
description: Binds voltage-dependently at site-3 of sodium channels and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin is active against insects (para/tipE).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like VnMKLT1-0111
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Conotoxin Asi14a
description: May have neurotoxic activities (Probable). Does not show any effect on voltage-gated potassium channels (10 uM of toxin tested), and on nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (5 uM of toxin tested) (PubMed:27801785). Does not show antibacterial activity on both Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria (PubMed:27801785).

name: Conotoxin Asi3a
description: Does not show any effect on voltage-gated sodium and potassium channels (10 uM of toxin tested), and on nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (5 uM of toxin tested) (PubMed:27801785). Does not show antibacterial activity on both Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria (PubMed:27801785). Intraperitoneal injection into fish provokes paralysis (By similarity).

name: Conorfamide-Vc1
description: This peptide causes an increase in cytosolic calcium in a specific subset of DRG neurons, and, in contrast to other Conus venom peptides, the peptide also affects a large fraction of the non-neuronal cells. In vivo, when intracranially injected into mice, it principally induces twiching limbs and hyperactivity (climbing and jumping at high frequency).

name: Conantokin-Gm
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors.

name: Conantokin-Ca2
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors.

name: Conantokin-Qu
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors.

name: Conotoxin AusB
description: Does not show any effect on voltage-gated sodium, potassium channels, and on nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (10 uM of toxin tested) (PubMed:27801785). Does not show antibacterial activity on both Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria (PubMed:27801785).

name: Conotoxin Lo6/7b
description: 1 uM of this toxin does not show any effect on voltage-gated sodium and potassium channels. Does not show antibacterial activity on both Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria (PubMed:27801785).

name: Conotoxin Lo6/7a
description: 1 uM of this toxin does not show any effect on voltage-gated sodium and potassium channels (PubMed:27801785). Shows a turbid zone of antibacterial activity against the Gram-positive strain Bacillus megaterium (ATCC13632), but does not show antibacterial activity against other Gram-positive bacteria, and on Gram-negative bacteria (PubMed:27801785).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like EpI
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This peptide blocks mammalian nicotinic acetylcholine receptors composed of alpha-3/beta-2 and alpha-3/beta-4 subunits.

name: Alpha-conotoxin AuIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin blocks mammalian nAChR alpha-3/beta-4 subunits.

name: Kappa-conotoxin PVIIA
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv). This toxin inhibits the Shaker channel from insects. The interaction site between the Shaker channel and this toxin is within the S5-S6 loop of the Shaker channel. In fish, this toxin induces hyperactivity, followed by continuous contraction and extension of major fins, without immobilization or death. Injection of this peptide together with the delta-conotoxin PVIA causes the sudden tetanus of prey (STOP) syndrome, which is a single, lethal "fin-pop" in envenomed fish. In mice, induces hyperactivity.

name: Alpha-conotoxin MII
description: Alpha-conotoxins bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and inhibit them. This toxin blocks neuronal mammalian nAChRs (alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-2-beta-3 > alpha-3-beta-2 > alpha-3-beta-4 = alpha-4-beta-2).

name: Beta-insect excitatory toxin Bj-xtrIT
description: Excitatory insect toxins induce a spastic paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Natriuretic peptide TNP-b
description: Exhibits vasoactive (PubMed:15652496) and hypotensive activity (By similarity). Is only weakly active on natriuretic peptide receptor-C (NPR3).

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Lc2c
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChRs), whereas it binds with a low affinity to neuronal alpha-7/CHRNA7 nAChRs.

name: U17-barytoxin-Tl1b
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1c
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Calglandulin
description: May be involved in the cellular control mechanism of the secretion of toxins from the gland into the venom.

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1b
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Toxin ICK-21
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Delta-conotoxin-like ErVIA
description: This toxin activates voltage-gated sodium channels. It shifts the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized potentials but has only little effect on channel inactivation. It is active on Nav1.3/SCN3A (EC(50)=3.98 nM), Nav1.4/SCN4A (EC(50)=4.99 nM), Nav1.6/SCN8A (EC(50)=1.27 nM) and Nav1.7/SCN9A (EC(50)=2.42 nM) voltage-gated sodium channels. In vivo, it induces nocifensive or pain-like behaviors in mice when injected intraplantarly.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor As-fr-19
description: May exert inhibitory effects on serine proteases and on potassium and/or calcium channels and then participate in the long-term non-lethal paralysis on the prey.

name: Basic phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like AnIC
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ca1.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin AnIB
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. Synthetic AnIB blocks mammalian alpha-3/beta-2 nAChRs (IC(50)=0.3 nM) and alpha-7 nAChRs (IC(50)=76 nM). Synthetic AnIA blocks mammalian alpha-3/beta-2 nAChRs (IC(50)=0.2 nM).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin PMMP-2
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin PMMP-1
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like mocarhagin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that inhibits platelet aggregation by cleaving platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha (GP1BA) at Glu-298/Asp-299, and abolishes binding of von Willebrand factor (VWF) to GPIBA. Cleaves P-selectin glycoprotein ligand-1 (PSGL-1/SELPLG) at Tyr-51/Asp-52, and completely abolishes the binding of PSGL-1 to P-selectin. Anionic amino acid sequences containing sulfated tyrosines are needed for cleavages. Inhibits the thrombin-induced platelet aggregation, and the thrombin-induced release of ATP and ADP. Has lectin activity (inhibited by heparin).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Exendin-3
description: Stimulates vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP) receptors in high concentrations (>100 nM), resulting in both an increase in cAMP and amylase secretion from pancreatic acini, although at low concentrations (between 0.3 and 3 nM) it increases cAMP without stimulating amylase release. Stimulates the GLP-1 receptor (GLP1R). Induces hypotension that is mediated by relaxation of cardiac smooth muscle.

name: Alpha-conotoxin GIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. The higher affinity site for alpha-conotoxin GI is the alpha/delta site on mouse muscle-derived BC3H-1 receptor, and the other site (alpha/gamma site) on nicotinic receptors from Torpedo californica electric organ.

name: Crabrolin
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Induces the chemotaxis of neutrophils. Has antimicrobial and hemolytic activity.

name: Mastoparan-J
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins that couple to phospholipase C.

name: Mastoparan-C
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins that couple to phospholipase C.

name: Mastoparan-X
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins that couple to phospholipase C.

name: Mastoparan-L
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins that couple to phospholipase C. May be able to switch from an in-plane to a transmembrane orientation in lipid bilayers.

name: Snaclec carinactivase-1 regulatory subunit 17 kDa chain
description: Calcium-dependent prothrombin activator. This protein may activate prothrombin via recognition by the regulatory subunit of the calcium ion bound conformation of its gamma-carboxyglutamic acid (GLA) domain, and the subsequent conversion of prothrombin to active thrombin is catalyzed by the catalytic subunit.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase carinactivase-1 catalytic subunit
description: Calcium-dependent prothrombin (F2) activator. This protein may activate prothrombin via recognition by the regulatory subunit of the calcium ion bound conformation of its gamma-carboxyglutamic acid (GLA) domain, and the subsequent conversion of prothrombin to active thrombin is catalyzed by the catalytic subunit.

name: Snaclec carinactivase-1 regulatory subunit 14 kDa chain
description: Calcium-dependent prothrombin activator. This protein may activate prothrombin via recognition by the regulatory subunit of the calcium ion bound conformation of its gamma-carboxyglutamic acid (GLA) domain, and the subsequent conversion of prothrombin to active thrombin is catalyzed by the catalytic subunit.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme LMR-47
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that specifically hydrolyzes the Aalpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA). Exhibits strong N-p-tosyl-L-arginine methyl esterase activity, and hydrolyzes tripeptide nitroanilide derivatives weakly or not at all.

name: Mu-agatoxin-Aa1d
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons.

name: Cytotoxin homolog
description: Has low cytotoxic activity.

name: Snake venom serine proteinase 4a
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Putative lysosomal acid lipase/cholesteryl ester hydrolase
description: In physiological conditions, is crucial for intracellular hydrolysis of cholesteryl esters and triglycerides that have been internalized via receptor-mediated endocytosis of lipoprotein particles. In venom, the biological contribution is unknown.

name: Toxin aagardi
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme bhalternin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that induces blood clotting in vitro, defibrinogenation in vivo (by intraperitoneal injection into mice), albuminolytic and fibrinogenolytic activities. Preferentially cleaves the alpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA). Causes hemolysis in the heart, causes apparent hyperemia and lymphocytic interstitial pneumonitis in the lung, causes necrosis and inflammatory infiltrate in the liver, and causes glomerular congestion in the kidney. Also provokes a drastic myonecrosis.

name: Phospholipase D LlSicTox-alphaIII-1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LiSicTox-alphaI-1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: U20-lycotoxin-Ls1a
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme stejnobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that has fibrinogen-clotting activity (FGA or FGB).

name: Alpha- and beta-fibrinogenase stejnefibrase-1
description: Snake venom serine protease. Degrades concomitantly alpha- (FGA) and beta-chains of fibrinogen (FGB).

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit A
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Snaclec A7
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec A15
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec A9
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec A8
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1x
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Hainantoxin-XVIII-7
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: Hainantoxin-XVIII-6
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like HR1b
description: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like HR1b: zinc protease that induces hemorrhage.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Conotoxin im23.3
description: Neurotoxin that induces excitatory symptoms in mice following intracranial administration. No symptoms are observed after intraperitoneal and intravenous (tail vein) injections (By similarity).

name: Conotoxin im23a
description: Neurotoxin that induces excitatory symptoms in mice following intracranial administration. No symptoms are observed after intraperitoneal and intravenous (tail vein) injections.

name: Conotoxin im23b
description: Neurotoxin that induces excitatory symptoms in mice following intracranial administration. No symptoms are observed after intraperitoneal and intravenous (tail vein) injections.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 A
description: Snake venom phospholipase A that has strong antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacterium X.axonopodis. Antimicrobial activity is not abolished by EDTA or p-BPB and is therefore not strongly dependent on the enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hi2b
description: Potent inhibitor of insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx34.5
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Bm12-b
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LlSicTox-alphaIII2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin (228.2 U/mg). May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. May induce complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation.

name: Con-Ins F1
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Bs2a
description: Has minor, but significant effects on the Para/tipE insect sodium channel.

name: Con-Ins T2
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. It is the smallest known insulin found in nature and lacks the C-terminal segment of the B chain that, in human insulin, mediates engagement of the insulin receptor and assembly of the hormone's hexameric storage form. Despite lacking this segment, it both binds and activates human insulin receptor (B isoform) with only a 10-fold reduced potency. In vivo, intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In addition, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Con-Ins G1
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock (PubMed:25605914, PubMed:27617429). It is the smallest known insulin found in nature and lacks the C-terminal segment of the B chain that, in human insulin, mediates engagement of the insulin receptor and assembly of the hormone's hexameric storage form (PubMed:27617429). Despite lacking this segment, it both binds and activates human insulin receptor (B isoform) with only a 10-fold reduced potency (PubMed:27617429). In vivo, intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin (PubMed:25605914). In addition, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency (PubMed:25605914).

name: Disintegrin viridistatin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin atroxatin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like catroriarin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like viristiarin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Kappa-ctenitoxin-Pn1a
description: Antagonist of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1). In GH3 cells, it reversibly inhibits the A-type potassium current but does not block other potassium currents or calcium channels. Causes paralysis in the posterior limbs and gradual decreases in movement and aggression during 24 hours at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse.

name: Omega-ctenitoxin-Pn1a
description: Antagonist of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1). Induces immediate clockwise gyration and flaccid paralysis after 6 hours at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like Ac6.5
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like Ac6.4
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Sm1.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Pu1.6
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Mu-conotoxin-like SxIIIB
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: Mu-conotoxin SxIIIA
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). This synthetic toxin potently blocks rNav1.4/SCN4A. It also moderately blocks rNav1.1/SCN1A, rNav1.2/SCN2A, and mNav1.6/SCN6A. When injected intraperitoneally or subcutaneously in mice, it causes motor impairment/paralysis and is lethal at doses as low as 0.6 nmol per mouse.

name: Delta-conotoxin-like Ac6.1
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Vn
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Delta-conotoxin-like Ac6.3
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process.

name: Delta-conotoxin-like Ac6.2
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process.

name: Snaclec trimecetin subunit alpha
description: Snaclec that induces platelet aggregation in either human platelet rich plasma (PRP) or washed platelet suspensions. It causes aggregation in a dose-dependent manner even in the absence of various platelet agonists such as ADP or von Willebrand factor (vWF). Interestingly, it does not induce aggregation in rabbit PRP. A monoclonal antibody against the platelet GPIb receptor blocks the aggregation induced by trimecetin, suggesting that it acts by binding to GPIb (GP1BA/GP1BB).

name: Snaclec trimecetin subunit beta
description: Snaclec that induces platelet aggregation in either human platelet rich plasma (PRP) or washed platelet suspensions. It causes aggregation in a dose-dependent manner even in the absence of various platelet agonists such as ADP or von Willebrand factor (vWF). Interestingly, it does not induce aggregation in rabbit PRP. A monoclonal antibody against the platelet GPIb receptor blocks the aggregation induced by trimecetin, suggesting that it acts by binding to GPIb (GP1BA/GP1BB).

name: Natriuretic peptide BF131
description: Natriuretic peptide that dose-dependently induces the rapid relaxation of rat aortic strips phenylephrine-precontracted. Acts by stimulating cGMP production in a dose-dependent manner. Does not inhibits platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Venom nerve growth factor 2
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Omega-lycotoxin-Gsp2671c
description: Modulates P-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) in rat cerebellar Purkinje cells and hippocampal CA1-CA3 neurons. At saturating concentrations (>10 nM) the toxin decelerates activation kinetics and slightly increases peak amplitude without affecting deactivation kinetics (By similarity).

name: Omega-lycotoxin-Gsp2671b
description: Modulates P-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) in rat cerebellar Purkinje cells and hippocampal CA1-CA3 neurons. At saturating concentrations (>10 nM) the toxin decelerates activation kinetics and slightly increases peak amplitude without affecting deactivation kinetics (By similarity).

name: Omega-lycotoxin-Gsp2671g
description: Modulates P-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) in rat cerebellar Purkinje cells and hippocampal CA1-CA3 neurons. At saturating concentrations (>10 nM) the toxin decelerates activation kinetics and slightly increases peak amplitude without affecting deactivation kinetics (By similarity).

name: Omega-lycotoxin-Gsp2671d
description: Modulates P-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) in rat cerebellar Purkinje cells and hippocampal CA1-CA3 neurons. At saturating concentrations (>10 nM) the toxin decelerates activation kinetics and slightly increases peak amplitude without affecting deactivation kinetics (By similarity).

name: Omega-lycotoxin-Gsp2671e
description: Modulates P-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) in rat cerebellar Purkinje cells and hippocampal CA1-CA3 neurons. At saturating concentrations (>10 nM) the toxin decelerates activation kinetics and slightly increases peak amplitude without affecting deactivation kinetics (By similarity).

name: Omega-lycotoxin-Gsp2671f
description: Modulates P-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) in rat cerebellar Purkinje cells and hippocampal CA1-CA3 neurons. At saturating concentrations (>10 nM) the toxin decelerates activation kinetics and slightly increases peak amplitude without affecting deactivation kinetics (By similarity).

name: Omega-agatoxin-Aa4b
description: Antagonist of voltage-gated Cav2.1/CACNA1A (P-type) calcium channels. Paralyzes insect by blocking neuromuscular transmission.

name: Conotoxin mr3f
description: Intracranially injection into mice does not elicit symptoms.

name: Conotoxin mr3c
description: Intracranially injection into mice does not elicit symptoms.

name: Protease inhibitor 3
description: Snake venom serine protease inhibitor.

name: Protease inhibitor 1
description: Snake venom serine protease inhibitor.

name: Protease inhibitor 4
description: Snake venom serine protease inhibitor.

name: Protease inhibitor 2
description: Snake venom serine protease inhibitor.

name: Putative conotoxin
description: Acts as a neurotoxin.

name: U2-agatoxin-Aop1a
description: Insect-selective toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. Suppresses the excitatory postsynaptic potentials evoked in lobster neuromuscular synaptic preparations, possibly by blocking the presynaptic calcium channel (Cav). Induces instantaneous reversible paralysis when injected into crickets.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like ohanin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that has hemorrhagic activity. Inhibits ADP-, TMVA- and stejnulxin-induced platelet aggregation in a dose-dependent manner (on washed platelet, but not on platelet rich plasm). Also specifically degrades alpha-chain of fibrinogen (FGA).

name: Omega-conotoxin SVIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin SVIB
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin blocks N-, P- and Q-type calcium channels.

name: Neurotoxin BTN
description: Inhibits sodium channels (Nav).

name: Kappa-hexatoxin-Hv1d
description: This excitatory toxin inhibits insect calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channels (Slo-type).

name: Insect toxin TbIT-1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). This toxin is only active against insects.

name: Alpha-conotoxin GID
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin reversibly blocks alpha-3-beta-2 (IC(50)=3.1-5.1 nM), alpha-7 (IC(50)=4.5-5.1 nM), and alpha-4-beta-2 (IC(50)=128.6-390 nM) nAChRs.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Gr2a
description: Blocks mammalian Kv4.2/KCND2 and Kv4.3/KCND3 (By similarity). Blocks mechanosensitive ion channels in rat astrocytes, without having effect on whole-cell voltage-sensitive currents.

name: U2-hexatoxin-Hi1a
description: Inhibits sodium channels (Nav) of insects.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor C6
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Insectotoxin-I5
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor C4
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor C3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor C2
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits plasmin and trypsin.

name: Amphipathic peptide CT2
description: Antimicrobial peptide that is rapidly bactericidal against Gram-positive bacteria.

name: Snake venom serine protease BmSP
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Alpha- and beta-fibrinogenase OhS1
description: Snake venom serine protease that possesses potent fibrinogenolytic (on both alpha- (FGA) and beta-chains (FGB)) and amidolytic activities.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: Snake venom serine protease NaSP
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids (highly active against L-Tyr, L-Asp, L-Phe, L-Glu, L-Trp, L-His, L-Gln, L-Ile, L-Met, L-Leu and moderately active against L-Lys, L-Arg, L-Ala and L-Asn), thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as edema, inflammatory cell infiltration, cytotoxicity and apoptosis, as well as induction of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions. This protein may also induce hemorrhage, hemolysis, and have antibacterial and antiparasitic activities.

name: Mastoparan-like peptide 12d
description: Shows mast cell degranulation and antimicrobial activities against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=3.0 ug/ml), the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus ATCC 2592 (MIC=1.5 ug/ml) and the fungus C.albicans ATCC 2002 (MIC=12.0 ug/ml).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like NaMP
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that inhibits platelet aggregation and degrades fibrinogen.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities (By similarity). This protein induces platelet aggregation by both hydrogen peroxide production and binding to platelet membrane proteins (that would enhance the sensitivity of platelets to hydrogen peroxide). Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions.

name: Natriuretic peptide Mf-NP
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Secapin
description: Nontoxic component of honeybee venom.

name: Omega-conotoxin CVIC
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin blocks N-, P- and Q-type calcium channels.

name: Omega-conotoxin CVIB
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin blocks N-, P- and Q-type calcium channels.

name: Snaclec agkicetin-C subunit alpha
description: Is a potent glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA) antagonist. Concentration-dependently inhibits botrocetin-, ristocetin- and low dose thrombin-induced platelet aggregation. Inhibits platelet adhesion only through inhibiting the vWF interaction with GP1BA, but has minimal effect on other platelet receptors, such as alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) or alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1). Causes an instant severe thrombocytopenia in rats and is not lethal to mice.

name: Snaclec agkicetin-C subunit beta
description: Is a potent glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA) antagonist. Concentration-dependently inhibits botrocetin-, ristocetin- and low dose thrombin-induced platelet aggregation. Inhibits platelet adhesion only through inhibiting the vWF interaction with GP1BA, but has minimal effect on other platelet receptors, such as alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) or alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1). Causes an instant severe thrombocytopenia in rats and is not lethal to mice.

name: Mu-diguetoxin-Dc1a
description: Insecticidal toxin (PubMed:8541888, PubMed:8896202). This toxin promotes opening of insect Nav channels. The toxin binds to the S1-S2 and S3-S4 loops in the domain II voltage-sensor of insect Nav channels (i.e., receptor site 4). The American cockroach P.americana is largely resistant to the effects of this toxin due to an unusual sequence within the domain II S1-S2 loop. In vivo, paralyzes lepidopteran and dipteran larvae. Paralyzed insects ultimately die from secondary effects of starvation and dehydration (PubMed:25014760).

name: Delta-conotoxin PVIA
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process. In mice, injection of this toxin causes hyperactivity, rapid running, limb extension, and death. In fish, the peptide elicites spurts of rapid swimming, with twisted motions, quivering fins and the lockjaw extended mouth syndrome. Rigid paralysis and death are observed at higher doses. In mollusks, this peptide is inactive. Injection of this peptide together with the kappa-conotoxin PVIIA causes the sudden tetanus of prey (STOP) syndrome, which is a single, lethal "fin-pop" in envenomed fish.

name: Alpha-latrotoxin-associated low molecular weight protein
description: May increase the toxicity of alpha-latrotoxin and/or other venom components. Is non-toxic to mice and to the cockroach Periplaneta americana.

name: Omega-conotoxin TVIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin RVIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin CVIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels. This toxin blocks N-type calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like CnVIIH
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin blocks N-type calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B), but unexpectedly, does not show any blocking activity at amphibian neuromuscular junction. Causes shaking activity, and, at higher doses, causes mild tremors when injected intracerebroventricularly into mice. Causes paralysis, and, at higher doses, causes death when injected intramuscularly into fish.

name: Phospholipase D LrSicTox-alphaIA1ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin and of a broad range of lysophospholipids, like LPI (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylinositol), LPG (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylglycerol), LPE (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylethanolamine), LBPA (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysobisphosphatidic acid), LPS (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylserine) and LPCs (lysophophatidylcholesterols) of varying chain lengths. The substrate preference is LPI > LPG > LPS > LPC >> LPE, LBPA. Furthermore, the enzyme also hydrolyzes cyclic phosphatidic acid to LPA. The enzyme does not hydrolyze SPC (sphingosylphosphorylcholine, also known as lyso-sphingomyelin). Does not exhibit detectable PLA1/2 activity. Induces dose-dependent hemolysis and dermonecrosis.

name: Phospholipase D LrSicTox-alphaIA1i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin and of a broad range of lysophospholipids, like LPI (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylinositol), LPG (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylglycerol), LPE (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylethanolamine), LBPA (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysobisphosphatidic acid), LPS (18:1-1-oleoyl-lysophosphatidylserine) and LPCs (lysophophatidylcholesterols) of varying chain lengths. The substrate preference is LPI > LPG > LPS > LPC >> LPE, LBPA. Furthermore, the enzyme also hydrolyzes cyclic phosphatidic acid to LPA. The enzyme does not hydrolyze SPC (sphingosylphosphorylcholine, also known as lyso-sphingomyelin). Does not exhibit detectable PLA1/2 activity. Induces dose-dependent hemolysis and dermonecrosis (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin SIIIB
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (VGSC). Potently displaces (125)I-TIIIA from native rat brain Nav1.2/SCN2A (IC(50) is 5 nM) and muscle Nav1.4/SCN4A (IC(50) is 3 nM) VGSCs. Potently and irreversibly inhibits current through Xenopus oocyte-expressed Nav1.2/SCN2A and Nav1.4/SCN4A.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like SmIVB
description: Kappa-A-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like SmIVA
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Alpha-conotoxin BnIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin inhibits acetylcholine-evoked currents reversibly in oocytes expressing the human alpha-7 nAChR, and blocks nerve-evoked skeletal muscle contractions in isolated mouse neuromuscular preparations, but with a very low affinity.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PLA-N
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays edema-inducing activities, as well as presynaptic neurotoxicity and myotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Potassium channel toxin Hge-beta-KTx
description: The full peptide presents antibacterial and cytotoxic activities. The C-terminus (33-76aa) blocks potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, and Kv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Hge-scorpine
description: Hge-scorpine has antibacterial activity against B.subtilis, but not against S.aureus. Also has hemolytic and cytolytic activities.

name: Potassium channel toxin TdiKIK
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin TcoKIK
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin TtrKIK
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin Tdi-beta-KTx
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin Ttr-beta-KTx
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PeBP(R)-I/II
description: Snake venom phospholipases A2 that have myotoxic, and edema-inducing activity, as well as extremely weak lipolytic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PePLA2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snake venom serine proteinase 5
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6.14
description: Blocks Shaker B channels expressed in Sf9 cells, with a dissociation constant of 52 nM.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1e
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1f
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1f
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1g
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1c
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1d
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Probable weak neurotoxin NNAM1
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Probable weak neurotoxin NNAM3
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1h
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Snake venom serine protease pallabin-2
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Probable weak neurotoxin NNAM2
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Toxin To6
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 A'
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Vespakinin-X
description: Bradykinins are a potent but short-lived agent of arteriolar dilation and increased capillary permeability (By similarity). May target bradykinin receptors (BDKRB). May cause hypotension.

name: Vespakinin-M
description: Bradykinins are a potent but short-lived agent of arteriolar dilation and increased capillary permeability (By similarity). May target bradykinin receptors (BDKRB). May cause hypotension.

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB1bii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Venom protein 13a
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide with hemolytic activity. Exhibits potent chemotactic activity for polymorphonucleated leukocytes (PMNL).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB1aii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB1ai
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIB1b
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIB1c
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LapSicTox-alphaIB1b3
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.1.2h
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.1.2g
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.1.2f
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin-like Cal 12.1.2e
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB1aiii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).
