description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Inactive hyaluronidase B
description: Has no hyaluronidase activity.

name: U32-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U32-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U31-theraphotoxin-Cg1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U31-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U30-theraphotoxin-Cg1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U30-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U29-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Alpha-conotoxin BuIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and inhibit them. This peptide potently blocks numerous mammalian nAChR subtypes: alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-2 (IC(50)=0.258 nM) > alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-4 (IC(50)=1.54 nM) > alpha-3-beta-2 (IC(50)=5.72 nM) > alpha-3-beta-4 (IC(50)=27.7 nM) > alpha-4-beta-4 (IC(50)=69.9 nM) > alpha-2-beta-4 (IC(50)=121 nM) > alpha-7 (IC(50)=272 nM) > alpha-2-beta-2 (IC(50)=800 nM) (PubMed:15520009). Recovery from toxin block is markedly slower for beta-4 versus beta-2 subunit-containing nAChRs (PubMed:15520009, PubMed:16964981). Residues Thr-83, Val-135 and Phe-143 in the rat beta-2 subunit and Lys-81, Ile-133 and Gln-141 in the rat beta-4 subunit are critical to off-rate differences (PubMed:16964981). Thus, this toxin represents a novel probe for distinguishing between beta-2 and beta-4 subunit-containing nAChRs (PubMed:15520009, PubMed:16964981).

name: Kappa-hexatoxin-Hv1e
description: This excitatory toxin inhibits insect calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channels (Slo-type).

name: Alpha-conotoxin PIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and inhibit them. This toxin blocks nAChR (alpha-6 or -3/beta-2 or -3 > alpha-3/beta-2 > alpha-3/beta-4). Does not block the muscle nor the major neuronal nAChR alpha-4/beta-2. Discriminates between nAChRs containing alpha-6 and alpha-3 subunits, being selective for alpha-6.

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hvn1a
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor stephenin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Toxin Tb4
description: Not toxic to mice.

name: Toxin Tb1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). Is lethal to mice (PubMed:8611151).

name: Toxin Tst1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on mammals (By similarity). Is toxic to mice (PubMed:8611151).

name: Phospholipase A2 large subunit
description: Phosholipase toxin, which catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides. Inhibits both skeletal (RYR1) and cardiac (RYR2) ryanodine receptors (calcium release channels). Probably blocks ryanodine receptors by generating a lipid product (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 BmatTX-III
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 that shows high myotoxic activity, slight neutrophil activation (demonstrated by activation induction of IL-1beta production), slight cytotoxicity against tumor cell lines (T leukemia and breast adenocarcinoma), and slight antiparasitic activity against promastigote forms of Leishmania amazonensis. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Venom metalloproteinase antarease-like TfasMP_A
description: Acts as a metalloprotease. Penetrates intact tissue and specifically cleaves the vesicle-associated membrane protein 2 (VAMP2) (part of the SNARE complex) involved in pancreatic secretion, thus disrupting the normal vesicular traffic (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 natratoxin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has an effectively inhibitory effect on A-type K(+) currents (Kv/KCN) in acutely dissociated rat dorsal root ganglion (DRG) neurons. This inhibitory effect is independent of its enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog Bsc-K49
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 that lacks enzymatic activity, but has myotoxic activity.

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin BaIT2
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Long neurotoxin OH-5
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that may exhibit cardiotoxicity, myotoxicity, antiplatelet activity, and edema-inducing activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Pandinin-2
description: Disrupts cell membranes through formation of pores. Has strong antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis, S.epidermidis, E.faecalis and S.aureus. Is less active against Gram-negative bacteria P.aeruginosa and E.coli. Also increases efficacy of antibiotics (ampicillin, chloramphenicol, streptomycin, kanamycin, novobiocin) when tested against E.coli, probably by facilitating their incorporation into the bacteria. Possesses antifungal activity against C.albicans and hemolytic activity against human, sheep and pig erythrocytes.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 13.1
description: Blocks reversibly Shaker B potassium channels. Also displaces binding of noxiustoxin to mouse brain synaptosome membranes.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 13.2
description: Potent and selective inhibitor of Kv1.2/KCNA2 potassium channels.

name: M-oxotoxin-Ot1a
description: Disrupts cell membranes, particularly those rich in phosphocholine, through formation of pores. Has antimicrobial activity against Gram-negative bacterium E.coli, Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis and S.aureus, and hemolytic activity against sheep, pig and guinea pig erythrocytes. Has insecticidal activity against S.frugiperda ovarian cells by opening non-selective ion channels. Enhances the insecticidal activity of spider venom neurotoxic peptides.

name: M-oxotoxin-Ot2b
description: Disrupts biological membranes, particularly those rich in phosphocholine. Has antimicrobial activity against Gram-negative bacterium E.coli, Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis and S.aureus, and hemolytic activity against sheep, pig and guinea pig red blood cells. Has insecticidal activity against S.frugiperda ovarian cells by opening non-selective ion channels. Enhances the insecticidal activity of spider venom neurotoxic peptides.

name: M-oxotoxin-Ot2a
description: Disrupts biological membranes, particularly those rich in phosphocholine. Has antimicrobial activity against Gram-negative bacterium E.coli, Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis and S.aureus, and hemolytic activity against sheep, pig and guinea pig red blood cells. Has insecticidal activity against S.frugiperda ovarian cells by opening non-selective ion channels. Enhances the insecticidal activity of spider venom neurotoxic peptides.

name: Long neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Lh2a
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin SN160
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 2
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Potassium channel toxin gamma-KTx 1.8
description: Blocks in a reversible manner human and rat Kv11.1/KCNH2/ERG1 potassium channels. Also completely and irreversibly blocks rat Kv11.2/KCNH6/ERG2 and human Kv11.3/KCNH7/ERG3 channels.

name: Snake venom serine protease salmonase
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Conophan vil-I'/vil-I'(O2P)
description: May act as a neurotoxin.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 cL037
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 cL038
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 cPt09
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 cPt10
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 cPm05
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 cPm08
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Snaclec rhodocytin subunit alpha
description: Elicits platelet aggregation by the binding to the C-type lectin domain family 1 member B (CLEC1B/CLEC2). Binding leads to tyrosine phosphorylation in the cytoplasmic tail of CLEC1B, which promotes the binding of spleen tyrosine kinase (Syk), subsequent activation of PLC-gamma-2, and platelet activation and aggregation. Binding to GPIbalpha (GP1BA) and alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1) may also induce aggregation, but this is controversial.

name: Snaclec rhodocytin subunit beta
description: Elicits platelet aggregation by the binding to the C-type lectin domain family 1 member B (CLEC1B/CLEC2). Binding leads to tyrosine phosphorylation in the cytoplasmic tail of CLEC1B, which promotes the binding of spleen tyrosine kinase (Syk), subsequent activation of PLCgamma2, and platelet activation and aggregation. Binding to GPIbalpha (GP1BA) and alpha2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1) may also induce aggregation, but this is controversial.

name: Chlorotoxin-like peptide
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity). Inhibits migration and invasion of U87 glioma cells expressing CLCN3/ClC-3 voltage-gated chloride channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6.1
description: Potently and reversibly inhibits the insect voltage-gated Shaker (Sh) potassium channel (isoform alpha (B)), the mammalian voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.2/KCNA2. Its effect on Kv1.3/KCNA3 is controversial, since this channel is voltage-independently inhibited in PubMed:9464266, but is not affected in PubMed:10931199. Furthermore, this toxin competes with apamin (a small conductance calcium-activated potassium channel inhibitor) for binding onto rat brain synaptosomes.

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide 5h
description: Induces chemotaxis. Shows antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=30 ug/ml), the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus ATCC 2592 (MIC=5 ug/ml) and the fungus C.albicans ATCC 2002 (MIC=25 ug/ml).

name: Mastoparan-like peptide 12c
description: Shows mast cell degranulation and antimicrobial activities against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=6.0 ug/ml), the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus ATCC 2592 (MIC=3.0 ug/ml) and the fungus C.albicans ATCC 2002 (MIC=12 ug/ml).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like SO-5
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Neurotoxin Cex7
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Cex6
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Cex9
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Cex8
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Cex11
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Cex10
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Neurotoxin Cex13
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Cex12
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Delta-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 3
description: Inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels, preferentially subtype Nav1.5/SCN5A (in cardiac myocytes), but also Nav1.6/SCN8A and Nav1.7/SCN9A (TTX-sensitive Nav in rat DRG neurons) and invertebrate Nav (in insect neurons) as well as voltage-gated potassium channels of the subtype Kv2.1/KCNB1. Is suggested to bind to site 3 of the channels and inhibiting the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Increases muscle contraction in several assays (mouse phrenic nerve-diaphragm, toad heart, rat vas deferens) and is suggested to act both presynaptically and postsynaptically.

name: U7-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Inhibits preferentially tetrodotoxin-insensitive sodium currents (Nav) on rat cardiac myocytes (IC(50) is 0.26 uM) and has weaker inhibition activity toward tetrodotoxin-sensitive sodium currents on rat dorsal root ganglion (DRG) sensory neurons (IC(50) is 0.83 uM) and on cockroach dorsal unpaired median (DUM) neurons (IC(50) is 1.19 uM). Has no significant effect on potassium currents on DRG neurons.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg2b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Delta-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 2
description: Inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels, preferentially subtype Nav1.5/SCN5A (in cardiac myocytes), but also Nav1.6/SCN8A and Nav1.7/SCN9A (TTX-sensitive Nav in rat DRG neurons) and invertebrate Nav (in insect neurons) as well as voltage-gated potassium channels of the subtype Kv2.1/KCNB1. Is suggested to bind to site 3 of the channels and inhibiting the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Increases muscle contraction in several assays (mouse phrenic nerve-diaphragm, toad heart, rat vas deferens) and is suggested to act both presynaptically and postsynaptically.

name: Snaclec botrocetin subunit beta
description: Snaclec that binds to von Willebrand factor (VWF) and induces its interaction with GPIbalpha (GP1BA) (via the vWF A1 domain), resulting in platelet aggregation.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like ts14a
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Contryphan-Bu
description: Inhibits high voltage-activated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Kunitz-type conkunitzin-B1
description: Blocks specifically voltage-activated potassium channels (Kv) of the Shaker family.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like Bu27
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: U2-lycotoxin-Ls1a
description: Antagonist of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). Blocks insect neuromuscular transmission presynaptically (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 DE-I
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits the ADP- and collagen-induced human platelet aggregation (By similarity). Exhibits high hydrolytic activities and preferred the anionic micelles to the zwitterionic micelles. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 caudoxin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows anticoagulant activity and presynaptic neurotoxicity. Acts as an anticoagulant toxin by inhibiting prothrombinase complex formation. Shows about 50% of the prothrombinase complex inhibition compared to CM-IV of N.nigricollis venom. Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 beta
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 CM-II
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Cytotoxin 2b
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Glutaminyl-peptide cyclotransferase
description: Responsible for the biosynthesis of pyroglutamyl peptides. Has a bias against acidic and tryptophan residues adjacent to the N-terminal glutaminyl residue and a lack of importance of chain length after the second residue. Also catalyzes N-terminal pyroglutamate formation (By similarity).

name: Glutaminyl-peptide cyclotransferase
description: Responsible for the biosynthesis of pyroglutamyl peptides. Has a bias against acidic and tryptophan residues adjacent to the N-terminal glutaminyl residue and a lack of importance of chain length after the second residue. Also catalyzes N-terminal pyroglutamate formation (By similarity).

name: Cytotoxin 2a
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Toxin TdNa10
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin binds, in vitro, to sodium channels and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels. Seems not toxic to mice, crickets and sweet-water shrimps (By similarity).

name: Toxin TdNa5
description: Inhibits the sodium currents (Nav) in an apparent irreversible manner. Produces small depolarization and induces repetitive firing in squid axons. Is specific for arthropods (crickets, triatomides, crabs and squids), but is non-toxic to mice (By similarity).

name: Toxin TdNa3
description: Inhibits the sodium currents (Nav) in an apparent irreversible manner. Produces small depolarization and induces repetitive firing in squid axons. Is specific for arthropods (crickets, triatomides, crabs and squids), but is non-toxic to mice (By similarity).

name: Toxin TdNa2
description: Inhibits the sodium currents (Nav) in an apparent irreversible manner. Produces small depolarization and induces repetitive firing in squid axons. Is specific for arthropods (crickets, triatomides, crabs and squids), but is non-toxic to mice (By similarity).

name: Toxin TdNa9
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin binds, in vitro, to sodium channels and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels. Seems not toxic to mice, crickets and sweet-water shrimps (By similarity).

name: Toxin TdNa8
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Toxin TdNa6
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. Is toxic to arthropods (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor conotoxin Cal9.1b
Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor conotoxin Cal9.1a
Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like VAP1
description: Zinc metalloprotease that has fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities. It induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. VAP1-induced apoptosis is inhibited by antibodies for integrin alpha-3, alpha-6, beta-1 and CD9. Apoptosis is accompanied by severe cell fragmentation, which is controlled by caspases.

name: Toxin CsE9
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like VLAIP-B
description: This metalloproteinase hydrolyzes azocasein, and oxidized insulin B-chain. Also hydrolyzes the Aalpha-chain (FGA) and more slowly the Bbeta-chain of fibrinogen (FGB), without affecting the gamma-chain. Does not cleave fibrin. Inhibits endothelial cell adhesion to extracellular matrix proteins such as fibrinogen, fibronectin, vitronectin, collagen I, and collagen IV. Induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like VLAIP-A
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that hydrolyzes the alpha-chain (FGA) and more slowly the beta-chain (FGB) of fibrinogen, without affecting the gamma-chain. Induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells and inhibits endothelial cell adhesion to extracellular matrix proteins such as fibrinogen, fibronectin, vitronectin, collagen I, and collagen IV. Also hydrolyzes azocasein, and oxidized insulin B-chain.

name: Alpha-conotoxin EIIB
description: Alpha-conotoxins bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and inhibit them. This peptide potently blocks muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNG-CHRND), and has no effect on neuronal receptors. It is able to totally displace [125I]-Bgtx from the Torpedo receptor with an inhibition constant (Ki) of 2.2 and 0.7 nM.

name: Con-Ins T1
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. It is the smallest known insulin found in nature and lacks the C-terminal segment of the B chain that, in human insulin, mediates engagement of the insulin receptor and assembly of the hormone's hexameric storage form. Despite lacking this segment, it both binds and activates human insulin receptor (B isoform) with only a 10-fold reduced potency. In vivo, intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In addition, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Putative calcium channel toxin 196
description: Putative ryanodine receptor inhibitor (RYR).

name: Antimicrobial peptide 36.4
description: Cationic host defense peptide that have antibacterial activity by breaking membranes. Is more effective on Gram-positive than on Gram-negative bacteria.

name: Neurotoxin alpha-KTx 29.3
description: Weakly inhibits the Kv1.3/KCNA3 channel (1 uM of thetoxin inhibits currents by 13.2%) and Kv7.1/KCNQ1 channel (10 uM of the toxin inhibits currents by 27.7%).

name: Neurotoxin LmNaTx45.2
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like atragin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that seems to inhibit cell migration. This activity is dominated by the local structure of the hyper-variable region.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Lethal neurotoxin that blocks neuromuscular transmission. Acts cooperatively to potentiate the activity of huwentoxin-I. This toxin is active against insects.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PA4
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Beta-toxin BmKAS
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. It binds to distinct receptor sites of mammal and insect voltage-gated sodium channels. It displays antinociceptive effect in rat models, which is due to its specific modulation of sodium channels of sensory neurons. It also significantly stimulates the binding of [3H]-ryanodine to ryanodine receptors on the sarcoplasmic reticulum of the skeletal muscle through an indirect mechanism. And it promotes noradrenaline release from the rat hippocampus slice.

name: Beta-toxin BmKAs1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. BmKAs1 also significantly stimulates the binding of [3H]-ryanodine to ryanodine receptors on the sarcoplasmic reticulum of the skeletal muscle. It also displays antinociceptive effect in rat models.

name: Cytotoxin 8
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cardiotoxin 7a
description: Has low cytotoxic activity.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Ba1a
description: Inhibits voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav) in rat cerebellar granule cells (By similarity). Has insecticidal activity (Ref.1).

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit B
description: When linked to subunit A of IX/X-bp, anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit A
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors IX (F9) and factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Sodium channel alpha-toxin Acra4
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Electrophysiological studies of this were performed using sodium-channels expressed in F11 cell culture, by patch-clamp recordings. Affinity of this toxin toward sodium channels in F11 cell line is in the order of 1 uM concentration.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 15.5
description: Binds to potassium channel and affects the potassium ion currents, by occluding the outer entry to the K(+) conducting pore. The blockade is partially reversible and affect both open and closed channels (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LiSicTox-alphaIA1bii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation.

name: Cathelicidin-related peptide lachesicidin
description: Potent antimicrobial peptide against Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria. Adopts an amphipathic alpha helical conformation, that may allow to partition into the target membrane. Low hemolytic activities have been observed on mammalian cells.

name: Tamulustoxin
description: Blocks Kv1.6/KCNA6 potassium channels.

name: Tamulustoxin-2
description: Blocks Kv1.6/KCNA6 potassium channels.

name: Omega-actinopoditoxin-Mb1a
description: Potent inhibitor of insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Ar1a
description: Insecticidal toxin that reversibly and voltage-independently blocks both mid-low- (M-LVA) and high-voltage-activated (HVA) calcium channels (Cav) in cockroach DUM neurons. Also causes a modest block of insect sodium channel currents (Nav). Induces potent excitatory symptoms, followed by flaccid paralysis leading to death in house crickets.

name: Toxin b subunit alpha
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and affects the channel activation process.

name: Toxin b subunit beta
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and affects the channel activation process.

name: Toxin Acra2
description: Excitatory insect toxins induce a spastic paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). Is lethal to mice. Is about 1% of the total protein in the venom.

name: Toxin a
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and affects the channel activation process.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like EoMP06
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that catalyzes the conversion of prothrombin (F2) to alpha-thrombin.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: Kallikrein-like EII
description: Cleaves a kininogen analog to release bradykinin.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme catroxobin-1
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Clots fibrinogen (FGA and FGB) very slowly, releasing fibrinopeptide A and a small amount of fibrinopeptide B.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide K12
description: Inhibits angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE), but does not serve as substrate for the enzyme. Potentiate bradykinin (BK) on the isolated guinea pig ileum as well as the isolated rat uterus for contraction. Also potentiates in vivo the depressor effect of BK on arterial blood pressure in the normotensive anesthetized rat. Intracerebroventricular injection into mice does not show toxic activity.

name: Omega-ctenitoxin-Pr2a
description: Antagonist of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1). Causes paralysis in posterior limbs, and gradual decrease in movement and aggression during 24 hours after intracerebroventricular injection in mice at dose levels of 3 ug per mouse.

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Omega-agatoxin-Aa1b
description: Omega-agatoxin are antagonist of voltage-gated calcium channels. They block insect neuromuscular transmission presynaptically. This toxin is a blocker of L-type calcium channels (Cav/CACNA1).

name: Auswaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Scuwaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 18.1
description: Reversible blocker of both Kv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channels (high affinity) and Shaker B (mammalian Kv1.1 analog) potassium channels (very low affinity).

name: Conotoxin Vc6.10
description: Inhibits voltage-gated ion channels.

name: Toxin To3
description: Affects sodium-permeability in pituitary GH3 cells in culture. Inhibits the inactivation of sodium activated channels (Nav). Slightly delays the activation time course, and consequently the time to peak. Shifts the voltage dependence of the activation to more negative potentials. Does not reduce the peak sodium-current amplitude.

name: Alpha-toxin To2
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Affects the tetrodotoxin-sensitive sodium current permeability of F-11 rat neuroblastoma cells. Produces a dose dependent increase in amplitude and duration of the current.

name: Toxin To4
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin To1
description: Affects the sodium (Nav) current permeability of rat cerebellum granular cells. This effect is partially reversible. Does not modify the function of the Shaker B potassium channels.

name: U13-ctenitoxin-Pn1c
description: Acts as a neurotoxin.

name: Snaclec trowaglerix subunit alpha
description: Potently induces platelet aggregation of washed human platelet and platelet-rich plasma in a concentration-dependent manner. It acts by binding to GPVI (GP6), leading to kinases-dependent exposure of functional alpha-IIb/beta-3 and platelet aggregation, and also induces metalloproteinase-dependent GP6 shedding from platelets.

name: Snaclec trowaglerix subunit beta
description: Potently induces platelet aggregation of washed human platelet and platelet-rich plasma in a concentration-dependent manner. It acts by binding to GPVI (GP6), leading to kinases-dependent exposure of functional alpha-IIb/beta-3 and platelet aggregation, and also induces metalloproteinase-dependent GP6 shedding from platelets.

name: Snake venom serine protease 2B
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease 3
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease 2C
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Waglerin-4
description: Waglerin-2 selectively blocks the epsilon subunit of muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR). Has also effects on rodent ionotropic GABA(A) receptors (GABR), since it potentiates I(GABA) in some neurons and depresses I(GABA) in others. In mice, it elicits tachypnea, ocular proptosis, rapid collapse and spasms, whereas no toxic effects on respiration and blood pressure are observed in rats (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 1.10
description: Reversibly blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv1.1/KCNA1 (Kd=79 uM), Kv1.2/KCNA2 (Kd=547 nM) and Kv1.3/KCNA3 (Kd=492 nM)).

name: Ryncolin-3
description: Initiates complement activation and/or interferes in platelet aggregation and/or blood coagulation.

name: Ryncolin-2
description: Initiates complement activation and/or interferes in platelet aggregation and/or blood coagulation.

name: Ryncolin-1
description: Initiates complement activation and/or interferes in platelet aggregation and/or blood coagulation.

name: C-type lectin
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that may induce platelet aggregation.

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1q
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 3.8
description: Potassium channel inhibitor.

name: Chlorotoxin-like peptide Bs 14
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A2 imperatoxin-1
description: Phosholipase toxin, which may catalyze the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides. Inhibits both skeletal (RYR1) and cardiac (RYR2) ryanodine receptors (calcium release channels). Probably blocks ryanodine receptors by generating a lipid product.

name: Snake venom metalloproteinase BpMP-1
description: Non-hemorrhagic snake venom zinc metalloprotease that hydrolyzes the Aalpha-chain of fibrinogen, more slowly the Bbeta-chain and shows no effect on the gamma chain. Has no coagulant activity on bovine plasma and fibrinogen.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Neurotoxin BmK-M11
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This recombinant toxin selectively inhibits the fast inactivation of mNav1.4 (EC(50) = 82.3 nM) (tested in HEK293 cells).

name: Toxin-like peptide AaF1CA5
description: Probable neurotoxin that inhibits ion channels.

name: Toxin-like peptide AaF1CA1
description: Probable neurotoxin that inhibits ion channels.

name: Beta-toxin KAaH1
description: Inhibits the vertebrate potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 and Kv1.3/KCNA3 in vitro with an IC(50) of 5.3 nM and 50.0 nM respectively.

name: Toxin-like peptide AaF1CA7
description: Probable neurotoxin that inhibits ion channels.

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide 5e
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide (By similarity). Has little hemolytic activity. Shows antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=30 ug/ml), the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus ATCC 2592 (MIC=5 ug/ml) and the fungus C.albicans ATCC 2002 (MIC=25 ug/ml).

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide 5g
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide (By similarity). Has little hemolytic activity. Shows antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=30 ug/ml), the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus ATCC 2592 (MIC=10 ug/ml) and the fungus C.albicans ATCC 2002 (MIC=12.5 ug/ml).

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide 5f
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide (By similarity). Has little hemolytic activity. Shows antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=30 ug/ml), the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus ATCC 2592 (MIC=10 ug/ml) and the fungus C.albicans ATCC 2002 (MIC=25 ug/ml).

name: Mastoparan-like peptide 12b
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Has little hemolytic activity. Shows antimicrobial activity against the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli ATCC 25922 (MIC=15 ug/ml), the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus ATCC 2592 (MIC=3.7 ug/ml) and the fungus C.albicans ATCC 2002 (MIC=7.5 ug/ml).

name: Dominulin-B
description: Shows antimicrobial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis ATCC 6633 (MIC=2 ug/ml), and the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli JM109 (MIC=8 ug/ml).

name: Dominulin-A
description: Shows antimicrobial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis ATCC 6633 (MIC=2 ug/ml), and the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli JM109 (MIC=8 ug/ml).

name: Snaclec 3
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Long neurotoxin OH-57
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin OH-56
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-latrotoxin associated low molecular weight protein SGV150-311
description: May increase the toxicity of alpha-latrotoxin and/or other venom components. Is non-toxic to mice and to the cockroach Periplaneta americana.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U9-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1t
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1u
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Orientotoxin-1
description: Neurotoxin of presynaptic effect which degrades lysophospholipids.

name: Orientotoxin-2
description: Has a highly toxic phospholipase A2 activity.

name: Long neurotoxin OH-55
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Long neurotoxin OH-37
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 5
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits platelet aggregation induced by ADP, arachidonic acid and PAF. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 4
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that exhibits strong myotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Gamma-conotoxin-like TxVIIA
description: Gamma-conotoxins may act on voltage-gated non-specific cation pacemaker channels (HCN) (By similarity). Potent neurotoxin.

name: Snaclec echicetin subunit alpha
description: Echicetin itself inhibits aggregation of washed platelets induced by vWF, thrombin or alboaggregin-A (PubMed:8481512, PubMed:11290595). However, when complexed with the pentameric plasma immunoglobulin Mkappa (IgMkappa), echicetin binds specifically to GPIb and activates platelets. This is caused by P-selectin expression and activation of alpha-IIb/beta-3 as well as tyrosine phosphorylation of several signal transduction molecules, including p53/56(LYN), p64, p72(SYK), p70 to p90, and p120 (PubMed:11290595). In vivo, it induces thrombocytopenia when injected into mice (PubMed:8481512), probably accounting of activation of platelets rather than inhibition (PubMed:11290595).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor C10
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits trypsin.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor C9
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin.

name: BPTI-like protein
description: Does not inhibit chymotrypsin or trypsin.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Gr3a
description: Inhibits sodium channels Nav1.7/SCN9A and potassium channels Kv11.1/KCNH2. Also binds the voltage-sensor domain of the potassium channel KvAP (from the archaeon Aeropyrum pernix) with very slow apparent binding kinetics and affects channel gating. Reaches its target by dynamically partitioning into anionic or zwitterionic headgroup lipid membranes. May bind to the open state of KvAP.

name: Adrenergic toxin rho-elapitoxin-Dp1a
description: Highly potent on various alpha-adrenoceptors (ADRA) (subnanomolar affinity for ADRA1A). Order of potency is the following: ADRA1A > ADRA1B > ADRA1D > ADRA2C (PubMed:23648423). Were also found to reversibly bind to muscarinic acetylcholine receptors (CHRM), but the affinity is much weaker (micromolar range) (PubMed:10978757, PubMed:23648423).

name: Muscarinic toxin alpha
description: Selectively binds with high-affinity to the a2B-adrenoceptor subtype (ADRA2B). The toxin reversibly binds to ADRA2B, and its mode of inhibition is non-competitive.

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB2iii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB2ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB2i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIB2c
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIB2bii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LapSicTox-alphaIB2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspaSicTox-alphaIA1iii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspaSicTox-alphaIA1ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Veswaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Veswaprin-b
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Veswaprin-c
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Carwaprin-b
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Supwaprin-c
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Snaclec bitiscetin subunit beta
description: Snaclec that binds to von Willebrand factor (VWF) and induces its interaction with GPIbalpha (GP1BA) (via the vWF A1 domain), resulting in platelet aggregation.

name: Disintegrin echistatin-gamma
description: Has antiplatelet activities on guinea pig, followed by human, rabbit and rat platelet-rich plasma.

name: Snaclec bitiscetin subunit alpha
description: Snaclec that binds to von Willebrand factor (VWF) and induces its interaction with GPIbalpha (GP1BA) (via the vWF A1 domain), resulting in platelet aggregation.

name: Snaclec tokaracetin subunit alpha
description: Platelet antagonist that specifically and reversibly binds to a site on platelet glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA) close to or identical with the site for vWF binding. It inhibits the binding of vWF to platelets and vWF-dependent shear-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Omega-ctenitoxin-Pn2a
description: Inhibits all known high-voltage activated calcium channels (L-, P/Q- and R-type currents) (Cav), and most effectively the P/Q- (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) and R-type (Cav2.3/CACNA1E) currents. Blocks glutamate exocytosis. Induces rapid general flaccid paralysis followed by death in 10-30 minutes at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse. In rat brain, inhibits glutamate release, neuronal death and loss of neurotransmission in the hippocampus resulting from ischemia.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 2.6
description: Potassium channel inhibitor (Kv).

name: Scorpine-like peptide
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Probable antimicrobial peptide Con10
description: Probable antimicrobial peptide.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6.16
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Insecticidal toxin OcyC10
description: Insecticidal toxin.

name: Alpha-toxin OD1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Mammalian sodium channels Nav1.7/SCN9A (EC(50)=4.5 nM), Nav1.4/SCN4A (EC(50)=9.6 nM), Nav1.6/SCN8A (EC(50)=30 nM) Nav1.5/SCN5A (only at micromolar concentrations), and insect sodium channel para/tipE (EC(50)=80 nM) are affected by this toxin.

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIB2a
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: U2-ctenitoxin-Cs1a
description: This toxin alone has very weak insecticidal activity, with an unknown molecular target. Acts as a neurotoxic enhancer, synergistically enhancing the neurotoxic action of omega-CNTX-Cs1a (CSTX-1) (AC P81694).

name: U3-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: May act as a neurotoxin.

name: Sarafotoxin
description: Vasoconstrictor activity. These toxins cause cardiac arrest probably as a result of coronary vasospasm.

name: U6-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: Neurotoxin. Causes spastic paralysis and death in mice. Does not inhibit L-type calcium channels.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin jerdonitin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that inhibits ADP-induced human platelet aggregation with an IC(50) of 120 nM (248 nM for the recombinant protein). May act by binding to the receptor GPIIb/GPIIIa (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface (PubMed:14511668). Degrades the alpha-chain of fibrinogen completely and the beta-chain partially, leaving the gamma chain intact (Ref.2). Also inhibits the growth of several cell lines, including human liver cancer cells (Bel7402), human leukemia cells (K562) and human gastric carcinoma cells (BGC823) (PubMed:19732785).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog mulgin-1
description: Serine protease inhibitor homolog that only shows inhibitory activity against MMP2.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor mulgin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PLA-1
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 PLA-2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 VRV-PL-VIIIa
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows weak neurotoxicity and medium anticoagulant effects by binding to factor Xa (F10) and inhibiting the prothrombinase activity (IC(50) is 130 nM) (PubMed:18062812). It also damages vital organs such as lung, liver and kidney, displays edema-inducing activities when injected into the foot pads of mice and induces necrosis of muscle cells when injected into the thigh muscle. Has a low enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2 superbin d
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation. In terms of inhibition of platelet aggregation, superbin d is less potent as superbin a, b, and c. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Short neurotoxin N2
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and hinders acetylcholine binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin N1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and hinders acetylcholine binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Toxin BmKa1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Cytotoxin NN-32
description: Shows cytotoxic activity against Ehrlich ascites carcinoma (EAC) model in mice. Also shows effect on apoptotic features such as nuclear fragmentation, caspase activity, pro- and anti-apoptotic protein levels on treated EAC cells. Increased levels of antioxidant enzymes and cytokine levels observed in toxin-treated EAC mice. Cardiotoxic towards guinea pig auricle. Has no cytotoxicity towards macrophages in vivo in EAC bearing mice or in vitro in normal human lymphocytes.

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog 4
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic activity. Induces acute muscle damage after intramuscular injection in mice and disrupts negatively charged liposomes but not positively charged ones. Also exerts a weak anticoagulant effect only at concentrations of 40 ug/ml or higher.

name: Snaclec B9
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Hhn1b
description: Postsynaptic neurotoxin.

name: Snaclec B1
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec B2
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec B3/B5
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec B4
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec B6
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec B7
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec B8
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Gilatoxin
description: Has kallikrein-like activity, releases bradykinin from kininogen. Catalyzes the hydrolysis of various arginine ester substrates for trypsin and thrombin and degrades both angiotensin I and II by cleavage of the dipeptide Asp-Arg from the NH2-terminal end. Fibrinogen is also degraded but a fibrin clot is not produced. May have a potentiating effect on potent hemorrhagic toxins present in the venom.

name: Peptide BmKn2
description: Peptide BmKn2: has strong antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus, M.luteus, B.subtilis, and Gram-negative bacteria E.coli, P.aeruginosa and N.gonorrhoeae. Also shows low activity against HIV-1 PV.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1d
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1a
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1f
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1d
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1d
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1e
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1b
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U15-lycotoxin-Ls1c
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Acetylcholinesterase-1
description: Terminates signal transduction at the neuromuscular junction by rapid hydrolysis of the acetylcholine released into the synaptic cleft.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 DE-II
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 DE-III
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 CM-I
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that causes myonecrosis when injected intramuscularly, shows indirect hemolytic activity, abolishes twitches evoked by indirect stimulation earlier than those by direct stimulation (in the mouse phrenic nerve-diaphragm preparation) but does not produce complete neuromuscular block (up to 30 ug/ml) (in the chick biventer cervicis nerve-muscle preparation) (PubMed:3615669). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 CM-II
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that causes myonecrosis when injected intramuscularly, causes neuromuscular blockade with a gradual contracture and a decreased sensitivity to ACh and KCl (in the chick biventer cervicis nerve-muscle preparation), abolishes twitches evoked by indirect stimulation earlier than those by direct stimulation (in the mouse phrenic nerve-diaphragm preparation), shows indirect hemolytic activity (PubMed:3615669), and shows weak anticoagulant activity (PubMed:3117784). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 CM-III
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows several activities. It shows strong anticoagulant activity, probably by binding to coagulation factor Xa (F10) and inhibiting the formation of the prothrombinase complex (PubMed:15922780), shows direct hemolytic action, causes neuromuscular blockade with a gradual contracture and a decreased sensitivity to ACh and KCl, abolishes twitches evoked by indirect stimulation earlier than those by direct stimulation (in the mouse phrenic nerve-diaphragm preparation), and causes myonecrosis when injected intramuscularly (PubMed:3615669). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2 "basic"
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows strong anticoagulant activity. Binds directly with the coagulation factor FXa (F10) and blocks the formation of the prothombinase complex. Acts by a nonenzymatic mechanism (PubMed:10462445). Also inhibits the complex composed of tissue factor (F3) and coagulation factor VIIa (F7) (TF-VIIa complex) by both enzymatic and nonenzymatic mechanisms (PubMed:8866616). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 notexin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. Is directly toxic to skeletal muscle upon local application in vivo (dystrophic effect). Also has direct nephrotoxicity in experimental mice; a single subcutaneous dose (1.38 ug/kg) produces renal tubular and glomerular damage within 24 hours (PubMed:7580101). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 notechis II-5
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. Notechis II-5 is less toxic than notexin but has a higher specific phospholipase activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Long neurotoxin LlLong
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin OKI-10
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Erabutoxin c
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: U2-plectoxin-Pt1a
description: Potent toxin that may paralyze and/or kill insect pests such as H.virescens (lepidoptera), S.exigua (beet armyworm) and M.sexta (tobacco hornworm).

name: Venom protein 51.1
description: Neurotoxin. Decreases the action potential of myelinated nerves in mice and frogs.

name: Venom protein 55.1
description: Regulates fluid secretion.

name: Hyaluronidase
description: Hydrolyzes high molecular weight hyaluronic acid to produce small oligosaccharides.

name: Hyaluronidase A
description: Hydrolyzes high molecular weight hyaluronic acid to produce small oligosaccharides.

name: Putative sodium channel alpha-toxin Acra5
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Venom nerve growth factor 2
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Pi-theraphotoxin-Hm3a
description: Inhibitor of proton-gated sodium channel ASIC1 isoform 2 from human and ASIC1 isoform 1 from rat. Potentiator of ASIC1 isoform 3 from human and rat as well as of combinations of human ASIC1 isoforms 2 and 3 and rat ASIC1 isoforms 1 and 3.

name: Phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Natriuretic peptide PNP
description: Increases urine flow and decreases blood pressure when administered to rats by intravenous injection. Inhibits thrombin-induced platelet aggregation. Stimulates cGMP production via the natriuretic peptide receptor-A (NPR1).

name: Myotoxin-2
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: Myotoxin-3
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor. It exhibits antimicrobial activities, hind limb paralysis, and severe muscle necrosis by a non-enzymatic mechanism (By similarity).

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids (highest specificity towards L-Met, L-Trp, L-Leu followed by L-His, L-Phe, L-Arg and L-Ile, wherease L-Gly, L-Ser, L-Thr, L-Pro, L-Cys, L-Asp are not oxidized), thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as antibacterial activities against both Gram-negative (E.coli) and Gram-positive (B.subtilis) bacteria, and inhibition of agonist-induced platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions. This protein may also induce hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis, and have antiparasitic activities.

name: Venom dipeptidyl peptidase 4
description: Venom dipeptidyl-peptidase which removes N-terminal dipeptides sequentially from polypeptides having unsubstituted N-termini provided that the penultimate residue is proline. May process promelittin into its active form and/or modulate the chemotactic activity of immune cells after the insect sting.

name: Mastoparan
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins that couple to phospholipase C.

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide L
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Induces the chemotaxis of neutrophils.

name: Chemotactic peptide
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Induces the chemotaxis of neutrophils.

name: Histamine-releasing peptide 2
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Induces the chemotaxis of neutrophils.

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide T
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Induces the chemotaxis of neutrophils.

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide A
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Induces the chemotaxis of neutrophils.

name: Vespid chemotactic peptide M
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Induces the chemotaxis of neutrophils.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6 hetlaxin
description: Binds to voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=0.48 uM) and Kv1.1/KCNA1 (IC(50)=6.7 uM) and inhibits channel activity.

name: Kappa-scoloptoxin-Ssm2a
description: Toxin that inhibits voltage-gated potassium channel currents in DRG neurons with an IC(50) of about 570 nM. Shows signs of neurotoxicity including twitching, paralysis, and body contraction.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 MVL-PLA2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays an inhibitory effect, independent from its catalytic activity, on tumor cell adhesion and migration. This effect is mediated via specific inhibition of integrins alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1), alpha-v/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) and alpha-v/beta-6 (ITGAV/ITGB6). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: U16-barytoxin-Tl1a
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: C-type lectin TsL
description: Galactose-binding protein which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin.

name: Toxin ICK-20
description: Ion channel inhibitor.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog Pgo-K49
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic activity, but shows myotoxicity.

name: Natriuretic peptide NP2
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that shows an increase in perfusion pressure, urinary flow and glomerular filtration rate. Reduces total and proximal tubular transport of sodium. In the aortic ring assay, causes a relaxant effect in endothelium-intact thoracic aortic rings precontracted with phenylephrine in the presence and absence of isatin, a natriuretic receptor antagonist.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 5
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme F202
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that coagulates fibrinogen by inducing a fast degradation of the alpha chain (FGA) from human citrated plasma, and a slow degradation of beta chain (FGB). Potently induces platelet aggregation in both platelet rich plasma and washed platelet preparations in a concentration-dependent fashion. Shows amidolytic activities.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Conantokin-R1-A
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. This toxin has the highest potency for the NR2B/GRIN2B subunit (IC(50)=0.11 uM), followed by NR2D/GRIN2D (IC(50)=0.48 uM), NR2A/GRIN2A (IC(50)=2.1 uM), and NR2C/GRIN2C (IC(50)=6.1 uM) subunits when tested on rat receptors.

name: Conotoxin PIVE
description: This toxin elicits dose-dependently excitatory activity upon injection into fish. Its action is slowly reversible. Does not have any direct effects on neuromuscular nAChRs (human adult alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta or fetal alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta receptors). Does not have any effects on human Kv1 (KCNA1, KCNA2, KCNA3, KCNA4, KCNA5, and KCNA), Kv2.1/KCNB1, Kv3.4 (KCNC4), Kv4.2 (KCND2), KCNQ2/3, and on the Drosophilia Shaker potassium channels. Does not have effects on the fish potassium channels, TSha1, TSha2 (Kv1 homologs), and Traw (Kv3 homolog), without detectable activity.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like PIVF
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels (By similarity). Elicits excitatory activity upon injection into fish.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 16.1
description: Blocks calcium-activated potassium channels.

name: Peptide TsPep3
description: Potassium channel blocker. At 3 uM, this toxin blocks voltage-gated potassium channels rKv1.2/KCNA2 (5%), hKv1.3/KCNA3 (10%),rKv1.4/KCNA4 (20%), Kv11/hERG (24%), and Shaker-IR (27%).

name: Potassium channel toxin epsilon-KTx 1.2
description: Potassium channel blocker. At 3 uM, this toxin blocks voltage-gated potassium channels rKv1.2/KCNA2 (5%), hKv1.3/KCNA3 (10%),rKv1.4/KCNA4 (20%), Kv11/hERG (24%), and Shaker-IR (27%).

name: Potassium channel toxin epsilon-KTx 1.1
description: Potassium channel blocker. At 3 uM, this toxin blocks voltage-independently voltage-gated potassium channels rKv1.2/KCNA2 (25%), hKv1.3/KCNA3 (27%), rKv4.2/KCND2 (25%), Kv10.1/KCNH1/EAG1 (15%), Kv11/hERG (12%), and Shaker-IR (10%). On hKv1.3/KCNA3, the IC(50) is 17.1 +-3.3 uM.

name: Snake venom serine protease serpentokallikrein-2
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease serpentokallikrein-1
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 beta-bungarotoxin A4 chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows presynaptic neurotoxicity. The A chain has phospholipase activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 15.1
description: Blocker of voltage-gated potassium channels (600 nM of the toxin induces a block of 25% of hERG currents) (PubMed:18687312). In adult rat brain, it blocks the transient potassium channels in cerebellum granular cells. Blocks potassium channels by a simple 'plugging mechanism', in which a single toxin molecule finds a specific receptor site in the external vestibule of the potassium channel and thereby occludes the outer entry to the potassium conducting pore (PubMed:11018665).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 Cvv-N6
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that induces myonecrosis in mice activities and moderate edema-inducing activity in rat paws. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Muscarinic m2-toxin
description: Blocks M2 muscarinic acetylcholine receptors (CHRM2). Fully blocks the binding of N-methylscopolamine (NMS) and oxotremorine-M to M2 receptors, slightly increased NMS binding to M1 receptors.

name: Muscarinic m1-toxin4
description: Binds irreversibly and specifically to M1 (CHRM1) muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, blocking further binding of antagonists and preventing the action of agonists.

name: Muscarinic m1-toxin3
description: Binds irreversibly and specifically to M1 (CHRM1) muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, blocking further binding of antagonists and preventing the action of agonists.

name: Muscarinic m1-toxin2
description: Binds irreversibly and specifically to M1 (CHRM1) muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, blocking further binding of antagonists and preventing the action of agonists.

name: Alpha-latrotoxin-Lh1a
description: Presynaptic neurotoxin that induces exhaustive neurotransmitter release from vertebrate (but not invertebrate) nerve terminals and endocrine cells. Binds to neurexin-1-alpha (NRXN1), adhesion G protein-coupled receptor L1 (ADGRL1, also known as latrophilin-1), and receptor-type tyrosine-protein phosphatase S (PTPRS), and induces neurotransmitter exocytosis through two calcium-dependent mechanisms (membrane pore formation and signaling via latrophilin) and a yet to be defined calcium-independent mechanism (By similarity). Induces rapid muscle contracture and loss of twitch tension when added to the isolated and indirectly stimulated chick biventer cervicis nerve-muscle preparation.

name: U20-lycotoxin-Ls1d
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog M1-3-3
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic activity. Is myotoxic (By similarity).

name: Toxin Aam3
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 S1E6-c
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Alpha-fibrinogenase A2
description: Snake venom serine protease that cleaves fibrinogen Aalpha chain (FGA), partially cleaves Bbeta chain (FGB) and has no activity on gamma chain. Is more potent than A3 alpha-fibrinogenases and less potent than A1.

name: Alpha-fibrinogenase A3
