description: Snake venom serine protease that cleaves fibrinogen Aalpha chain (FGA), partially cleaves Bbeta chain (FGB) and has no activity on gamma chain. Is less potent than A1 and A2 alpha-fibrinogenases.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein 6
description: May be a phenoloxidase inhibitor that stabilizes or inhibits venom phenoloxidase while it is stored in the venom sac.

name: Pacifastin-like protease inhibitor cvp4
description: Probable serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor cvp2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein 1
description: May be a phenoloxidase inhibitor that stabilizes or inhibits venom phenoloxidase while it is stored in the venom sac.

name: Imperatoxin-A
description: Affects the activity of ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channels RyR1, RyR2 and RyR3. At lower concentrations the toxin increases full openings of the RyRs, and at higher concentrations it inhibits full openings and induce openings to subconductance levels and reduces the number of full conductance openings. The different actions may be attributed to the toxins binding at different sites on the RyRs, with binding at a high-affinity site mediating the increase in full openings and the induction of subconductance states evoked upon binding to a lower-affinity site.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 5.4
description: Blocks small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels in pyramidal neurons of the hippocampus. Displays a unique, remarkable selectivity for SK2/KCNN2 versus SK1/KCNN1 and SK3/KCNN3 channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 6.3
description: Potently blocks voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 and Kv1.3/KCNA3. Mildly blocks intermediate (IK) conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa3.1/KCNN4) and ERG1/Kv11.1/KCNH2.

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin BotIT6
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Toxin Cll7
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Beta-toxin BotIT2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin specifically acts by inducing a new current with very slow activation/deactivation kinetics due to the transformation of normal fast channels into slow ones. It possess properties of excitatory and depressant toxins. It is highly active on insects and less active on mammals.

name: L-amino-acid oxidase
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids, thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits diverse biological activities, such as hemorrhage, hemolysis, edema, apoptosis of vascular endothelial cells or tumor cell lines, antibacterial and antiparasitic activities, as well as regulation of platelet aggregation. Effects of snake L-amino oxidases on platelets are controversial, since they either induce aggregation or inhibit agonist-induced aggregation. These different effects are probably due to different experimental conditions (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Mr1.3
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Toxin CngtIV
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin CngtIII
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Cll1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). This toxin is only active on crustaceans.

name: Beta-toxin Cll1m
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Leiurutoxin-3
description: Blocker of potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 16.5
description: Augments responses to direct muscle stimulation probably by blocking calcium-activated potassium channels.

name: Beta-toxin Cn5
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is lethal to crustaceans (freshwater crayfish (Cambarellus montezumae spp.)), it provokes a reversible paralysis to insects (crickets (Achaeta spp.)), but is not toxic to mice. At high concentrations, it does displace the (beta) mammal-specific toxin Cn2 from rat brain synaptosomes.

name: Beta-toxin Cn4
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin affects the activation mechanism of sodium channels of squid axon. It also competes with Cn2 in rat brain synaptosomes. Is lethal to mice.

name: Neurotoxin-2
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This toxin is active against mammals.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ml20.3
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ml20.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ms20.5
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Vt20.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Rt20.2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Rt20.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin specifically blocks mammalian neuronal nAChR of the alpha-7/CHRNA7, alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2 and alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2 subtypes (By similarity).

name: Sodium channel alpha-toxin Acra8
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 26.3
description: Recombinant toxin that reversibly inhibits the potassium current of mKv1.3/KCNA3 channel stably expressed in COS7 cells (IC(50)=150 nM).

name: Disintegrin halysin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Disintegrin triflavin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Venom peptide Tv1
description: Injections of 20 uM of this synthetic peptide (Ile) causes partial paralysis to polychaete worms (Nereis virens), the natural prey of terebrid snails (PubMed:24713808). This paralysis may be due to an inhibition of nicotinic receptors at the neuromuscular junction (Probable).

name: Neurotoxin beta-KTx 17
description: Isoform 1 has a very weak effect to block voltage-gated potassium channel Kv1.1/KCNA1.

name: Three-finger muscarinic toxin 1
description: Shows a non-competitive interaction with adrenergic and muscarinic receptors. Binds to alpha-2b (ADRA2B) (IC(50)=2.3 nM), alpha-1a (ADRA1A), alpha-1b (ADRA1B), and alpha-2c (ADRA2C) adrenergic receptors. Reversibly binds to M1 (CHRM1) muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, probably by interacting with the orthosteric site (PubMed:7778123, PubMed:12488533, PubMed:24793485). Also reveals a slightly weaker effect at M3 (CHRM3) (PubMed:7778123) and M4 (CHRM4) receptors (PubMed:12488533, PubMed:24793485). The order of potency is ADRA2B>>CHRM1>ADRA1A>ADRA1B>ADRA2C/CHRM4 (PubMed:24793485).

name: Muscarinic toxin 3
description: Potent antagonist (IC(50)=1-10 nM) of M4 (CHRM4) muscarinic receptors (PubMed:8154745, PubMed:24793485,PubMed:21557730), and CHRM1, ADRA1A (PubMed:8154745), ADRA2A and ADRA2C adrenergic receptors. Also antagonises ADRA1B and ADRA1D adrenergic receptors with a 10-times lower affinity (PubMed:24793485).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 15.4
description: Blocker of A-type voltage-gated potassium channels of cerebellar granular cells. The occlusion of the outer entry of the K(+) conducting pore is partially reversible and affects both open and closed channels. It shares the same target in rat brain than BmTX3 (AC Q8I0L5) and AmmTX3 (AC P60208).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme cerastotin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that preferentially cleaves the alpha-chain of fibrinogen (FGA). Induce platelet aggregation in the presence of exogenous fibrinogen. Possesses esterase and amidolytic activities.

name: Toxin GaTx1
description: Chloride channel ligand. Potently and reversibly inhibits CFTR chloride channels when the channels are in the interburst closed state. May also interact with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex may be then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation.

name: Kappa-conotoxin ViTx
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels. This toxin inhibits the mammalian potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 and Kv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Phospholipase A2 acanmyotoxin-1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has myotoxic activity but no significant neurotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2 acanmyotoxin-3
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has myotoxic activity but no significant neurotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2 acanmyotoxin-2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has myotoxic activity but no significant neurotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Beta-insect excitatory toxin LqqIT1
description: Excitatory insect beta-toxins induce a spastic paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin induces a fast excitatory contraction paralysis on fly larvae. It is active only on insects.

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin LqqIT2
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. Aside from typical beta-toxin effects, this toxin also affects the inactivation process and ion selectivity of the insect voltage-gated sodium channel. This toxin is active only on insects. Is active on the insect voltage-gated sodium channel para.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor
description: Serine protease inhibitor that inhibits chymotrypsin.

name: Disintegrin applaggin
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen.

name: Phospholipase D LspaSicTox-alphaIA2iii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2biii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2bii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2bv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2biv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2bvi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspaSicTox-alphaIA2ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LspaSicTox-alphaIA2i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: C-type lectin LmsL
description: Galactose-binding protein which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. Is a calcium-dependent lectin. Shows high hemagglutinating activity, that is inhibited by lactose, galactose and inositol.

name: Snaclec GPIB-binding protein subunit beta
description: Binds to platelet GPIb (subunit alpha) (GP1BA) and functions as a receptor blocker for vWF binding to GPIb. The platelet GPIb-binding site resides on the GPIB-BP subunit beta and not on the alpha subunit. At a final concentration of 104 nM totally abolishes vWF-dependent shear-induced platelet aggregation (SIPA) at a high shear stress, but had no effect on SIPA at a low shear stress.

name: Snaclec GPIB-binding protein subunit alpha
description: Binds to platelet GPIb (subunit alpha) (GP1BA) and functions as a receptor blocker for vWF binding to GPIb. The platelet GPIb-binding site resides on the GPIB-BP subunit beta and not on the alpha subunit. At a final concentration of 104 nM totally abolishes vWF-dependent shear-induced platelet aggregation (SIPA) at a high shear stress, but had no effect on SIPA at a low shear stress.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit B
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to coagulation factor IX (F9) and coagulation factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium. It may bind the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry. The dissociation constant (K(d)) are 6.6 nM for factor IX (F9) and 125 nM for factor X (F10). Does not bind carbohydrates.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX/factor X-binding protein subunit A
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to coagulation factor IX (F9) and coagulation factor X (F10) in the presence of calcium. It may bind the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factors with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry. The dissociation constant (K(d)) are 6.6 nM for factor IX (F9) and 125 nM for factor X (F10). Does not bind carbohydrates.

name: Phospholipase A1 2
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A1 3
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A1 1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: Mu-conotoxin Lt5d
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). This toxin inhibits tetrodotoxin(TTX)-sensitive sodium channels, but does not affect TTX-resistant sodium channels. Reduces the amplitude of currents without changing the activation and inactivation kinetics of currents.

name: Melittin
description: Main toxin of bee venom with strong hemolytic activity. Integrates into cell membranes and has multiple effects, probably, as a result of its interaction with negatively charged phospholipids. It inhibits well known transport pumps such as the Na(+)-K(+)-ATPase and the H(+)-K(+)-ATPase. Increases the permeability of cell membranes to ions, particularly Na(+) and indirectly Ca(2+), because of the Na(+)-Ca(2+)-exchange (By similarity).

name: Snaclec tokaracetin subunit beta
description: Platelet antagonist that specifically and reversibly binds to a site on platelet glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA) close to or identical with the site for vWF binding. It inhibits the binding of vWF to platelets and vWF-dependent shear-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Disintegrin ussuristatin-1
description: Strongly suppress platelet aggregation induced by ADP, collagen, thrombin, and epinephrine (IC(50)=17-33 nM). Also dose-dependently inhibits the adhesion of human melanoma cells to fibrinogen and fibronectin.

name: Bradykinin potentiating and C-type natriuretic peptides
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide 10c: inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) by a preferential interaction with its C-domain. May also potentiate the hypotensive effects of bradykinin.

name: Snaclec 1
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec 2
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec 3
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin 1
description: Induces capillary permeability and angiogenesis through VEGF receptor (KDR/VEGFR-2) signaling.

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin 2
description: Induces capillary permeability and angiogenesis through VEGF receptor (KDR/VEGFR-2) signaling.

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein 2
description: Weakly blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1m
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1n
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1o
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1p
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1i
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1j
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1k
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1l
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: U2-agatoxin-Ao1g
description: Insect active toxin causing rapid but reversible paralysis in crickets. No activity shown in mammals. Does not show effect on mammalian voltage-gated calcium channels (By similarity).

name: Opiscorpine-1
description: The short synthetic peptide (20-54) has antimicrobial activity against the yeasts F.culmorum (IC(50)=8.8 uM) and F.oxysporum (IC(50)=10 uM) P.aeruginosa, and the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli.

name: Opiscorpine-2
description: Has antimicrobial activity against yeasts and bacteria.

name: Probable toxin Lqh 8/6
description: Toxin with unknown function in healthy organisms. On glioma cells, interacts with chloride channels (probably ClC-3/CLCN3) and MMP2 at the surface of glioma cells. This complex is then internalized via caveolae, thus inhibiting the chloride channels necessary for cell shrinkage and tumor propagation (By similarity).

name: Alpha-conotoxin PIVA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin has higher affinity for the adult subtype (alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta subunits) (IC(50)=2.3 nM) of the receptor than for the fetal subtype (alpha-1/beta-1/epsilon/delta subunits) (IC(50)=22 nM).

name: Snake venom serine protease 3
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Snake venom serine protease 2
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey (By similarity). Has weak fibrinogen clotting activity. Possesses amidolysis activity towards S-2251 (substrate for plasmin) but has no hydrolytic activity with S-2302 (plasma kalikrein substrate) or S-2238 (thrombin substrate).

name: Omega-conotoxin MVIIB
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin MVIIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels. This toxin blocks Cav2.2/CACNA1B calcium channels (IC(50)=180 nM). When injected in mamals, show adverse effects, such as tremor, diminution of spontaneous locomotor activity and bad coordinated locomotion (PubMed:26344359).

name: Arg-conopressin S
description: Targets vasopressin-oxytocin related receptors.

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-alphaIA1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Omega-conotoxins GVIIA/GVIIB
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Mu-conotoxin GIIIC
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: Phospholipase A2
description: PA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides. Activity determined by an indirect hemolysis test and against chromogenic substrate 4-nitro-3-octanoyloxybenzoic acid (4N30BA).

name: Hyaluronidase CdtHya1
description: Snake venom endo-hyaluronidase that degrades hyaluronan to smaller oligosaccharide fragments. In venom, it is not toxic by itself, but increases the diffusion of other venom proteins such as crotoxin (a neurotoxic and myotoxic PLA2) by degrading the extracellular matrix. In addition, it displays antiedematogenic activity, since it significantly diminishes the oedematogenic activity of crotoxin (probably by direct substrate hydrolysis, since hayluronan possesses strong water-binding capacity).

name: Neurotoxin BmK-M10
description: Binds to voltage-dependent sodium channels (Nav) and voltage-dependent delayed rectifier potassium channels and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Administration to mice at a dosage of 0.8 mg/kg produces an analgesic effect.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Conotoxin p5a
description: Low levels of the peptide injected into male specimens of the Siamese fighting fish causes an immediate aggressive display in this fish in response to their reflection when placed in a mirrored aquarium; High levels of the peptide suppressed this behavior. No effect is observed when injected into mice.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 1
description: Serine protease inhibitor that principally inhibits trypsin (Ki=0.34 nM). Also inhibits alpha-chymotrypsin (Ki=270 nM), plasmin, plasma and pancreatic kallikrein.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 3
description: Serine protease inhibitor that principally inhibits alpha-chymotrypsin (Ki=4.3 nM). Shows weak inhibition on trypsin (Ki=5100 nM), and plasma kallikrein.

name: Phospholipase A1 2
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A2 (EC 3.1.1.4) and phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activities.

name: Rho-elapitoxin-Da1b
description: Non-competitive antagonist of alpha-2 adrenergic receptors (ADRA2) in smooth muscles (PubMed:20659106), and partial antagonist of D3 dopamine receptors (DRD3) (inhibits 25% of methylspiperone binding to this receptor). Also shows a low antagonism on D2 dopamine receptors (DRD2) (short isoforms) (PubMed:24793485). Shows affinity of 14 nM, 73 nM, and 38 nM for ADRA2A, ADRA2B, and ADRA2C, respectively (PubMed:20659106). Increases heart rate and blood catecholamine concentrations (PubMed:21419153).

name: Neurotoxin PRTx26An0C3
description: Neurotoxin. Causes spastic paralysis and death in mice. Moderate inhibitor of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like 2
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like 6
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like 9
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like 15
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: U20-lycotoxin-Ls1b
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: U20-lycotoxin-Ls1c
description: Has antibacterial activity.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like 12
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like C1.1
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Eumenine mastoparan-ER
description: Linear cationic alpha-helical peptide that acts as antimicrobial peptide by forming pore in membrane. Has antibacterial activities against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative strains. Has more potent activities against the yeast C.albicans. Shows moderate mast cell degranulation and leishmanicidal activities. Has a very low hemolytic activity.

name: Eumenine mastoparan-EF
description: Linear cationic alpha-helical peptide that acts as antimicrobial peptide by forming pore in membrane. Has antibacterial activities against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative strains. Has more potent activities against the yeast C.albicans. Shows moderate mast cell degranulation and leishmanicidal activities. Has a very low hemolytic activity.

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin IC1
description: Induces capillary permeability through VEGF receptor (KDR/VEGFR-2) signaling. May also induce angiogenesis.

name: Bradykinin inhibitor peptide
description: Bradykinin inhibitor peptide antagonizes the vasodilatory actions of bradykinin at the B2 bradykinin receptor (BDKRB2).

name: Taicatoxin, alpha-neurotoxin-like component
description: The heterotrimer blocks the voltage-dependent L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1) from the heart, and the small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCa2/KCNN) in the chromaffin cells and in the brain. Is very toxic to mice.

name: Eumenitin-R
description: Linear cationic alpha-helical peptide that acts as antimicrobial peptide by forming pore in membrane. Has antibacterial activities against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative strains. Has more potent activities against the yeast C.albicans. Shows moderate mast cell degranulation and leishmanicidal activities. Has a very low hemolytic activity.

name: Eumenitin-F
description: Linear cationic alpha-helical peptide that acts as antimicrobial peptide by forming pore in membrane. Has antibacterial activities against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative strains. Has more potent activities against the yeast C.albicans. Shows moderate mast cell degranulation and leishmanicidal activities. Has a very low hemolytic activity.

name: Toxin OAIP 5
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor. Shows insecticidal activity when injected into mealworms.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Spl1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor. Shows insecticidal activity when injected into mealworms.

name: Astacin-like metalloprotease toxin 4
description: Zinc metalloprotease. Provoques deadhesion of endothelial cells from cell cultures, and also degradation of fibronectin, fibrinogen and gelatin in vitro. Its role in the venom is not fully understood but it might act as a spreading factor that facilitates diffusion of other venom toxins. Alternatively, it might be involved in the proteolytic processing of other venom toxins or it might play a role in extra-oral digestion of prey (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LiRecDT7
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin in a concentration-dependent manner. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Has hemolytic activity in human erythrocytes in a dose-dependent manner. In vivo, this toxin induces dermonecrosis, edema, hemorrhage, massive inflammatory response, as well as blood vessel permeability. In addition, thrombus formation has also been detected in dermal blood vessels.

name: Astacin-like metalloprotease toxin 5
description: Zinc metalloprotease. Provoques deadhesion of endothelial cells from cell cultures, and also degradation of fibronectin, fibrinogen and gelatin in vitro. Its role in the venom is not fully understood but it might act as a spreading factor that facilitates diffusion of other venom toxins. Alternatively, it might be involved in the proteolytic processing of other venom toxins or it might play a role in extra-oral digestion of prey (By similarity).

name: Orally active insecticidal peptide-3
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor. Shows insecticidal activity when injected into mealworms.

name: Orally active insecticidal peptide
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor. Shows insecticidal activity when injected into mealworms.

name: Long neurotoxin homolog TA-bm16
description: Exhibits M2 muscarinic acetylcholine receptor (CHRM2)-blocking activity, but has a weak binding activity toward nicotinic AChR. Moreover, it inhibits collagen-induced platelet aggregation.

name: Kappa-5-bungarotoxin
description: Postsynaptic neurotoxin that binds and inhibits neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) with high affinity (IC(50)<100 nM). Is a selective, and slowly reversible antagonist of alpha-3/CHRNA3-containing and some alpha-4/CHRNA4-containing AChRs.

name: Kappa-4-bungarotoxin
description: Postsynaptic neurotoxin that binds and inhibits neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) with high affinity (IC(50)<100 nM). Is a selective, and slowly reversible antagonist of alpha-3/CHRNA3-containing and some alpha-4/CHRNA4-containing AChRs.

name: Snaclec coagulation factor IX-binding protein subunit A
description: Anticoagulant protein which binds to the gamma-carboxyglutamic acid-domain regions of factor IX (F9) (but not factor X) in the presence of calcium with a 1 to 1 stoichiometry.

name: Snaclec flavocetin-A subunit alpha
description: Strong platelet aggregation inhibitor. Binds specifically to platelet glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA) with high affinity and inhibits vWF-dependent platelet aggregation (PubMed:7599152). Has also been observed to induce small agglutinates in washed platelets by binding to GPIb (PubMed:10688335).

name: Antimicrobial peptide AcrAP1
description: Has antimicrobial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria S.aureus (MIC=8 uM) and the yeast C.albicans (MIC=16 uM). Causes hemolysis on horse erythrocytes (64 uM for 100% hemolysis). Minimum bactericidal concentrations have also been tested against S.aureus and is four-fold higher (MBC=32 uM).

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin vammin
description: Induces angiogenesis, probably through VEGF receptor (KDR/VEGFR-2) signaling, as well as drastic hypotension. The hypotension is mediated by nitric oxide (NO), which is produced by VEGF-activated endothelium NO synthase. May also induce capillary permeability.

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin
description: Strongly increases vascular permeability, and weakly stimulates angiogenesis. Interacts with human VEGF receptor-1 (FLT1) with a high affinity, whereas it binds to human VEGF receptor-2 (KDR) with a low affinity. Stimulates autophosphorylation of VEGF receptor-1 (VEGFR-1/FLT1), and VEGF receptor-2 (VEGFR-2/KDR).

name: Snake venom vascular endothelial growth factor toxin VR-1
description: Induces angiogenesis probably through VEGF receptor (KDR/VEGFR-2) signaling, as well as drastic hypotension. The hypotension is mediated by nitric oxide, which is produced by VEGF-activated endothelium NO synthase. May also induce capillary permeability.

name: Snaclec flavocetin-A subunit beta
description: Strong platelet aggregation inhibitor. Binds specifically to platelet glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA) with high affinity and inhibits vWF-dependent platelet aggregation (PubMed:7599152). Has also been observed to induce small agglutinates in washed platelets by binding to GPIb (PubMed:10688335).

name: Turripeptide OL55
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Turripeptide OL55-like
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog Cax-K49
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic activity, but displays edema-inducing activities and induces local swelling when injected on rat paw.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme cerastocytin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease which potently induces platelet aggregation and has fibrinogenolytic activities. Clots purified fibrinogen and hydrolyzes alpha-chains (FGA). High concentrations of this enzyme also cleave prothrombin (F2) and factor X (F10). Is also able to activate factor XIII (F8).

name: Toxin Tst3
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Hyaluronidase
description: Possesses high activity against hyaluronan in vitro.

name: Lysozyme-like peptide
description: Lysozymes have primarily a bacteriolytic function.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx
description: Blocks voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: U11-ctenitoxin-Pn1b
description: Non-toxic to mice.

name: U7-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Causes immediate spastic paralysis and death in mice within 1 min of injection at dose levels of 1.5 ug per mouse.

name: U23-ctenitoxin-Pn1a
description: Non-toxic to mice.

name: U8-theraphotoxin-Hs1a
description: Probable secreted venom neurotoxin.

name: U8-theraphotoxin-Hs1b
description: Probable secreted venom neurotoxin.

name: Omwaprin-b
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor blackelin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Venom prothrombin activator nigrarin-D
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This protein is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa (By similarity).

name: U4-ctenitoxin-Pr1a
description: Neurotoxin. Causes spastic paralysis and death in mice. Moderate inhibitor of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1).

name: U9-ctenitoxin-Pr1a
description: Non-toxic to mice and insects.

name: U13-ctenitoxin-Pn1a
description: Acts as a neurotoxin.

name: U1-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: Neurotoxin. Causes rapid general flaccid paralysis and death in mice at dose levels of 5 ug per mouse.

name: U4-ctenitoxin-Pk1a
description: Neurotoxin. Causes spastic paralysis and death in mice within 10 minutes at dose levels of 3 ug per mouse.

name: Phospholipase A1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: C-type lectin
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaIB2bi
description: Converts lysophosphatidylcholine and sphingomyelin to cyclic phosphatidic acids. This enzyme was previously described to catalyze the cleavage of choline by hydrolysis, but only transphosphatidylation products (cyclic products but no hydrolysis products) have been observed (PubMed:24009677). Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hmo1a
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hmo1b
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hmo1c
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-hexatoxin-Hmo1d
description: Inhibits insect, but not mammalian, voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Kappa-hexatoxin-Hmo1d
description: This excitatory toxin inhibits insect calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channels (Slo-type).

name: U2-ctenitoxin-Pn1b
description: Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: Delta-ctenitoxin-Pn2c
description: Reversible inhibitor of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Delays the fast inactivation kinetics of neuronal-type sodium channels. Causes scratching, lacrimation, hypersalivation, sweating and agitation followed by spastic paralysis of the anterior and posterior extremities and death at dose levels of 0.24 mg/mouse. Insecticidal to the larval and adult forms of the house fly.

name: Phospholipase D LiSicTox-betaIA1i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel blood vessel permeability. Causes swelling and erythema.

name: Phospholipase A1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A2 homolog 1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic and anticoagulant activities. In mice, it induces conspicuous local myonecrosis, edema, and a systemic interleukin-6 response. In vitro, it is cytolytic upon myoblasts, and weakly bactericidal.

name: U4-theraphotoxin-Hhn1p
description: Postsynaptic neurotoxin.

name: Snaclec purpureotin subunit beta
description: Snaclec that induces platelet aggregation without any cofactor in a dose-dependent manner. Its platelet aggregation effect is blocked by echicetin, suggesting it is a GPIb-binding protein which binds to the same or a closely related GPIb site on platelets as echicetin.

name: Imcroporin
description: Has potent antibacterial activity against Gram-positive bacteria M.luteus, B.thuringiensis, S.aureus and B.subtilis, but not Gram-negative bacteria. Shows a weak cytotoxicity effect against mammalian cell lines and relatively low hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes.

name: Cytotoxin 1
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 5
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 9
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 1
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 4
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 10
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 1
description: This three-finger cytotoxin is a basic protein that interacts and penetrates into the cell membrane, with the tips of all the three loops. Cytotoxins which have a 'Pro-30' (P-type) interacts with membrane stronger that those which have a Ser-28 (S-type). CTI interacts with membrane weaker than CTII.

name: Cytotoxin 3
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Cytotoxin 3
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 1.9
description: Potent selective inhibitor of Kv1/KCNA voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.6
description: Potent inhibitor of Kv1/KCNA voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: U9-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 2.5
description: Potent selective inhibitor of Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, Kv1.3/KCNA3 voltage-gated potassium channels. Weak inhibitor of Kv1.6/KCNA6 potassium channel.

name: Alpha-conotoxin EIIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and inhibit them. This peptide potently blocks muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNG-CHRND), and has no effect on neuronal receptors. It is able to totally displace [125I]-Bgtx from the Torpedo receptor with a complete inhibition in the high micromolar range. It produces a biphasic inhibition curve which fits nicely with a two-site model (Ki of 0.46 and 105 nM).

name: Contulakin-G
description: Acts as an agonist of neurotensin receptors. It binds to human neurotensin type 1 receptor (NTSR1), rat neurotensin types 1 and 2 receptors (NTSR1/NTSR2) and mouse neurotensin type 3 receptor (SORT1).

name: Natriuretic peptide HsNP-b
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Natriuretic peptide NsNP-b
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Natriuretic peptide HsNP-a
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Natriuretic peptide TcNP-a
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Natriuretic peptide NsNP-a
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog acutohaemolysin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that shows myotoxic activity. Lacks both catalytic and direct hemolytic activity.

name: Long neurotoxin 20
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 28
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 18
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 161
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor 87
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Kunitz serine protease inhibitor Pr-mulgin 3
description: Serine protease inhibitor that acts against trypsin (EC(50)=10 nM, Ki=5nM), and plasmin (EC(50)=200 nM, Ki=100 nM).

name: Kunitz serine protease inhibitor Pr-mulgin 2
description: Serine protease inhibitor that acts against trypsin (EC(50)=10 nM, Ki=5nM), chymotrypsin (EC(50)=100 nM, Ki=40 nM), and plasmin (EC(50)=100 nM, Ki=40 nM).

name: Kunitz serine protease inhibitor Pr-mulgin 1
description: Specifically inhibits MMP2 activity (EC(50)=100 nM and Ki=60 nM).

name: Snake venom serine protease HS114
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: U10-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Antagonist of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1).

name: U10-ctenitoxin-Co1b
description: Antagonist of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1).

name: U12-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: U15-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: U6-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Antagonist of L-type calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1).

name: U1-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal (By similarity). This product has not been identified in the venom.

name: Disintegrin acostatin-alpha
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation in human platelet-rich plasma.

name: U13-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Neurotoxin.

name: Disintegrin piscivostatin-alpha
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits both ADP-induced platelet aggregation and platelet aggregate dissociation in human platelet-rich plasma.

name: Cytotoxin 4b
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Alpha-bungarotoxin isoform V31
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Amphipathic peptide OcyC1
description: Amphipathic peptide OcyC1: antimicrobial peptide that inhibits the growth of Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Reg1b/Reg1c
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2ai
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2aiii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaIA2aii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: U10-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 1
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U10-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 3
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Cg1d 1
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U9-theraphotoxin-Cg1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Cg1d 2
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U8-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 1
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U8-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 2
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U1-theraphotoxin-Cg1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIB1b
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIB2a
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIB4
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIB1a
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaVI1ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIB3
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LarSicTox-alphaVII1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LhSicTox-alphaVI1i
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIB2b
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D StSicTox-betaIC1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters (By similarity).

name: Venom plasminogen activator LV-PA
description: Snake venom serine protease that activates plasminogen. Weakly hydrolyzes the alpha chain of human fibrinogen without releasing fibrinopeptide A. Does not hydrolyze plasma kallikrein or factor Xa. Does not clot fibrinogen. Does not affect platelet function. Induces hypotensive effects on rats.

name: Alpha-conotoxin PeIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This synthetic peptide potently and reversibly blocks alpha-9-alpha-10 nAChR (IC(50)=6.9-54.9 nM), alpha-3-beta-2 (IC(50)=9.7-97.5 nM) and alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-2-beta-3 (IC(50)=11.1-17.2 nM) (PubMed:15983035, PubMed:21252227, PubMed:22914547, PubMed:23846688). Also shows a weak inhibition of alpha-6/alpha-3-beta-4 (IC(50)=147 nM) and alpha-3-beta-4 (IC(50)=480-1500 nM) (PubMed:15983035, PubMed:22914547). This synthetic toxin also inhibits N-type calcium channels (Ca2.2/CACNA1B) (IC(50)=1.1 nM) via the activation of the G protein-coupled GABA(B) receptor in DRG neurons (PubMed:21252227).

name: Ohanin-like protein
description: Neurotoxin.

name: Bradykinin-potentiating and C-type natriuretic peptides
description: Bradykinin-potentiating peptide both inhibits the activity of the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) and enhances the action of bradykinin by inhibiting the peptidases that inactivate it. It acts as an indirect hypotensive agent (By similarity).

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1i
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.1 mg/kg body weight.

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1a
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.5 mg/kg body weight. Orally active against larvae of the tomato moth (Laconobia oleracea), the rice brown planthopper (Nilaparvata lugens), and the peach-potato aphid (Myzus persicae) when fused to snowdrop lectin.

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1b
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.25 mg/kg body weight.

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1c
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.25 mg/kg body weight (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A2 II-5b
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that exhibits weak enzymatic activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: U2-segestritoxin-Sf1e
description: Insecticidal toxin. Causes flaccid paralysis followed by death when injected into Heliothis virescens larvae. Does not induce any toxic effects when injected intravenously into adult mice at a dose of 1.25 mg/kg body weight (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PLA-B'
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acetylcholinesterase
description: Terminates signal transduction at the neuromuscular junction by rapid hydrolysis of the acetylcholine released into the synaptic cleft.

name: Phospholipase A2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that strongly inhibits platelet aggregation and has a strong anticoagulant activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Phospholipase A2 taicatoxin
description: Heterotrimer: blocks the voltage-dependent L-type calcium channels from the heart, and the small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels in the chromaffin cells and in the brain. Is very toxic to mice.

name: Psi-conotoxin PIIIF
description: Psi-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, and act as non-competitive antagonist of nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR). Is less toxic than Psi-conotoxin PIIIE.

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1a
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that modulates the insect Nav channel (DmNaV1/tipE (para/tipE)) in a unique manner, with both the activation and inactivation processes being affected. The voltage dependence of activation is shifted toward more hyperpolarized potentials (analogous to site 4 toxins) and a non-inactivating persistent sodium current is induced (site 3-like action). Interestingly, both effects take place in a voltage-dependent manner, producing a bell-shaped curve between -80 and 0 mV. Compared to beta/delta-agatoxin-1 to -3, this toxin appears to affect the insect sodium channel only weakly.

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1d
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons (By similarity).

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1e
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons (By similarity).

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1b
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons (By similarity).

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1c
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that modulates the insect Nav channel (DmNaV1/tipE (para/tipE)) in a unique manner, with both the activation and inactivation processes being affected. The voltage dependence of activation is shifted toward more hyperpolarized potentials (analogous to site 4 toxins) and a non-inactivating persistent sodium current is induced (site 3-like action). Interestingly, both effects take place in a voltage-dependent manner, producing a bell-shaped curve between -80 and 0 mV.

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1h
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons (By similarity).

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1i
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons (By similarity).

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1f
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that modulates the insect Nav channel (DmNaV1/tipE (para/tipE)) in a unique manner, with both the activation and inactivation processes being affected. The voltage dependence of activation is shifted toward more hyperpolarized potentials (analogous to site 4 toxins) and a non-inactivating persistent sodium current is induced (site 3-like action). Interestingly, both effects take place in a voltage-dependent manner, producing a bell-shaped curve between -80 and 0 mV. In vivo, induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects.

name: U3-agatoxin-Ao1g
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that modulates the insect Nav channel (DmNaV1/tipE (para/tipE)) in a unique manner, with both the activation and inactivation processes being affected. The voltage dependence of activation is shifted toward more hyperpolarized potentials (analogous to site 4 toxins) and a non-inactivating persistent sodium current is induced (site 3-like action). Interestingly, both effects take place in a voltage-dependent manner, producing a bell-shaped curve between -80 and 0 mV.

name: U1-TRTX-Sp1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor. Shows insecticidal activity. Acts synergistically with the neonicotinoid insecticide imidacloprid. Is neither a repellent that repels insects nor an attractant that is preferentially consumed by insects. Is very stable.

name: Omwaprin-a
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has antibacterial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria B.megaterium and S.warneri. Has no antibacterial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria B.thuringiensis, S.aureus and S.clavuligerus, or the Gram-negative bacteria E.coli and A.tumefaciens. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like proatherocytin
description: Stimulates platelet aggregation through activation of PAR-1 (F2R).

name: Neurotoxin BmK AGAP-SYPU2
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). Shows analgesic activity (ED(50) is 1.42 mg/kg) and antitumor activity against Ehrlich ascites tumor and fibrosarcoma models in vivo.

name: Long neurotoxin 3FTx-Oxy1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: C-type lectin 6
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Alpha-insect toxin BotIT1
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. This contractive toxin is highly toxic to insects and barely toxic to mammals.

name: Beta-insect depressant toxin BotIT5
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Venom prothrombin activator hopsarin-D
description: Snake prothrombin activator that attacks the hemostatic system of prey. This protein is functionally similar to blood coagulation factor Xa. The procoagulant activity of hopsarin-D is approximately 10-fold lower than that of trocarin-D and FXa.

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like Sx11.2
description: Modulator of potassium channels, specifically up-modulates the calcium and voltage-gated BK channels, has no effect on single channel conductance, but increases the open probability of BK channels.

name: Iota-conotoxin-like S11.2
description: Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of activation to more hyperpolarized levels. Produces general excitatory symptoms (By similarity).

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like Em11.10
description: Inhibits the vertebrate voltage-gated potassium channels Kv1.1/KCNA1 and Kv1.3/KCNA3.

name: Natriuretic peptide
description: Snake venom natriuretic peptide that exhibits hypotensive and vasodepressor activity. Acts by activating natriuretic receptors (NPR1 and/or NPR2 and/or NPR3) (By similarity).

name: Three finger toxin MALT0066C
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Three-finger toxin MALT0059C
description: Neurotoxin. Blocks muscular nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR).

name: Astacin-like metalloprotease toxin 2
description: Zinc metalloprotease. Provoques deadhesion of endothelial cells from cell cultures, and also degradation of fibronectin, fibrinogen and gelatin in vitro. Its role in the venom is not fully understood but it might act as a spreading factor that facilitates diffusion of other venom toxins. Alternatively, it might be involved in the proteolytic processing of other venom toxins or it might play a role in extra-oral digestion of prey (By similarity).

name: Snaclec rhodocetin subunit gamma
description: Potent inhibitor of collagen-induced platelet aggregation. It acts by binding to the integrin alpha2A domain and blocks collagen binding to integrin alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1). The gamma/delta subunits mainly contribute to this activity.

name: Con-Ins Im2
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Cytotoxin 3
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Toxin Tst2
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). Is toxic to mice (PubMed:8611151).

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Translationally-controlled tumor protein homolog
description: Venom protein that causes edema, enhances vascular permeability and is likely related to the inflammatory activity of the venom.

name: Snaclec bothrojaracin subunit alpha
description: This potent antithrombotic agent acts in a calcium-independent manner. Exerts its anticoagulant effect by two distinct mechanisms. It binds to activated thrombin through exosite 1, blocking fibrinogen clotting, platelet activation, factor V activation and other effects, and it interacts with prothrombin (F2), decreasing its proteolytic activation -especially in the presence of factor Va. In vivo, intravenous injection before thrombosis induction causes a significant decrease in thrombus weight. Furthermore, BJC shows a prolonged effect by remaining in the plasma bound to prothrombin for at least 12 hours.

name: Snaclec bothrojaracin subunit beta
description: This potent antithrombotic agent acts in a calcium-independent manner. Exerts its anticoagulant effect by two distinct mechanisms. It binds to activated thrombin through exosite 1, blocking fibrinogen clotting, platelet activation, factor V activation and other effects, and it interacts with prothrombin (F2), decreasing its proteolytic activation -especially in the presence of factor Va. In vivo, intravenous injection before thrombosis induction causes a significant decrease in thrombus weight. Furthermore, BJC shows a prolonged effect by remaining in the plasma bound to prothrombin for at least 12 hours.

name: Osmin
description: Synthetic peptide exhibits hemolytic activities (less than melittin) and inhibits bacterial (M.luteus and E.coli) and fungal (F.oxysporum) growth at micromolar concentrations. A synthetic peptide with a free C-terminus shows weaker hemolytic, antibacterial and antifungal activities.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme jerdonobin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that has fibrinogen-clotting activity (217 NIH units/mg). It releases fibrinopeptide A and a small amount of fibrinopeptide B from fibrinogen alpha (FGA) and beta (FGB).

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 2.7
description: Weakly inhibits the Kv7.1/KCNQ1 channel (10 uM of the toxin inhibits currents by 17.8%).

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 3.2
description: Potassium channel inhibitor (Kv).

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 3.1
description: Potassium channel inhibitor (Kv).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 23.1
description: Selectively and irreversibly binds (K(d)=2.9 pM) and blocks hKv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channels of human T-lymphocytes. Weakly blocks hKCa3.1/KCNN4, mKv1.1/KCNA1, and hKv1.2/KCNA2 channels. In vivo, high doses (200 ug) produce no symptoms of intoxication when injected into mice.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Conotoxin as25a
description: Upon intracranial injection in mice, this toxin provokes paralysis of the hind limbs and death with a dose of 240 pmol.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 23.2
description: Selectively and irreversibly binds (K(d)=2.9 pM) and blocks Kv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channels of human T-lymphocytes. Weakly blocks Kv1.2/KCNA2 (9%).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin BlatH1
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease-disintegrin that hydrolyzes azocasein, gelatin and fibrinogen (Aalpha and Bbeta chains and partially gamma-chain), and exerts a potent local and systemic hemorrhagic activity in mice. It inhibits ADP- and collagen-induced human platelet aggregation (IC(50) = 0.3 uM and 0.7 uM for ADP and collagen, respectively). This inhibition is dependent of protease activity, and probably occurs through the degradation of an unknown platelet receptor.

name: Phospholipase A2 neuwieditoxin-1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows presynaptic neurotoxicity. 10 ug/ml of this protein produce complete neuromuscular blockade up to 80 minutes, without inhibiting the responses to acetylcholine (ACh) and potassium chloride (KCl). In addition, it produces a calcium-dependent blockade of acetylcholine release and causes appearance of giant miniature end-plate potentials. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 3.4
description: Potassium channel inhibitor (Kv).

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 3.3
description: Potassium channel inhibitor (Kv).

name: Porflan
description: Inflammatory peptide. Induces leukocyte recruitment and adherence to the vascular endothelium when applied to mouse cremaster muscle.

name: Tryptophan-containing weak neurotoxin
description: Modulates both nicotinic and muscarinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR and mAChR/CHRM). On nAChR, acts as an competitive antagonist (muscle-type and alpha-7). On mAChR, in presence of ACh, it partially inhibits the effect of ACh (allosteric antagonist), whereas in the absence of ACh, it activates the receptor (allosteric agonist). In vivo, it exerts a myorelaxant effect, induces a dose-dependent decrease in blood pressure and an increase in heart rate in mice and rats.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Gr2c
description: Inhibits sodium channels Nav1.1/SCN1A, Nav1.2/SCN2A, Nav1.4/SCN4A, Nav1.6/SCN8A, Nav1.7/SCN9A, potassium channels Kv11.1/KCNH2, as well as high-voltage-gated calcium channels Cav1.2/CACNA1C. Also blocks mechanosensitive ion channels (also named stretch-activated channels or SACs) and the hypotonic cell swelling induced calcium increase associated with the activation of such channels. It can thus be useful in treating cardiac ventricular disturbances. Also induces analgesia in mammals. This analgesia is probably mediated by a non-opioid receptor related mechanism.

name: Beta-theraphotoxin-Gr1b
description: Inhibits the sodium channels Nav1.1/SCN1A, Nav1.2/SCN2A, Nav1.3/SCN3A, Nav1.4/SCN4A, Nav1.6/SCN8A, Nav1.7/SCN9A and potassium channels Kv11.1/KCNH2. Induces analgesia in mammals. This analgesia is mediated by a non-opioid receptor related mechanism. Does not show cross tolerance with morphine.

name: Potassium channel toxin-like Tx677
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx Tx308
description: May block potassium channels.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 9.9
description: Potassium channel inhibitor.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 2
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.
