description: Binding of echicetin to glycoprotein Ibalpha (GP1BA) receptor on platelets alone results in inhibition of platelet aggregation, while binding to both GPIba receptor and IgMk promotes platelet aggregation and signal transduction.

name: Cysteine-rich secretory protein
description: Weakly blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: C-type lectin mannose-binding isoform
description: Mannose-binding lectin that binds to and agglutinates rabbit (but not human) erythrocytes in a calcium-dependent manner.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 2.8
description: Voltage-gated potassium channel inhibitor (Kv) that acts on Kv1.3/KCNA3 and Kv7.1/KCNQ1. 1 uM of the toxin inhibits Kv1.3/KCNA3 currents by 35.1%, whereas 10 uM of the toxin inhibits Kv7.1/KCNQ1 currents by 44.9%.

name: Protease inhibitor
description: Snake venom serine protease inhibitor.

name: Defensin-BvL
description: Has antimicrobial activity.

name: Potassium channel toxin kappa-KTx 1.4
description: Potassium channel inhibitor (Kv).

name: Ornithorhynchus venom defensin-like peptide A
description: Does not show antimicrobial, myotoxic, hemolytic and cell-promoting activities.

name: L-amino acid oxidase Lm29
description: Catalyzes an oxidative deamination of predominantly hydrophobic and aromatic L-amino acids (L-Met=L-Leu>>L-Phe>L-Trp>L-Tyr>L-Ile>L-His>L-Arg> L-Val>L-Gln,), thus producing hydrogen peroxide that may contribute to the diverse toxic effects of this enzyme. Exhibits a low myotoxicity (a mild myonecrosis is observed after injection in mice quadriceps muscle). In vitro, is cytotoxic to a lot of human cell lines, including AGS (IC(50)=22.7 ug/ml), MCF-7 (IC(50)=1.4 ug/ml), HL-60, HeLa and Jurkat cells, as well as to the parasite Leishmania brasiliensis (IC(50)=2.22 ug/ml). This cytotoxicity is dependent on the production of hydrogen peroxyde, since it is inhibited by catalase, a hydrogen peroxyde scavenger.

name: Bibrotoxin
description: Vasoconstrictor activity. These toxins cause cardiac arrest probably as a result of coronary vasospasm. May act by displaying agonistic activities towards endothelin-1 and -2 receptors (EDNRA and EDNRB).

name: Conantokin-P
description: Conantokins inhibit N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors. This toxin has the highest potency for the NR2B/GRIN2B subunit, followed by NR2A/GRIN2A, NR2C/GRIN2C, and NR2D/GRIN2D subunits.

name: Neurotoxin alpha-KTx 28.1
description: Selectively inhibits Kv7.1/KCNQ1 channel (K(d) is 11.69 uM) and inhibits Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, Kv1.3/KCNA3 with a very low potency.

name: Neurotoxin alpha-KTx 29.2
description: Weakly inhibits the Kv1.3/KCNA3 channel (1 uM of thetoxin inhibits currents by 13.2%) and Kv7.1/KCNQ1 channel (10 uM of the toxin inhibits currents by 27.7%).

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-LOXN6
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-beta-LOXN8
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LbSicTox-alphaIB1b
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin (9.5 U/mg). May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, and dermonecrosis. May induce blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation.

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alpha-1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis and dermonecrosis.

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-alphaI-1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-beta-LOXN1/LOXN7
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-beta-LOXN2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-beta-LOXN3
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-beta-LOXN4
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LgSicTox-LOXN5
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme elegaxobin-2
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that clots rabbit fibrinogen. Only the beta chain of fibrinogen (FGB) is cleaved, releasing fibrinopeptide B. Human and bovine fibrinogen are unaffected. Also cleaves Met-Lys and Arg-Ser bonds in heat-denatured bovine plasma kininogen to release Lys-bradykinin.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme elegaxobin-1
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that clots rabbit fibrinogen. Only the beta chain of fibrinogen (FGB) is cleaved, releasing fibrinopeptide B. Incubation with human fibrinogen alpha and beta resulted in cleavage of both fibrinogen chains but generated neither fibrinopeptide A nor fibrinopeptide B. Promotes clotting of rabbit fibrinogen, but not bovine or human fibrinogen.

name: Neurotoxin BmK 18(2)
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin NCA-04
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin OKI-Ed
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Toxin TbTx5
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Omega-theraphotoxin-Gr1a
description: Inhibits P/Q- (Cav2.1/CACNA1A) and N-type (Cav2.2/CACNA1B) voltage-gated calcium channel by modifying voltage-dependent gating. It selectively and reversibly blocks the calcium channels coupled to glutamate release. Also inhibits potassium channels (Kv2.1/KCNB1) with lower affinity.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 intermexin
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that shows presynaptic neurotoxicity and low myotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Factor V activator RVV-V alpha
description: Venom serine protease that activates factor V (F5) in a calcium-independent manner. It cleaves the Arg(1545)-Ser(1546) linkage in the human factor V molecule. Induces the coagulation of mammalian plasma.

name: Factor V activator RVV-V gamma
description: Venom serine protease that selectively activates factor V (F5) in a calcium-independent manner. It cleaves the Arg(1545)-Ser(1546) linkage in the human factor V molecule. Induces the coagulation of mammalian plasma.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 homolog
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) homolog that lacks both catalytic and neurotoxicity activities.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 3
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Short neurotoxin 2
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 pgPLA 1b/pgPLA 2b
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Toxin BmKaTx10
description: Binds to sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Venom peptide BmKAPI
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Waprin-Rha1
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Dinoponeratoxin Da-2501
description: Dinoponeratoxin Da-2501 may have antibacterial activity.

name: Short neurotoxin 1
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Dinoponeratoxin Da-1837
description: May have antibacterial activity.

name: Dinoponeratoxin Da-3105
description: May have antibacterial activity, since it is predicted to form an amphipathic alpha helix.

name: Dinoponeratoxin Da-3177
description: The synthetic peptide has antimicrobial activity against the Gram-positive bacteria B.amyloliquefacies S499 (MIC=0.05 mM), L.monocytogenes 2231 and S.aureus ATCC 29213, against the yGram-negative bacteria P.putida BTP1, P.aeruginosa PaO1 and E.coli ATCC 10536, and against the fungi S.cerevisiae, R.mucilaginosa and C.cucumerinum. Not active against the fungi F.oxysporum and B.cinerea.

name: Dinoponeratoxin Da-1039
description: May have antibacterial activity.

name: Long neurotoxin 1
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Delta-conotoxin TxVIB
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process. Induces membrane depolarization and spontaneous repetitive firing of neurons.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog bothropstoxin-1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 homolog that lacks enzymatic activity. In vivo, induces muscle necrosis, accompanied by polymorphonuclear cell infiltration, and edema in the mouse paw. Damages artificial and myoblast membranes by a calcium-independent mechanism. Has bactericidal activity.

name: Basic phospholipase A2
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Toxin BmKa3
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-13
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PA-11
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 6
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Disintegrin rubistatin
description: Recombinant disintegrin rubistatin inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation. In addition, it strongly induces apoptosis, and inhibits cell migration and proliferation of the human cancer cell line SK-Mel-28.

name: Alpha-neurotoxin homolog 8
description: Binds and inhibits muscular and neuronal nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR).

name: Alpha-neurotoxin NTX-3
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Alpha-neurotoxin NTX-4
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: U14-theraphotoxin-Cg1c
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U14-theraphotoxin-Cg1b
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 5
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv2.1/KCNB1 > Kv4.2/KCND2 > Kv4.1/KCND1). Also inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels of subtype Nav1.5/SCN5A (in cardiac myocytes). The toxin shifts activation towards more depolarized potentials and is suggested to bind to the extracellular S3-S4 loop of the channel.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 2
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv2.1/KCNB1 > Kv4.2/KCND2 > Kv4.1/KCND1). Also inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels of subtype Nav1.5/SCN5A (in cardiac myocytes). The toxin shifts activation towards more depolarized potentials and is suggested to bind to the extracellular S3-S4 loop of the channel.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 3
description: Inhibits voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv2.1/KCNB1 > Kv4.2/KCND2 > Kv4.1/KCND1). Also inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels of subtype Nav1.5/SCN5A (in cardiac myocytes). The toxin shifts activation towards more depolarized potentials and is suggested to bind to the extracellular S3-S4 loop of the channel.

name: U14-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 2
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U14-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 1
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U14-theraphotoxin-Cg1a 3
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Cg1c
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: Antimicrobial peptide HsAp2
description: Possesses antimicrobial activity against both Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria, as well as against the fungus C.tropicalis. Also possesses a relatively high hemolytic activity.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like
description: This protein is a zinc metalloprotease from snake venom that possesses hemorrhagic activity.

name: Snake venom serine protease
description: Snake venom serine protease that may act in the hemostasis system of the prey.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like VMP-III
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase that impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin VMP-II
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin VMP-II
description: Snake venom zinc metalloproteinase that inhibits ADP-induced platelet aggregation (probably by binding integrin alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3)) and degrades fibrinogen.

name: Toxin Boma6d
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: U13-ctenitoxin-Pn1b
description: Acts as a neurotoxin.

name: Crotamine Ile-19
description: Cationic peptide that possesses multiple functions. It acts as a cell-penetrating peptide (CPP), and as a potent voltage-gated potassium channel (Kv) inhibitor and exhibits antimicrobial activities (By similarity). It also elicts a short-lasting hyperextension of the hind limb. It does not cause observable tissue damage (whereas the whole venom causes severe myonecrosis accompanied by edema and hemorrhage).

name: Toxin Boma6c
description: Binds voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor scutellin-3
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Phospholipase A2 heteromtoxin
description: Phosholipase toxin, which catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides. Inhibits both skeletal (RYR1) and cardiac (RYR2) ryanodine receptors (calcium release channels). Probably blocks ryanodine receptors by generating a lipid product (By similarity).

name: Opicalcin-1
description: Potently and reversibly modifies channel gating behavior of the type 1 ryanodine receptor (RYR1) by inducing prominent subconductance behavior. Binds a different site as ryanodine (By similarity).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 BFPA
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits blood coagulation and shows bactericidal activities against both Gram-negative and -positive bacteria (E.coli, MIC=0.4 uM and S.aureus, MIC=0.1 uM). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 16.3
description: Blocks calcium-activated potassium channels.

name: Phospholipase D StSicTox-betaIF1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SdSicTox-betaIF1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like alternagin
description: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like alternagin: hemorrhagic protease that acts as a potent inhibitor of collagen-induced adhesion by blockage of alpha-2/beta-1 (ITGA2/ITGB1) integrin. Cleaves at Leu-|-Met bonds (PubMed:11368322).

name: Kunitz-type U1-aranetoxin-Av1a
description: Putative insecticidal toxin that may inhibit trypsin.

name: Phospholipase D LafSicTox-betaIE1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpaSicTox-betaIF1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIF1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Venom metalloproteinase antarease-like TpachMP_B
description: Acts as a metalloprotease. Penetrates intact tissue and specifically cleaves the vesicle-associated membrane protein 2 (VAMP2) (part of the SNARE complex) involved in pancreatic secretion, thus disrupting the normal vesicular traffic (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D SpeSicTox-betaIIA2ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin ocellatin
description: Inhibits ADP-induced human platelet aggregation.

name: Disintegrin multisquamatin
description: Inhibits ADP-induced human, canine and rabbit platelet aggregation by binding with high affinity to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3).

name: Conotoxin sr5a
description: When injected intracranially into 9-day-old mice, causes transient symptoms, including extension of the body and clockwise and counter-clockwise turns, that last 3 to 4 minutes. When injected intracranially into 16-day-old mice, causes transient symptoms, including agitated breathing and occasional turning followed by scratching and grooming behavior, that last for 15-19 minutes.

name: Opistoporin-1
description: At high concentrations, acts as pore former in cellular membranes and causes the leakage of the cells. At submicromolar concentrations, degranulates granulocytes and has a weak hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. Also strongly inhibits the production of superoxide anions. Has a strong antibacterial activity against Gram-negative bacteria but is less active against Gram-positive bacteria. Also has antifungal activity.

name: Parabutoporin
description: At high concentrations, acts as pore former in cellular membranes and causes the leakage of the cells. At submicromolar concentrations, degranulates granulocytes and has a weak hemolytic activity against human red blood cells. Also strongly inhibits the production of superoxide anions. Has a strong antibacterial activity against Gram-negative bacteria but is less active against Gram-positive bacteria. Also has antifungal activity. Induces reversible G-protein dependent Ca(2+) release from intracellular stores and increase Ca(2+) influx in HL-60 cells. Induces the activation of the Rac pathway in granulocytes. Synergistically enhances the excitatory effects of short and long chain ion-channel-specific neurotoxins by interaction with the neuronal membranes.

name: Opistoporin-2
description: At high concentrations, acts as pore former in cellular membranes and causes the leakage of the cells. At submicromolar concentrations, degranulates granulocytes and has a weak hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. Also strongly inhibits the production of superoxide anions. Has a strong antibacterial activity against Gram-negative bacteria but is less active against Gram-positive bacteria. Also has antifungal activity.

name: Mastoparan-3
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins (Gi component), which in turn activates the cascade of molecular events cAMP-regulated, resulting in mast cell degranulation.

name: Mastoparan-1
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Has hemolytic activity. Its both activities may be due to pore formation.

name: Mastoparan-2
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins (Gi component), which in turn activates the cascade of molecular events cAMP-regulated, resulting in mast cell degranulation.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 KBf-VA
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 Vb-2
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has only a weak enzymatic activity. Inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Delta-latroinsectotoxin-Lt1a
description: Insecticidal toxin that induces massive neurotransmitter release at insect but not vertebrate neuromuscular junctions. Forms cation-permeable pores (with high permeability to calcium) in lipid membranes locust muscle membrane and artificial lipid bilayers. Binds to neurexin-1-alpha (NRXN1), adhesion G protein-coupled receptor L1 (ADGRL1, also known as latrophilin-1), and receptor-type tyrosine-protein phosphatase S (PTPRS), and induces neurotransmitter exocytosis through two calcium-dependent mechanisms (membrane pore formation and signaling via latrophilin) and a yet to be defined calcium-independent mechanism (By similarity).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme gyroxin B2.1
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Displays a specificity similar to trypsin. Releases only fibrinopeptide A in the conversion of fibrinogen (FGA) to fibrin (By similarity). Shows coagulant, esterase and amidase activities. Reversibly increases the permeability of the blood brain barrier (BBB) in mice. Induces the barrel rotation syndrome in mice, which is manifested by gyroxin-like, rapid rolling motions. This syndrome may be due to its effect on BBB permeability, and certainly also to other actions affecting endogenous substrates present in the endothelium, nervous tissues or blood.

name: Toxin Aah6
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects (By similarity). This toxin has very low anti-insect activity.

name: Exendin-1
description: O-linked and free exendin-1 and exendin-1b have vasoactive intestinal peptide(VIP)/secretin-like biological activities. They interact with rat and human VIP receptors 1 (VIPR1) and 2 (VIPR2), with the highest affinity for the human VIPR2. They induce hypotension that is mediated by relaxation of cardiac smooth muscle.

name: Mastoparan-M
description: Mast cell degranulating peptide. Activates G proteins that couple to phospholipase C.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 12.3
description: Inhibits high conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCNMA) (By similarity). Inhibits Shaker B potassium channels.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 LmTX-I
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that displays neurotoxic and myotoxic activities. Induces inflammatory edema by mechanisms involving mast cell activation and arachidonic acid metabolites. Increases plasma creatine kinase activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 LmTX-II
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that may display neurotoxic and myotoxic activities. May induce inflammatory edema by mechanisms involving mast cell activation and arachidonic acid metabolites. May increase plasma creatine kinase activity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Cytotoxin najalgesin
description: Analgesic toxin that is blocked by atropine and naloxone, suggesting the involvement of cholinergic and opiodergic mechanisms in its antinociceptive effect (PubMed:18765245). Shows cytolytic activity by forming pore in lipid membranes (By similarity).

name: M-theraphotoxin-Gr1a
description: This cationic hydrophobic peptide inhibits a lot of different channels and has an antimicrobial activity. It blocks mechanosensitive ion channels (also named stretch-activated channels or SACs), without having effect on whole-cell voltage-sensitive currents. Acts by partitioning into the membrane and perturbing the interface between the channel and the lipid bilayer without necessarily being in physical contact with the channel. Inhibits atrial fibrillation as well as the membrane motor of outer hair cells at low doses. It also binds to the voltage sensor of voltage-gated potassium channels from the archaebacterium Aeropyrum pernix (KvAP) without affecting channel gating. It has also a medium toxicity on a large spectra of sodium channels (Nav1.1/SCN1A, Nav1.2/SCN2A, Nav1.3/SCN3A, Nav1.4/SCN4A, Nav1.5/SCN5A, Nav1.6/SCN8A, Nav1.7/SCN9A), and also inhibits potassium channels Kv11.1/KCNH2 and Kv11.2/KCNH6. It also exhibits antimicrobial activities against the Gram-positive bacteria B.subtilis (MIC=0.5 uM), S.aureus (MIC=2-4 uM), and S.epidermidis (MIC=4-8 uM), and Gram-negative bacteria S.typhimurium (MIC=32.64 uM), P.aeruginosa (MIC=8-16 uM), and E.coli (MIC=8-16 uM).

name: Conotoxin r11e
description: Causes hyperactivity, circular motion, convulsion, urination and death, when injected into 13- to 15-day-old mice. Causes gasping, backward swimming or swimming in a vertical direction and death, when intraperitoneally injected into goldfish.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor BmKTT-2
description: Dual-function toxin that completely inhibits trypsin activity at a molar ratio of 1:1 (dissociation constant of 420 nM) and that inhibits mKv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channel currents with an IC(50) of 371.3 nM.

name: Phospholipase A2 pseudexin C chain
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: C-type lectin galactose-binding isoform
description: Galactose-binding lectin that binds to and agglutinates erythrocytes in a calcium-dependent manner.

name: C-type lectin mannose-binding isoform
description: Mannose-binding lectin that binds to and agglutinates erythrocytes in a calcium-dependent manner.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 daboxin P
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that exhibits anticoagulant activity, probably by binding to factor X and its activated form factor Xa (F10). Shows no cytotoxicity. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Disintegrin jerdostatin
description: Recombinant protein inhibits the adhesion of alpha-1/beta-1-K562 (ITGA1/ITGB1) cells to collagen IV with an IC(50) of 80 nM.

name: Cytotoxin homolog Clbp-3
description: Has low cytotoxic activity.

name: Amphipathic peptide Tx348
description: Amphipathic peptide that has antibacterial activities.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin-like crotastatin
description: Snake venom zinc metalloprotease that induces apoptosis in vascular endothelial cells (VEC), without degrading the extracellular matrix (it cannot cleave collagen) or inhibiting adhesion of VEC. Has also fibrinogenolytic and hemorrhagic activities (By similarity).

name: Cytotoxin I-like P-15
description: Shows cytolytic activity on many different cells by forming pore in lipid membranes. In vivo, increases heart rate or kills the animal by cardiac arrest. In addition, it binds to heparin with high affinity, interacts with Kv channel-interacting protein 1 (KCNIP1) in a calcium-independent manner, and binds to integrin alpha-V/beta-3 (ITGAV/ITGB3) with moderate affinity.

name: Kappa-hexatoxin-Hv1b
description: This excitatory toxin inhibits insect calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channels (Slo-type).

name: Conotoxin pc16a
description: Potential neurotoxin. No target has been identified for this peptide.

name: Kappa-hexatoxin-Hv1c
description: This excitatory toxin inhibits insect calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channels (Slo-type). Pan-neuronal expression in Drosophila is lethal but flies engineered to express the toxin only in clock neurons have defects in circadian rhythm but a normal lifespan.

name: Epsilon-conotoxin TxVA
description: Epsilon-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, blocking the calcium channels or G protein-coupled receptors. Causes hyperactivity upon intracranial injection into mice. Causes dorsal fins drooping in fish.

name: Conotoxin Fi3c
description: May act as a neurotoxin.

name: Conotoxin Fi3a
description: May act as a neurotoxin.

name: Contryphan Fib
description: Inhibits high voltage-activated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Conotoxin Fi5a
description: May act as a neurotoxin.

name: Contryphan-Le
description: Inhibits high voltage-activated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Basic phospholipase A2 homolog
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has almost no phospholipase A2 activity. Displays edema-inducing activities.

name: Disintegrin isoform D-2
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to the alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin isoform D-3
description: Inhibits fibrinogen interaction with platelets. Acts by binding to alpha-IIb/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) on the platelet surface and inhibits aggregation induced by ADP, thrombin, platelet-activating factor and collagen (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A2 OS1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has a low specific activity on phospholipid substrates, and is neither neurotoxic, nor myotoxic. Triggers cell migration (PubMed:11090064), has antimalarial activity (PubMed:16669624), but is not able to potently inhibit HIV-1 replication (PubMed:16669624). Binds in a calcium-independent fashion with very high affinity to a muscle-type (M-type) PLA2 receptor, but is a very poor ligand for neuronal-type (N-type) receptors. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase-disintegrin agkistin
description: Inhibits ADP-induced human platelet aggregation, inhibits bovine aortic endothelial cells (BAEC) migration, has anti-angiogenic activity and induces BAEC and human micro-vascular endothelial cell (HMEC) apoptosis. The metalloproteinase domain may act in hemorrhage.

name: Cathelicidin-related peptide Na_CRAMP
description: Potent antimicrobial peptide against most of Gram-negative bacteria, some Gram-positive bacteria (Bacillus) and some fungi. Adopts an amphipathic alpha helical conformation, that may allow to partition into the target membrane. No hemolytic and cytotoxic activities have been observed on mammalian cells.

name: Cathelicidin-related peptide Oh-Cath
description: Potent antimicrobial peptide against Gram-negative (MIC=0.25 ug/mL against E.coli ATCC 25922, MIC=0.5 ug/mL against P.aeruginosa) and Gram-positive bacteria (MIC=64 ug/mL against E.faecalis, MIC=64 ug/mL against S.aureus) (PubMed:25100358). Adopts an amphipathic alpha helical conformation, that may allow to partition into the target membrane (By similarity). Low hemolytic activities have been observed on mammalian cells (PubMed:25100358).

name: Poneratoxin
description: Blocks nicotinic synaptic transmission in insect CNS and affects voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). It is a strong, but very slowly acting agonist for smooth muscles and its blocks synaptic transmission in the insect CNS in a concentration-dependent manner and depolarizes giant interneurons. Also affects neuromuscular transmission in rat tissue.

name: Hainantoxin-XV-3
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: Hainantoxin-XV.2
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Hainantoxin-XV
description: Putative ion channel inhibitor.

name: Techylectin-like protein
description: Lectin involved in innate immunity.

name: Beta-toxin Tz1
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. Strongly affects skeletal muscle channels Nav1.4/SCN4A, poorly affects the neuronal channels Nav1.6/SCN8A and Nav1.2/SCN2A. Induces spastic paralysis of rear limbs, increased salivation, apnea, tachycardia and increased perspiration.

name: Beta-fibrinogenase mucrofibrase-2
description: Snake venom serine protease with fibrinogenolytic activities. Cleaves beta-chain of fibrinogen (FGB) efficiently and shows relatively lower activity on alpha-chain.

name: U4-ctenitoxin-Co1a
description: Omega-agatoxins are antagonists of voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav) (By similarity). Toxic to mice by intracerebroventricular injection.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin-like HR1a
description: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin-like HR1a: zinc protease that induces hemorrhage and has proteolytic activity.

name: Weak neurotoxin OH-72
description: Binds with low affinity to muscular (alpha-1-beta-1-epsilon-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNE-CHRND) and very low affinity to neuronal (alpha7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR).

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Qc1.4b
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Qc1.4a
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like Ac1.1b
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Peptide Ctri9293
description: Antimicrobial peptide.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like lp1.6b
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Alpha-conotoxin-like lp1.6a
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like Ac4.3b
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Kappa-conotoxin-like Ac4.3a
description: Kappa-conotoxins bind and inhibit voltage-gated potassium channels.

name: Neurotoxin 3FTx-RI
description: Binds to muscle nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibit acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular transmission.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 KBf-grIB
description: PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Neurotoxin 3FTx-LI
description: Blocks both the muscle-twitch response to nerve stimulation and the response to exogenous acetylcholine.

name: Neurotoxin 3FTx-LK
description: Blocks both the muscle-twitch response to nerve stimulation and the response to exogenous acetylcholine.

name: U1-sicaritoxin-Li1c
description: Toxin active against insects (S.frugiperda larvae). May act on sodium (Nav) or calcium (Cav) channels.

name: Phospholipase D LiSicTox-betaIA1ii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin with a low activity. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Does not cause hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like PuIIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like PuIA
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Phospholipase D isoform 2
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Shows complement-dependent hemolysis. May also induce dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability, and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D isoform 1
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Shows complement-dependent hemolysis. May also induce dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability, and platelet aggregation.

name: Waprin-Lio1
description: Damages membranes of susceptible bacteria. Has no hemolytic activity. Not toxic to mice. Does not inhibit the proteinases elastase and cathepsin G.

name: Muscarinic toxin 2
description: Binds irreversibly to M1 (CHRM1) muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, and reveals a slightly weaker effect on M3 (CHRM3) receptors. The mechanism of toxin-receptor interaction comprises at least two steps. The first step is fast with no competition between the toxin and the antagonist. The second step is slow with formation of a more stable toxin-receptor complex and inhibition of the antagonist binding.

name: Toxin C13S1C1
description: Is cytotoxic against human non-small cell lung adenocarcinoma A-549 cells (LC(50)=56 ug/ml), breast adenocarcinoma MDA-MBsy-231 cells (LC(50)=62 ug/ml) and colorectal adenocarcinoma HT-29 cells (LC(50)=110 ug/ml). Shows low hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes (LC(50)>600 ug/ml). Is also cytotoxic against human umbilical vein endothelial HUVEC cells (57 ug/ml) indicating no differential activity against cell lines derived from neoplastic tissues.

name: C-type lectin 2
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor bitisilin-2
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Mu-conotoxin-like CalTx 12.2.1E
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels. This toxin reversibly blocks voltage-gated sodium channel in cephalopods, with no alteration in the voltage dependence of sodium conductance or on the kinetics of inactivation (By similarity).

name: Disintegrin EC3B
description: Inhibits adhesion of cells expressing alpha-4/beta-1 (ITGA4/ITGB1) and alpha-4/beta-7 (ITGA4/ITGB7) integrins to the natural ligands vascular cell adhesion molecule 1 (VCAM-1) and mucosal addressin cell adhesion molecule 1 (MADCAM-1). It is also a weaker inhibitor of alpha-5/beta-1 (ITGA5/ITGB1) and alpha-2b/beta-3 (ITGA2B/ITGB3) integrins. The inhibitory activity of EC3 towards alpha-4 integrins is associated with the MLD sequence of EC3B subunit. The ability of EC3 to inhibit ITGA5/ITGB1 resides in both subunits A and B.

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 2
description: Snake venom phospholipase that inhibits ADP- and collagen-induced human platelet aggregation. This inhibition is completely inhibited by abolition of catalytic activity in case of collagen as inducer and partially inhibited in case of ADP as inducer. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Toxin Td2
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Td9
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Td3
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Td10
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Toxin Td11
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Toxin Td12
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Fasciculin-1
description: Interferes with neuromuscular transmission by inhibiting the enzyme acetylcholinesterase (AChE) present at the neuromuscular junction. It selectively binds and inhibits with a 1:1 stoichiometry the mammalian and electric fish AChE at picomolar concentrations. It is highly specific for the peripheral site of AChE and blocks the entry of acetylcholine into the active site of the enzyme, thereby preventing its breakdown. It has been called fasciculin since after injection into mice it causes severe, generalized and long-lasting (5-7 hours) fasciculations.

name: Natterin-3
description: Shows nociceptive, edema-inducing and kininogenase activity with release of kallidin from low molecular weight kininogen. The cleavage occurs at Met-Lys bonds (By similarity).

name: Natterin-4
description: Shows nociceptive, edema-inducing and kininogenase activity with release of kallidin from low molecular weight kininogen. The cleavage occurs at Met-Lys bonds (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1av
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1aiv
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Cytotoxin 1
description: Produces complete blockade of auricular contraction, which is irreversible at high concentrations. Induces apoptosis in leukemic cells. Possess anti-arthritic and anti-inflammatory potential.

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1bii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1bi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1ai
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase D LdSicTox-alphaIB3avi
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: Hyaluronidase
description: Hydrolyzes high molecular weight hyaluronic acid to produce small oligosaccharides.

name: Phospholipase D LsaSicTox-alphaIB1aii
description: Catalyzes the hydrolysis of sphingomyelin. May also act on other phosphatidyl esters. Induces complement-dependent hemolysis, dermonecrosis, blood vessel permeability and platelet aggregation (By similarity).

name: C-type lectin lectoxin-Enh6
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: C-type lectin lectoxin-Enh7
description: Mannose-binding lectin which recognizes specific carbohydrate structures and agglutinates a variety of animal cells by binding to cell-surface glycoproteins and glycolipids. May be a calcium-dependent lectin (By similarity).

name: Alpha-mammal toxin BeM9
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission. Has paralytic activity in mice.

name: Toxin BeM14
description: Alpha toxins bind voltage-independently at site-3 of sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation of the activated channels, thereby blocking neuronal transmission (By similarity). Has paralytic activity in mice.

name: Venom nerve growth factor
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity). It promotes neurite outgrowth in rat PC12 pheochromocytoma cells.

name: Putative beta-neurotoxin RjAa14F
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing.

name: Snaclec CHH-B subunit alpha
description: Binds to the subunit GPIbalpha (GP1BA) of the platelet GPIb/V/IX receptor system. It inhibits ristocetin- and vWF-induced platelet aggregation in platelet-rich plasma by inhibiting the binding of vWF to GPIbalpha.

name: Snaclec CHH-B subunit beta
description: Binds to the subunit GPIbalpha (GP1BA) of the platelet GPIb/V/IX receptor system. It inhibits ristocetin- and vWF-induced platelet aggregation in platelet-rich plasma by inhibiting the binding of vWF to GPIbalpha.

name: Kunitz-type kappaPI-theraphotoxin-Hs1e
description: Dual-function toxin that inhibits both serine proteases (trypsin) and voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv).

name: Insect toxin AaHIT5
description: Excitatory insect toxins induce a spastic paralysis. They bind voltage-independently to sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). This toxin elicits excitatory activity with no flaccid paralysis despite its high degree of sequence similarity with other depressant insect toxins. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Alpha-conotoxin SrIA/SrIB
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. Has weak blocking effects on muscle nAChR composed of alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta subunits and the central nervous system nAChR composed of alpha-4/beta-2 subunits. Does not detectably affect the peripheral nervous system nAChR composed of alpha-3/beta-4 subunits. Low toxin concentrations potentiate currents in muscle nAChR composed of alpha-1/beta-1/gamma/delta subunits and central nervous system nAChR composed of alpha-4/beta-2 subunits, but not the peripheral nervous system nAChR composed of alpha-3/beta-4 subunits.

name: Toxin BmTxKS4
description: Reversibly inhibits potassium channels.

name: Mu-agatoxin-Aa1f
description: Insecticidal neurotoxin that induces an irreversible spastic paralysis when injected into insects. Modifies presynaptic voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav), causing them to open at the normal resting potential of the nerve. This leads to spontaneous release of neurotransmitter and repetitive action potentials in motor neurons.

name: Insect toxin OsI1
description: Depressant insect beta-toxins cause a transient contraction paralysis followed by a slow flaccid paralysis. They bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing. This toxin is active only on insects.

name: Pilosulin-5
description: Causes a significant and dose-dependent histamine release, probably by influencing the signal transduction of mast cells through a non-IgE-mediated pathway. This peptide does not have cytotoxic activities.

name: Venom serine protease Bi-VSP
description: Multifunctional venom serine protease. In insects, it acts as an arthropod prophenoloxidase-activating factor, thereby triggering the phenoloxidase cascade. When injected into larvae, it induces a lethal melanization response in target insects by modulating the innate immune response. In mammals, it converts fibrinogen into fibrin, activates prothrombin, and also degrades fibrin. In mammal, it may act in a cooperative manner with the serine protease inhibitor Bi-KTI (AC G3LH89) to promote the spread of bee venom under anti-bleeding conditions.

name: Insect-toxin Cn10
description: Beta toxins bind voltage-independently at site-4 of sodium channels (Nav) and shift the voltage of activation toward more negative potentials thereby affecting sodium channel activation and promoting spontaneous and repetitive firing (By similarity). Is toxic on insects and crustaceans, but not on mammals.

name: Venom nerve growth factor 1
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Omega-conotoxin MVIIC
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin preferentially blocks P/Q-type calcium channels (Cav2.1/CACNA1A).

name: Venom nerve growth factor 3
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Venom nerve growth factor 2
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Venom nerve growth factor 5
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Venom nerve growth factor 4
description: Nerve growth factor is important for the development and maintenance of the sympathetic and sensory nervous systems. It stimulates division and differentiation of sympathetic and embryonic sensory neurons as well as basal forebrain cholinergic neurons in the brain. Its relevance in the snake venom is not clear. However, it has been shown to inhibit metalloproteinase-dependent proteolysis of platelet glycoprotein Ib alpha, suggesting a metalloproteinase inhibition to prevent metalloprotease autodigestion and/or protection against prey proteases (By similarity).

name: Beta/omega-theraphotoxin-Tp1a
description: Inhibits voltage-gated calcium channels Cav3.1/CACNA1G, voltage-gated potassium channels Kv2.1/KCNB1 and all sodium channels tested (Nav1.2/SCN2A, Nav1.5/SCN5A, Nav1.7/SCN9A, and Nav1.8/SCN10A). Shifts the voltage-dependence of channel activation to more positive potentials. Most potent against Nav1.8/SCN10A.

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 9.1
description: Blocks small conductance calcium-activated potassium channels (KCNN, SK). Weakly inhibits the Kv7.1/KCNQ1 channel (10 uM of the toxin inhibits currents by 23.3%). Low toxicity by intracerebroventricular injection into mice.

name: Alpha-fibrinogenase-like
description: Degrades alpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA), and has strong caseinolytic activity.

name: Protein C activator
description: Snake venom serine protease that selectively cleaves the heavy chain of protein C (PROC). This activation is thrombomodulin-independent.

name: Venom plasminogen activator
description: Snake venom serine protease that activates plasminogen.

name: Beta-fibrinogenase-like
description: Snake venom serine protease that has fibrinogenolytic activities by hydrolyzing the beta chain of fibrinogen (FGB). Typical arginine esterase which hydrolyzes esters and amides of arginine.

name: Cathelicidin-related peptide Bf-CRAMP
description: Potent antimicrobial peptide against most of Gram-negative bacteria, some Gram-positive bacteria (Bacillus) and some fungi (C.albicans, P.pastoris, A.terreus, A.nidulans, and C.globosum). Adopts an amphipathic alpha helical conformation, that may allow to partition into the target membrane. No hemolytic and cytotoxic activities have been observed on mammalian cells.

name: Toxin To7
description: Inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Delta-conotoxin TxVIA
description: Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process. Binding of this toxin is strongly calcium-dependent but not voltage-dependent. The binding site is most likely on the extracellular side of the sodium channel. Binds receptor sites on both mollusk and rat central nervous system, but despite its high affinity binding to rat sodium channel, it has no functional effect in vivo and in vitro on it. Has also no effect on Gambusia fish. Is important in mollusk for the paralysis of the prey. Upon injection of the peptide, a subordinate lobster assumes an exaggerated dominant posture (of a 'King-Kong' lobster!).

name: Cd-146 peptide
description: Inhibits angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) with a Ki of 61.8 uM, and targets B1 bradykinin receptors (BDKRB1). In vivo, induces hyperalgesic effects in living rats after intraplantar injection.

name: Toxin BmKBT
description: This toxin increases the peak sodium current, slows down the inactivation of sodium channels (Nav), and prolongs the action potential of dorsal root ganglion neurons, which indicates that it behaves as a classical alpha-toxin. It binds to mammal brain and insect sodium channels, but with a different manner. This peptide may bind to a distinct receptor site on mammal brain sodium channels, which is unconnected with that for BmKAS (a beta-toxin), BmKIT2 (a beta-toxin) or BmK I (an alpha toxin). In contrast, the receptor site for BmKabT on insect sodium channels might be closely related to that for the beta-insect depressant toxin BmKIT2. Possess potent toxicity in mice but induces only paralysis in cotton bollworm.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Gr4a
description: Binds the voltage-sensor domain of the potassium channel KvAP (from the archaeon Aeropyrum pernix) and affects channel gating.

name: Kappa-theraphotoxin-Gr2b
description: Binds the voltage-sensor domain of the potassium channel KvAP (from the archaeon Aeropyrum pernix) and affects channel gating.

name: Astacin-like metalloprotease toxin 1
description: Zinc metalloprotease. Provoques deadhesion of endothelial cells from cell cultures, and also degradation of fibronectin, fibrinogen and gelatin in vitro. Its role in the venom is not fully understood but it might act as a spreading factor that facilitates diffusion of other venom toxins. Alternatively, it might be involved in the proteolytic processing of other venom toxins or it might play a role in extra-oral digestion of prey.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog dendrotoxin I
description: Serine protease inhibitor homolog that blocks voltage-gated potassium channels (Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, and Kv1.6/KCNA6) (IC(50)=0.13-50 nM).

name: U11-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a
description: Probable ion channel inhibitor.

name: U5-theraphotoxin-Hs1a 1
description: Agglutinates human and mice erythrocytes. This activity can be specifically inhibited by mannosamine. This lectin shows very low toxicity in both mammals and insects.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme BJ-48
description: Thrombin-like serine protease which cleaves specifically the Aalpha chain of human fibrinogen (FGA) to release fibrinopeptide A. Also cleaves rapidly the Bbeta chain of human fibrinogen (FGB).

name: Thrombin-like enzyme BpSP-1
description: Thrombin-like enzyme that has high clotting activity upon bovine and human plasma. Has also fibrinogenoltic activity by rapidly hydrolyzing Aalpha chain of fibrinogen (FGA), and partially consumes Bbeta chain (FGB). Has high catalytic activity upon substrates such as TAME, and specific substrates for thrombin S-2238 and S-2288. Also hydrolyzes specific substrates for kallikrein (S-2266 and S-2302), however, no release of kinin upon plasma has been determined. When administered intraperitoneally in mice, causes defibrinogenation, making the plasma incoagulable.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme chitribrisin
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease that activates fibrinogen by releasing both fibrinopeptides A and B. Has also fibrinogenolytic activity, with a complete digestion of alpha chain (FGA) at 30 min and of beta chain (FGB) at 60 min.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme purpurase
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Releases only fibrinopeptides A after 2 hours incubation. Clots fibrinogen with different clotting time depending on the species: cat > human > dog > goat >> rabbit.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme albolabrase
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease. Releases both fibrinopeptides A and B after 90 min incubation, but only fibrinopeptides A after 10 min incubation. Clots fibrinogen with different clotting time depending on the species: bovine > dog = human > goat. Fails to clot both rabbit and cat fibrinogens.

name: Venom plasminogen activator GPV-PA
description: Snake venom serine protease that activates plasminogen.

name: Zinc metalloproteinase/disintegrin
description: Snake venom metalloproteinase-4: impairs hemostasis in the envenomed animal.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Ls2a
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Al2b
description: Potent long-chain postsynaptic neurotoxin. Pseudo-irreversibly inhibits the nicotinic acetylcholine receptor through competitive antagonism.

name: Alpha-elapitoxin-Al2a
description: Binds with high affinity to muscular (alpha-1/CHRNA1) and neuronal (alpha-7/CHRNA7) nicotinic acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) and inhibits acetylcholine from binding to the receptor, thereby impairing neuromuscular and neuronal transmission.

name: Alpha-conotoxin S2
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. Has no effect on the release of catecholamines evoked by nicotine.

name: Alpha-conotoxin SIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them. This toxin blocks muscular nAChR alpha-1/gamma subunits.

name: Ponericin-L2
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria. Has non-hemolytic activity.

name: Ponericin-W1
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Ponericin-G7
description: Has activity against Gram-positive bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has non-hemolytic activity.

name: Ponericin-L1
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria. Has non-hemolytic activity.

name: Ponericin-W4
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Ponericin-W5
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Ponericin-W2
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Ponericin-W3
description: Broad spectrum of activity against both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria and S.cerevisiae. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Ponericin-W6
description: Activity against Gram-positive bacteria. Has insecticidal and hemolytic activities.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 PC1
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 23.3
description: This toxin shows both immunosuppressive and anti-inflammatory activities (PubMed:28077339). It has the potential to inhibit human T cell activation, since it reduces IL-2 secretion and the expression of T cell activation marker CD69 and acts as a antiinflammatory agent, since it provokes the reduction of secretion of both IFN-gamma and TNF-alpha (PubMed:28077339). In vivo, the delayed-type hypersensitivity response in rat autoimmune disease model is ameliorated in the presence of this toxin (PubMed:28077339). Acts by blocking Kv1.3/KCNA3 potassium channels of T-lymphocytes (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein bucarin
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein asurin-2
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein asurin-1
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein ascarin
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Snaclec echicetin subunit beta
description: Echicetin itself inhibits aggregation of washed platelets induced by vWF, thrombin or alboaggregin-A (PubMed:8481512, PubMed:11290595). However, when complexed with the pentameric plasma immunoglobulin Mkappa (IgMkappa), echicetin binds specifically to GPIb and activates platelets. This is caused by P-selectin expression and activation of alpha-IIb/beta-3 as well as tyrosine phosphorylation of several signal transduction molecules, including p53/56(LYN), p64, p72(SYK), p70 to p90, and p120 (PubMed:11290595). In vivo, it induces thrombocytopenia when injected into mice (PubMed:8481512), probably accounting of activation of platelets rather than inhibition (PubMed:11290595).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein tripurin
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Cysteine-rich venom protein tropirin
description: Blocks contraction of smooth muscle elicited by high potassium-induced depolarization, but does not block caffeine-stimulated contraction. May target voltage-gated calcium channels on smooth muscle (By similarity).

name: Acidic phospholipase A2 VP7
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that is not toxic by itself, but the synergistical mixture of a basic and this acidic protein is lethal. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides (By similarity).

name: Phospholipase A1 1
description: Hydrolysis of phosphatidylcholine with phospholipase A1 (EC 3.1.1.32) activity. Has weak hemolytic activity (By similarity). Shows a phospholipase A1 enzymatic activity of 3.6 U/ml.

name: Mu-conotoxin TsIIIA
description: Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). This toxin specifically inhibits TTX-resistant sodium currents (IC(50)=2.61 uM) but has no effect on TTX-sensitive sodium currents. In vivo, mice hotplate analgesic assay indicates that this toxin obviously increases the pain threshold at 0.5-4 hours. In addition, TsIIIA has better analgesic effects than Ziconotide.

name: Alpha-conotoxin CnIA
description: Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus inhibit them (PubMed:10320362, PubMed:28238803). CnIA and CnIB block muscular nAChR alpha-1/gamma and alpha-1/delta subunits (PubMed:10320362).

name: Scorpine
description: Has antibacterial activity against B.subtilis and K.pneumoniae and a potent inhibitory effect on the ookinete (ED(50) 0.7 uM) and gamete (ED(50) 10 uM) stages of Plasmodium berghei development.

name: Snaclec stejaggregin-B subunit beta-2
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec stejaggregin-B subunit beta-1
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec stejaggregin-B subunit alpha
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec stejaggregin-A subunit beta-1
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Snaclec stejaggregin-A subunit alpha
description: Interferes with one step of hemostasis (modulation of platelet aggregation, or coagulation cascade, for example).

name: Putative Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor
description: Serine protease inhibitor.

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxMKLT1-0223
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxMKLT1-031
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TeAr94
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels.

name: Omega-segestritoxin-Sf1a
description: Potent and selective blocker of N-type voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav2.2/CACNA1B). Also blocks vertebrate Cav2.1/CACNA1A (P/Q-type) and Cav1.2/CACNA1C (L-type) channels at very high concentration (2 micromolar).

name: U1-ctenitoxin-Cs1a
description: Blocks mammalian neuronal L-type (Cav1/CACNA1) of high-voltage-activated calcium channels (By similarity). Causes paralysis in Drosophila. Its insecticidal activity is synergistically increased by potassium ions, M-ctenitoxin-Cs1a (AC P83619), omega-ctenitoxin-Cs1a (AC P81694), and U1-ctenitoxin-Cs2a (AC P83919).

name: Omega-conotoxin-like TxMKLT1-0211
description: Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav).

name: Turripeptide Ici9.1
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel (By similarity). May also act as a serine protease inhibitor, since it possess the kazal serine protease inhibitor signature.

name: Turripeptide OL11-like
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel (By similarity). May also act as a serine protease inhibitor, since it possess the kazal serine protease inhibitor signature.

name: Turripeptide OL71
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Turripeptide Lol9.1
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel (By similarity). May also act as a serine protease inhibitor, since it possess the kazal serine protease inhibitor signature.

name: Turripeptide Lol6.2
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Turripeptide OL184
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Turripeptide OL179
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Turripeptide Lol6.1
description: Acts as a neurotoxin by inhibiting a ion channel.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog T1-2 B chain
description: Neurotoxin T1-2 is a presynaptic neurotoxin of the venom that exhibits indirect hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. The B chain is homologous to venom basic protease inhibitors but has no protease inhibitor activity and is non-toxic.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 T1-2 A chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini and exhibits indirect hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog T1-1 B chain
description: Neurotoxin T1-1 is a presynaptic neurotoxin of the venom that exhibits indirect hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. The B chain is homologous to venom basic protease inhibitors but has no protease inhibitor activity and is non-toxic.

name: Kunitz-type serine protease inhibitor homolog T2 B chain
description: Neurotoxin T2 is a presynaptic neurotoxin of the venom that exhibits indirect hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. The B chain is homologous to venom basic protease inhibitors but has no protease inhibitor activity and is non-toxic.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 T2 A chain
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that inhibits neuromuscular transmission by blocking acetylcholine release from the nerve termini and exhibits indirect hemolytic activity against human erythrocytes. PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Delta-ctenitoxin-Pn2a
description: Irreversible inhibitor of voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Binds voltage-dependently to sodium channels and inhibits the inactivation of the activated channels. Also shifts the voltage dependence of the sodium conductance to negative potentials and decrease the peak inward current. Causes scratching, lacrimation, hypersalivation, sweating and agitation followed by spastic paralysis of the anterior and posterior extremities and death at dose levels of 0.79 mg/mouse. Is insecticidal to the larval and adult forms of the house fly. Enhances rat erectile function by increasing NO release in the cavernosum tissue.

name: U5-ctenitoxin-Pn1a
description: Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav). Causes tail erection, scratching and a reduction in mobility at a dose level of 1.40 mg/mouse.

name: U2-ctenitoxin-Pn1a
description: Inhibits voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav) (By similarity). Causes scratching, lacrimation, hypersalivation, sweating and agitation followed by spastic paralysis of the anterior and posterior extremities and death at dose levels of 1.62 mg/mouse. Insecticidal to the larval and adult forms of the house fly.

name: Con-Ins Q1
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Con-Ins Q1b
description: This venom insulin facilitates prey capture by rapidly inducing hypoglycemic shock. Intraperitoneal injection of this peptide into zebrafish lowers blood glucose with the same potency than human insulin. In vivo, when applied to water, this peptide reduces overall locomotor activity of zebrafish larvae, observed as a significant decrease in the percentage of time spent swimming and movement frequency.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme 1
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease.

name: Thrombin-like enzyme 2
description: Thrombin-like snake venom serine protease.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 F17
description: Snake venom phospholipase A2 (PLA2) that has anticoagulant activity and inhibits bactericial growth of the Gram-negative bacteria Xanthomonas axonopodis pv. passiflorae (in monomeric form). PLA2 catalyzes the calcium-dependent hydrolysis of the 2-acyl groups in 3-sn-phosphoglycerides.

name: Basic phospholipase A2 F16
